</MAP>





	

















	
	

	<img border=0 align=center src="/Banners/Portal/advertisement.gif" alt="advertisement"></a><br>

	
	

	<a href="/cgi-bin/redirect.cgi?location=http://www.software.ibm.com/info/eye13%3fportal.ad3">









<img width=100 height=115 border=2 align=center src="/Banners/Portal/Business/ibm.bus-112196.ptl.banner.gif?" alt="IBM"></a><br><p>



 


        </td>

        <td width=5 rowspan=1>
        </td>
        



        
       <td valign=top width=305>


       <font size=+2 face="Arial", "Helvetica"><STRONG>IBM to source in Taiwan</STRONG></font>

        <br>

        
<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">
        By <a href="mailto:letters@news.com">
			 Reuters</a><BR>

        
	
	
	
		December 13, 1996, 10:45 a.m. PT
		</font>


    <p>

    <font  face="Times">





<a href="http://www.ibm.com/">IBM</a> <a href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=ibm">(IBM)</a> today says it will buy up to $1.73 billion worth of notebook and desktop computers in 1997 from Taiwan equipment makers.<p>

Under a recent letter of intent, IBM agreed to procure notebook and desktop computers worth up to $864 million in 1996 from Taiwan makers and nearly twice that in 1997, IBM Taiwan purchasing manager Danny Dang said.<p>

"Our PC-related sourcing from Taiwan in 1996 will rise 70 to 80 percent from the 1995 level of $480 million," Dang said. "The 1997 sourcing will be almost double the 1996 level." <p>

He said <a href="http://www.acer.com/">Acer</a> would be the lead supplier under the pact in the second year but would not say at what level. Dang declined to give more specific figures or list the other Taiwan makers IBM will tap with its purchase plans for both years.<p>

Acer executives declined to comment on Dang's disclosure.<p>

Dang said the U.S. computer giant did not hesitate to source its computer line in Taiwan and said Acer in particular offered excellent logistical support. <p>

"The reason is simple: Taiwan's computer products are cheap and good," he said.<p>

He noted that IBM was not the biggest buyer of Taiwan computer products, saying it ranked behind <a href="http://www.compaq.com/">Compaq Computer</a>.<p>


<P><font size=-1><A HREF="/copyright_reuters.html">Story Copyright</A> &#169; 1996 <A HREF="http://www.reuters.com/">Reuters Limited</A>. All rights reserved.</font>

</font>

        </td>

