       <td valign=top width=305>


       <font size=+2 face="Arial", "Helvetica"><STRONG>Corel handheld on hold</STRONG></font>

        <br>

        
<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">
        By <a href="mailto:letters@news.com">
			 Reuters</a><BR>

        
	
	
	
		December 3, 1996, 12 p.m. PT
		</font>


    <p>

    <font  face="Times">





<a href="http://www.corel.com/">Corel</a> <a href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=COSFF">(COSFF)</a> is delaying plans to develop a handheld PC in favor of concentrating on its new network computer, the company said today.
<p>
Corel, Canada's largest software company, had been planning
to ship 1 million of the tiny computers by mid-1997, marking
a major foray into the hardware business.
<p>
But spokeswoman Carrie Bendzsa said the company now wants to see how the market develops before deciding whether to proceed with the handheld unit, which was to be powered by the new Java software programming language. <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a>, Corel's rival in the software market, recently unveiled Windows CE, an operating system for handheld computers and an alternative to Java.
<p>
Bendzsa said the company will continue developing the Corel
Video NC, however. Corel expected to have a prototype ready early in the new year, she added.

<p><font size=-1><a href="/copyright_reuters.html">Copyright</A> &#169;
1996 <A HREF="http://www.reuters.com">Reuters Limited</a>.  All rights
reserved.</font></font>

        </td>

