        </td>
        



        
       <td valign=top width=305>


       <font size=+2 face="Arial", "Helvetica"><STRONG>Layoffs mar The Spot</STRONG></font>

        <br>

        
<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">
        By <a href="mailto:letters@news.com">
			 Reuters-Variety</a><BR>

        
	
	
	
		November 22, 1996, 4:45 p.m. PT
		</font>


    <p>

    <font  face="Times">





<a href="http://www.americancybercast.com/">American
Cybercast</a>, the company that put Web soaps on the map with its Internet series <a href="http://www.thespot.com/">The Spot</a>, is laying off a dozen staffers and is relaunching one of its daily shows, <a
href="http://www.thepyramid.com/">The Pyramid</a>, as a weekly, <i>Variety</i> reports.<p> 

The company, which is typically known as AMCY, had grown rapidly in recent months, expanding its offerings by adding <a href="http://www.eon4.com/">Eon-4</a> and <a href="http://www.qfix.com/">Quick Fix Theater</a>, as well as The Pyramid. Before the cuts, the full-time staff had numbered 56.<p> 

The highest-ranking staff member to be let go was Creative Director Scott Ford. Jobs were eliminated throughout the company, in creative areas, as well as operational ones.<p>

AMCY President Sheri Herman acknowledged that the company may have grown too fast for its own good. "We jumped ahead of our plan. We started in January, and there was a very hot IPO market at the time. The general wisdom was that you start up a company and grow as quickly as you can," she said. <p>

Creative Artists Agency was an initial investor in the company. <a href="http://www.tci.com/">TCI</a>, <a href="http://www.intel.com/">Intel</a>, Allen & Company, and <a href="http://www.softbank.co.jp/">Softbank</a> are also investors. <p>

Earlier this month, Scott Siegler, former TV president of Columbia Pictures, was named president of entertainment at AMCY. Herman said the decision to lay off staffers was made before Siegler signed on. <p>

"This is not a company going through financial difficulties," Herman emphasized, adding that the number of series the Web channel plans to carry--15 by the end of 2000--remains unchanged. <p>

But industry sources said AMCY was in some ways victimized by its own success. As one of the hottest companies in a sizzling industry--one that's yet to truly prove itself fiscally--AMCY expanded too fast, rather than focusing on its initial hit, The Spot. <p>

"American Cybercast was built on The Spot. Unfortunately, when that became extremely popular, instead of putting more money into it, making sure it was solid, they spent more money on other things. They recruited a lot of really talented people, but they also became heavy in upper management," a source said.<p>

<P><font size=-1><a href="/copyright_reuters.html">Copyright</A> &#169;
1996 <A HREF="http://www.reuters.com">Reuters Limited</a>.  All rights
reserved.</font> 
</font>

        </td>

<td width=5 rowspan=1>
</td>



     


