<p>

<p>
<p>
<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_29_96/">March 29, 1996-- This week, on episode 53 of </i>CNET Central</i>...</a>
<br>
Online ads that target kids come under fire...New Senate bill would expand, protect encryption...Alternative culture gets cataloged online...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_28_96/">March 28, 1996-- If you're tired of dealing with separate companies for your phone, long distance, cable and net access, just hang on...</a>
<br>
Capitol Hill reckons with online news reporters...Junk e-mailer sues AOL...Red Cross goes heavily online...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_27_96/">March 27, 1996-- The MTV Choose or Lose
bus is on the road, and its making both roadside and Netside appearances...</a>
<br>
Apple braces to take a huge hit in Q2...AMD rolls out its Pentium clone--finally...Protection against non-existent Java viruses...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_26_96/">March 26, 1996-- There's a flurry of activity around VRML and 3-D via the Web...but most of it seems like kid's stuff...</a>
<br>
Java has a leak...MSN hits a million, stays on Web course...Netcom polishes up the front office...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_25_96/">March 25, 1996-- If the middle class has discovered anything in the 90's, its investing and the Net...</a>
<br>
Intuit wants to hawk financial info...H-P pulls back a bit from PostScript...FireWire picks up steam...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_22_96/">March 22, 1996-- A preview of episode #52 of <i>CNET Central</i>...</a>
<br>
Netizens v. Decency, Round Two...SAT exam to move from pencil to keyboard?...Intel wants to be everybody's ally in cable modems...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_21_96/">March 21, 1996-- Its a sign of the times that old computers are starting to show up on the same American terrain that used to be strewn primarily with old tires and shopping carts...</a>
<br>
Netizens v. Decency, Round One...RAM makers move to end the glut..."California's Most Wanted" may go online...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_20_96/">March 20, 1996-- Tonight, on the eve of the Computer Decency Amendment's first courtroom test...</a>
<br>
Software industry lobbies for a little respect...Laptop sales healthiest of slowing market...CDA trial tomorrow, Encarta gets it online tonight...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_19_96/">March 19, 1996-- An activist umbrella group was outraged to learn recently that it was included in a Pentagon report...</a>
<br>
The big boys go Mac cloning...New Apple internet chief...Web site shows teachers what to do with the Net...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_18_96/">March 18, 1996-- Web access hasn't quite made it to the Formica counters at McDonald's yet...</a>
<br>
MCI steals some AT&T thunder...Microsoft moves to wrest banking crown from Intuit...Motorola will be your ISDN ambassador...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_15_96/">March 15, 1996-- This week on, episode #51...</a>
<br>
FTC goes after online fraud...Amendment to CDA encourages parental control...Microsoft rather hush about latest alliance...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_14_96/">March 14, 1996-- It seems that the First Amendment only makes headlines when someone uses it in court to defend their misdemeanors...</a>
<br>
AT&T throws the switch...USWeb franchises Web site authoring...Macromedia gets Backstage access...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_13_96/">March 13, 1996-- Bill Gates addressed thousands of developers from the Windows world at the Professional Developers Conference in San Francisco...</a>
<br>
Gates, Case evangelize the coming dynamic Web...CompuServe launches WOW!...First Union bank pioneers digital investor relations

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_12_96/">March 12, 1996-- Maritz describes how Microsoft sees the Web's next plateau...</a>
<br>
Microsoft rolls out platform for "living" web pages...AOL goes with Navigator yesterday, Explorer today...Project OPEN to make a
kinder, gentler Net

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_11_96/">March 11, 1996-- Hear how the the Net-a-Thon and Penny-A-Processor will play a role in connecting our schools...</a>
<br>
Microsoft sees a future in ISDN...AOL cuts deals with AT&T and Netscape...DirectTV to plug into your PC

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_9_96/">March 8, 1996-- Listen to what's coming on this week's episode of CNET Central:...</a>
<br>
CompuServe brings Navigator aboard...and gets into Net telephony...Internet Phone connects to ordinary phones...
<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_7_96/">March 7, 1996-- Most people don't exactly know their way around a motherboard...</a>
<br>
AT&T hooking up with an online service?...The RAM "fire sale" of '96...Shockwave goes streaming...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_6_96/">March 6, 1996-- Forget about schools that integrate computers in the classroom...</a>
<br>
Legislators seek to excise an 1873 law from the CDA...Long distance resellers outraged over "web phones"...Corel oils up to wrestle Microsoft Office...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_5_96/">March 5, 1996-- Forget about schools that integrate computers in the classroom...</a>
<br>
Encryption Bill launched...Netscape cleans its server house...Virus assessment on "Michaelangelo Eve"...

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_4_96/">March 4, 1996-- We hear all kinds of wildly varying figures about Net usership...But a more fundamental number--computer usership--is much easier to get a handle on...</a>
<br>
Apple announces demise of e-world...New crypto bill seeks more ironclad privacy...120 MB floppy hits the scene

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/March_96/3_1_96/">March 1, 1996-- Starting this week, each Friday we'll give you an early glimpse of what's coming on this week's episode of <i>CNET Central</i>...</a>
<br>
Pentium Pro slowed by its own chipset...Some concerns over WorldNet dial-up...Ultra-high bandwidth breakthrough

