<p>
<p>
<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_29_96/">February 29, 1996 -- Hear how an entreprenurial student found that in these higher-stakes days of the Web, domain naming can be a dicey business.</a>
<br>
Telco's say loophole gives onlines a free local ride...Apple, Microsoft launch competing 3-D specs...Massive sting operation reveals hot grey market for silicon

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_28_96/">February 28, 1996 -- All we seem to hear about these days is how much profit will be mined from the Net...But even in the world of non-profits, there's also gold in them silicon hills.</a>
<br>
Student punished for email "bombing"..White House expects email flood tomorrow...Hottest laptops ever bow Monday

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_27_96/">February 27, 1996 -- Larry Ellison's vision of the "$500 Network Computer", or NC, was formally introduced at the Oracle Developer's Conference in San Francisco Monday.</a>
<br>
AT&T becomes big fish in the ISP pond..Oracle's Ellison preaches from the NC pulpit...Does business not "get" the Web?

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_26_96/">February 26, 1996 -- Few things are imbued with as much weighty tradition as applying to college...</a>
<br>
Second major suit filed against CDA..SGI buys most of Cray...Sun, Motorola work toward high-speed home connections

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_23_96/">February 23, 1996 -- CNET radio's Brian Cooley spoke with CompuServe member Richard Eastman of Billerica, Massachusetts.</a>
<br>
Navigator security hole called minor..Netscape founders cash in a few shares...24 Hours of Democracy draws literary response

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_22_96/">February 22, 1996 -- More than a few people are under the pressure of corporate America's "right-sizing" of the 90's...</a>
<br>
Corporate cyberspace to join "Free Net" suit...Intel's new CPU is multimedia to the core...Netscape squeezes under Microsoft's server limbo bar

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_21_96/">February 21, 1996 -- The CNET user calls don't stop when it comes to the new Net Decency law...Outrage, disappointment and irony are some of the responses.</a>
<br>
Pre-trial standoff on net decency...Sears will bail out of Prodigy...New online look of photofinishing

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_20_96/">February 20, 1996 -- Between all the din over ISDN and cable modems, you may not have heard of an alternative called ADSL...</a>
<br>
CompuServe will be spun off from parent...Microsoft to reorganize headquarters...Bill Gates says he has nothing against "secretaries"

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_19_96/">February 19, 1996 -- Hear from the folks at U.S. Robotics how the new breed of modems "share."</a>
<br>
Motorola licenses the Mac OS...Kasparov beats Deep Blue...New anti-virus for email borne infections

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_16_96/">February 16, 1996 -- As we finish the week's look at the ways of shareware, we meet "Dr. File Finder", aka Mike Callahan, who looks back at shareware's nascence in 1982.</a>
<br>
Partial victory for Free Net advocates...How many of us are out there?...CU-SeeMe gets shrinkwrapped

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_15_96/">February 15, 1996 -- Hear from ASP chairman George Campbell about the place of shareware in a competitive software world.</a>
<br>
Justice responds to Telecom challenge...Intuit tax bugs become an annual affair...Intel sued for fashion design theft

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_14_96/">February 14, 1996 -- Fifty years ago, the computer was born.</a>
<br>
Usenet post starts investigation...Former MIPS head goes Pentium...The computer turns 50

<p>
<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_13_96/">February 13, 1996 -- behind shareware part II: Ziga Turk's "virtual shareware library"</a>
<br>
CompuServe frees up most Usenet groups... Apple lends its name to toy line... News via screensaver

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_12_96/">February 12, 1996 -- behind shareware part I: Nico Mak, the master of the archived file</a>
<br>
Moving Worlds becomes online 3D standard... "Computer Required" seen on more college applications... Surprised parent finds vile language on computer toy

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_9_96/">February 9, 1996 -- Justice agrees to cool it on decency--for now</a>
<br>
"Power Rangers" Web box... Intercasting gets some serious footing

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_8_96/">February 8, 1996 -- 24 Hours in Cyberspace underway</a>
<br>
Net "decency" becomes law...MCI, News Corp cool off their romance

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_7_96/">February 7, 1996 -- Hear about the "mother of all tech support nightmares"</a>
<br>
Web pages go black in protest...candyland.com case takes a twist..."Webdultery" case going to court

<p>

<a href="/Radio/Vault/Vaulted_96/February_96/2_6_96/">February 6, 1996 -- Orange County's businesses are using the Net to climb out of a hole</a>
<br>
