<td valign=top width="305" align=left>



<!----------- SECTION NAME ---->

<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/index_perspectives.gif"><br>


<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Upgraditis</strong>
</font>
<br>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>January 17, 1997</font><br>

<p>

<font face="Times">

"<a href="http://www.intel.com/">Intel</a> giveth and <a
href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> taketh away." This formula
has served each side
well. In fact it has worked so well that it has created the industry's most
feared
duopoly: "Wintel." <P>

This is how it works: Approximately every 18 months, Intel, in keeping with
Moore's
Law, creates a market for faster chips, bigger hard drives, increased
memory. And Microsoft comes along and ships "bloatware" that uses it all
up--well most of it, anyway. <p>

<img height=82 width=138 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_giveth.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>
The end result is "upgraditis," the biannual ritual that drives
users--voluntarily or otherwise--to throw away their old wares and get
new stuff. Who wins? Compare the earnings reports of Microsoft-Intel and
the expense reports (new wares plus maintenance costs) of corporations and
you'll get the idea. <p>
 
This week's launch of <a
href="http://www.news.com/News/Item/0,4,7061,00.html">Office 97</a> is the
latest case in point.  It is here.
And as far as Microsoft is concerned users had better  prepare to adopt it.
Resistance will be futile. <p> 


Office will run on 486 PCs, so says Microsoft, but you will need Windows 95
or Windows NT, because it wont run on the older version of Windows. And
Microsoft just didn't decide on this on its own. It checked in with
customers. Honest.<p>

<img height=104 width=161 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_centerpiece.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
"Our investment in understanding the needs of customers and our continued
ability to deliver exciting enhancements are the cornerstone of Office's
ongoing success," said <a
href="http://www.news.com/Newsmakers/Gates/gates.html">Bill Gates</a> at
the launch event. "Customers will be
very pleased with the Internet integration, the new collaboration
capabilities of Outlook 97, and the IntelliSense technology featured in the
Office Assistant." <p>

What is not clear is if this "understanding" of the customers' needs
applied to the millions of Windows 3.1 users (some two-thirds of corporate PCs
still run on Win 3.1). If these users want to tap into the "exciting
enhancements" they have no choice but to upgrade. And not just to Office
97, but also to Windows 95 or NT. Now you understand why Microsoft is such a
brilliant marketer. <p>



</font>
<P>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives_cont.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>
</td>
<td width=3>

</td>

