<td align=left width=155>

<span class="shorttakes">

<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">

<strong><a href="/Perspectives/Soapbox/nn1_3_97a.html">Government and the
Internet</strong></a>
<br>
Give me Bill Gates, his pretzel logic, and never-stop-swimming shark-like
business acumen to <i>any</i> government program any day, any time. Mr.
Newman proposes stronger Internet regulation by the same government that is
still fighting tooth and nail to preserve what it feels is its "right" to
monitor our digital transmissions.
<br>
The Internet has become commercially viable and <i>no</i> government
intervention is required.
&nbsp; --<a href="mailto:yusuf@infomagic.com"> Yusuf Faruq'Abd-al-Hakim </a>

<br>
&nbsp;
<br>

<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc12_30_96a.html"><strong>1997
Predictions</strong></a>
<br>
You didn't mention anything about high bandwidth. Will cable modems catch
on or will ASDL or XSDL technologies or 56-kbps modems be the winners?
Personally, I feel 56-kbps will dominate and ISDN will go the way of
5.25-inch floppies. I hope cable modems will also make an impact.
&nbsp;--<a href="mailto:alwatson@netime.com">A. L. Watson</a>
<br>
