<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>We're not in Kansas anymore, Toto</strong>
</font>
<br>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>January 15, 1997</font><br>

<p>
<font face="Times">
<p>
The loose network of people who make policy for the Internet are in the
hot seat these days.
<p>
As the impact of Internet policy widens, the group of researchers, engineers,
and volunteer committees that used to cipher Internet protocols in peace
and obscurity are facing the kind of scrutiny and criticism usually
reserved for national politicians.
<p>
<img height=188 width=153 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_reasonable.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>
Last year, a proposal to expand commercial Internet names beyond ".com"
brought a rain of angry criticism that set the plan back by months. And
just this week another controversy erupted over a plan to charge fees
for Internet Protocol addresses, the network numbers behind domain
names.
<p>
That may not seem like much to newcomers who see
the Internet's intellectual underpinnings as public property, but the
people who have labored on the Internet in obscurity (and often for free)
are bewildered and not a little defensive at the proliferation of outsiders
in their once-cozy town hall meetings.
<p>
<img height=135 width=131 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_practical.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
It's times like these that Don Mitchell longs for the Internet he used to
know: "The governing principles for the Internet are that reasonable people
discuss options and then come to a consensus," said the National Science
Foundation official responsible for administering a grant that today
subsidizes Internet address registration. "Unfortunately, a couple of years
ago when the Internet took off, that ethic was lost."
<p>



</font>
<P>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw1_15_97b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>
</td>
<td width=3>

</td>

