<td valign=top width="305" align=left>



<!----------- SECTION NAME ---->

<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">
<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif">
</a>

<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Software and info services led way for 1996 venture-backed IPOs</strong>
</font>
<br>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>January 14, 1997</font><br>

<p>
<font face="Times">
<p>
It was another killer year for venture-backed software and information services 
companies that completed an IPO in 1996. These companies accounted for more than 
23 percent of all initial public offerings by venture-backed tech firms.
<p>

And what a year it was for venture-funded companies as a whole. A record 260 
venture-backed firms raised $11.8 billion in the IPO market. This astounding 
number shatters the previous record of $8.4 billion raised by 203 initial issues 
in 1995.
<p>
<img height=135 width=150 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_outpaced.gif" hspace=0 vspace=0 align=left>
Technology issues significantly outpaced health care and nontechnology IPOs, 
accounting for roughly half the deals and dollars raised in 1996.
<p>

As I said before, software and information services companies led all other 
industries with over 60 transactions totaling $2.3 billion. Client-server 
technology drove most of the deals in 1994 and 1995. But last year, the  Internet 
was the common base among software companies. <a href="http://www.yahoo.com/">
Yahoo</a> <a href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=YHOO">(YHOO)</a>, 
<a href="http://www.infoseek.com/">Infoseek</a> <a href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=SEEK">(SEEK)</a>, 
<a href="http://www.excite.com/">Excite</a> <a href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=XCIT">(XCIT)</a>, 
and <a href="http://www.lycos.com/">Lycos</a> <a href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=LCOS">(LCOS)</a> are 
but a few of the Internet companies to go public within the first half of the year.
<p>
<img height=115 width=162 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_dramatic.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
Valuations for these venture-backed software firms also saw a dramatic rise. The 
average IPO deal carried a preoffering value of about $123 million, up 20 percent 
from 1995's figures. (The preoffering valuation is the total number of shares 
outstanding prior to the offering multiplied by the price per share at IPO.)
<p>




</font>
<P>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/Marketwise/rs1_14_97b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>
</td>
<td width=3>

</td>

<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->
