<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Enough talk</strong>
</font>
<br>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>January 13, 1997</font><br>

<p>
<font face="Times">
<p>

Maybe that's why they don't let you talk at your own funeral. <p>

Watching <a href="http://www.apple.com/">Apple Computer</a> 
<a href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=AAPL">
(AAPL)</a> chairman <a href="/Newsmakers/Amelio/amelio.html">Gil Amelio</a> 
meander through two and a half hours at a <a href="http://www.macworld.com/expo/">
Macworld</a> keynote last week was for me a painful experience. <p>

Amelio's presentation apparently played well with the Macintosh faithful, as 
NEWS.COM's Alex Lash <a href="/SpecialFeatures/0,5,6882,00.html">reported last 
week</a>. But a dwindling core of loyalists is not Apple's only constituency, 
and Amelio's stumbling performance hurt Apple's cause. 
<p>
<img height=71 width=132 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_keynotes.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>
Apple had billed Macworld as its forum for outlining its operating system 
strategy, particularly the tough transition from Apple's homegrown OS to the 
one it just bought from Steve Jobs's <a href="http://www.next.com/">
Next Software</a>, which it must now port to run on the Mac. But last week, an 
avuncular Amelio first downplayed the importance of an operating system and then 
asked the world to trust Apple to handle the switch-over as well as it did the 
transition to the PowerPC chips. <p>

It was left to Ellen Hancock, Apple's chief technology officer, to provide the 
clearest information about Apple's intentions, which she did in two sessions 
limited to press and analysts. A colleague who sat through it all suggested 
Hancock should run the company, not Amelio. She surely should give the keynotes. 
<p>
<img height=163 width=122 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_ali.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
<a href="http://www.dataquest.com/">Dataquest</a> analyst Chris Le Tocq graded 
Apple's presentation "A" for technology and "D" for message. Without Steve Jobs, 
it would have been an "F" in my book. 
<p>

This not-so-riveting performance turned toward the pathetic when Amelio ran down 
the lists of celebrities in attendance. The on-stage appearance of the two Steves 
(Apple cofounders Jobs and Wozniak) was obligatory, and Jobs was the high point 
of the day. 
<p>

</font>


<P>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc1_13_97b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>
</td>
