<tr>


<td valign=top width=310>


<!-- -----MAIN CONTENT-- -->

<font face="Arial" size=+1><strong>How private business almost derailed the
Internet</strong></font>

<br> <font face="Arial" size=-1>(continued)</font>
<p>

<font face="Times">

<p>
In the early sixties, researcher Paul Baran had begun 
planning the technology necessary to 
network computers. Baran worked at <a href="http://www.rand.org/">Rand</a>, a 
research company set up to monitor and preserve the U.S. 
government operations' research capability.  Worried about the 
survivability of U.S. communication networks in the case of nuclear 
war, Baran envisioned the movement from analog telephone signals 
to digital signals that could perform in a networked system of 
digital transmission.
<p>
     Rand was enthusiastic about Baran's ideas but when <a
href="http://www.att.com/">AT&T</a> was 
approached about its feasibility, AT&T executives dismissed the 
idea and even refused to share information on their long distance 
<img height=187 width=159 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_flexible.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>
circuit maps. Baran had to purloin a copy to evaluate his ideas 
which he and Rand were convinced were right. The Air Force directly asked
AT&T to build such a network but AT&T still refused. The company work (except 
for a faction of scientists at Bell Labs) said it wouldn't work. 
<p>
This may have been 
technical myopia by the business-oriented executives, but it was 
an economically self-interested myopia.  Such a distributed 
network threatened (and today does threaten) the central economic 
assets of the telephone industry: central computers and central 
switches. It highlights the fact that corporate research labs, 
the main alternative to long-term government funding of 
technological alternatives, rarely if ever invest in fundamental 
technology that will likely undermine the natural economic 
monopolies they currently enjoy.
<p>
This technological shortsightedness and economic self-interest was repeated
throughout the 1960s.  
British physicist Donald Davies, who had begun 
promoting the idea of a computer network with "packets" of 
information, was supported only by the British Post Office, 
notably a state-run agency which maintained the British telephone system.
In 1968, the first computer distributed network was 
established on computers located at the National Physical 
Laboratory where Davies worked. 
<p>
     Only at the U.S. military's <a href="http://ftp.arpa.mil/">Advanced
Research Projects 
Agency</a> (ARPA) would distributed computing would be taken to the 
next level. Although in 1968, ARPA advertised the bid for building the 
specialized computers  to be used to run the network.  <a
href="http://www.ibm.com/">IBM</a> and 
other big computer companies declined to make a bid, saying 
it wasn't possible at a reasonable price.  
<p>
     Throughout the 1970s and 1980s, ARPA would build a national 
community of public-minded experts who helped shepherd open 
Internet standards that would radically expand the network to a 
wide range of users.  In doing so, it was clear that the public-
spirited professional norms promoted by ARPA and the community of 
researchers was critical in keeping individual profit-taking from 
undermining that openness. In one case, the ARPA threatened the federal
contracts of BBNthe 600 employee consulting firm that helped put initial
nodes online--to force the contractor to release its routing code publicly.
<p>
And as networks spread in the 1980s, it was the 
government experts at ARPA and universities who backed the 
flexible, tested TCP/IP protocol, while big private companies 
like <a href="http://www.mci.com/">MCI</a>, IBM and <a
href="http://www.hp.com/">Hewlett-Packard</a> adopted an untested, 
bureaucratically inspired standard created in international 
committees called Open Standards Interface (OSI). 
<p><img height=121 width=139 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_threatens.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>

The reality is that the Internet is 
no accident but neither was it a technological inevitability.  It 
was the product of a U.S. federal government, in association with 
other nation's experts, who guided its evolution, demanded that 
its standards be open and in the public domain, and maintained that its 
reach be extended broadly enough to overwhelm the proprietary 
corporate competitors.
<p>
     It is under such an open system that small companies can 
create Internet-related software products and know that they will 
be compatible with other products given the pervasiveness of the 
standards.  The fate of the companies that were building 
<a href=http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft's</a> proprietary
network--dropped by Microsoft and left 
with a useless set of products when Microsoft switched to 
Internet standards--shows the shadow life of companies that 
depend on the whims of corporate standards.   The open standards 
of the Internet and the easy distribution of products assures 
that new companies have the ability to take 
on established players without having the technology itself used 
as a block against them.
<p>
The privatization of the Internet threatens further 
evolution of the Internet. This extends from the coordination of 
networking to avoid capacity overload, to the danger that 
standards and protocol design are being shaped increasingly to 
commercial needs.  While the overall compatibility of systems 
through the IP protocol is unlikely to be undermined in the near 
term, related standards such as Web browsers are being 
increasingly designed with commercial interests in mind.   
<p>
What is worth emphasizing is that the federal government did 
a very good job for 25 years in designing and guiding 
the standards and development of the Internet. Putting some 
regulatory teeth back into government standards committees is an 
infinitely preferable alternative to letting Microsoft or 
Netscape's corporate strategies determine the standards with which the rest
of us 
have to live.


<p>


</font>
<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>

<p>
<a href="mailto:newman@garnet.berkeley.edu">Nathan Newman</a> is a partner
at Progressive Communications, a consultantcy that specializes  in helping
community organizations and governments use the Internet. He is writing a
book about how the Internet is changing the nature of regional  economies
and politics. Before starting Progressive Communications, he headed the
University of California at Berkeley's Center for Community Economic
Research. This Perspective is an edited excerpt of an article that
originally appeared in E-NODE, a free email publication distributed by his
company. To subscribe,
send email to enodelist@garnet.berkeley.edu. Type "subscribe e-node" in the
body.
<p>
Email your comments about this week's guest Perspective to opinions editor
<a href="mailto:margiew">Margie Wylie</a>. Your letter may be excerpted and
printed in a future Perspectives.



</font>
<p>

