<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">
<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif">
</a>

<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->

<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>What's news?</strong>

</font>

<br>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 27, 1996</font><br>

<p>

<font face="Times">

Since this is the time of the year when everyone in the media is pumping out

year-in-review stories, it's only fitting that we reviewed the

existence--albeit short--of NEWS.COM.

<p>

We launched NEWS.COM on September 4 with an ambitious goal: create a unique news operation built expressly for the Web. The editorial mission was to cover breaking technology news taking advantage of the new medium's audio, video, and interactive capabilities, not as an end to themselves, but where they could clarify, deepen, or broaden our coverage.

<p>

<img height=113 width=152 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_detached.gif" hspace=0 vspace=0 align=left>

One of the first letters to the editor read: "Don't blow your

techno-weenie credentials on your first day," in reference to our news

story on ATM. This well-meaning critic's

concern was whether our reporter even understood the term. (We can vouch

for the fact that the reporter was not writing about a cash dispenser.)

<p>

I suspect the underlying issue for this reader was whether a news operation conceived, created, and designed just for

the Internet could be credible, especially one that had no publishing history

and one where the "publishers" (the owners/founders) didn't hail from or

have any affiliations to the

established media companies.

<p>


That being the case, we mulled the following issues at length: Are we going

to be held to different set of rules and standards than our colleagues in

the "traditional" media?  Will <I>their</I> online versions fall under the same intensity of scrutiny? Are we

going to be considered apologists because we not only write

and report on the Internet, but because our very existence depends on the Web's

success? Are we going to be seen as cheerleaders for the Web instead of

detached observers and reporters? 

<P>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>

<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_27_96b.html">
<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>

</td>

<td width=3>
</td>

<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->

<td valign=top width=155>

<img border=0 height=200 width=155
src="/Graphics/per_singh_a.gif"><br>
<p>
<img border=0  height=16 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">
<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" 
width=155 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>

<tr>     

<td align=left width=155>

<span class="shorttakes">

<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">

<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_19_96a.html"><strong>WebTV</strong></a><br>
Dream on!  The PC is just a digital TV/VCR without a traditional tuner, and
with a lot of unnecessary expense mounted on the desktop instead of at the
cable company where it belongs. You go ahead and live in the past.  Keep your big clunky dinosaur PC! Disconnect from the network!  Keep your loyalty to companies who have <i>no</i>
loyalty to <i>you</i>.  But don't expect us to!  We'll be flying down the
Information Highway on our Kawasaki NetCruisers!  

&nbsp; --<a href="mailto: jamesefe@concentric.net"> James E. Felton </a>

<br> &nbsp; <br>

<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_18_96a.html"><strong>Pink software</strong></a><br>

Your article coincided with my viewing last night

of an episode of <I>The Simpsons</I> about Lisa's

disgust with Malibu Stacy.  She creates a

competitor doll, "Lisa Lionheart," which flops

commercially.  As Lisa says at

the end (observing the sole customer of Lisa

Lionheart), if they touched just one girl's life,

then it will have been enough.

&nbsp; --<a href="mailto:jknudsen@ix.netcom.com"> Jonathan Knudsen </a>

<br> &nbsp; <br>

<a href="/Perspectives/mw/dr12_17_96a.html"><strong>Internet reckoning </strong></a><br>
Mr. Rimer's analysis of the situation is correct on the timing, but he left out one factor: rapid gut-wrenching change. After two years, none of the companies mentioned in his article will be operating as they do today. Hold on to your hats!&nbsp; --<a href="mailto:hrr@fastlane.net">William A. Riggs, Jr., CPA</a>

<br> &nbsp; <br>

