<td valign=top width="305" align=left>















































<!----------- SECTION NAME ---->

<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">
<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif">
</a>






















<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->

<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Don't wait to be "pushed" off corporate desktops</strong>

</font>

<br>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 20, 1996</font><br>

<font face="Times">

<p>

A word to the wise: put a lid on flaunting the Web-as-TV to corporate America. <p>

A PC on every desktop has been the oft-stated goal of a certain billionaire--pre-Network Computer, of course. Putting a proverbial watercooler on every desktop probably was not what the billionaire had in mind. <p>

Everyone is trying to turn Internet-based computing into a television-like experience, replete with 5 million-plus channels. Unlike the doomed 500-channel dream of interactive TV, this trend certainly has the legs. And therein lies the problem. <p>

<img height=141 width=117 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_every.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>Employers have never sanctioned TVs in the workplace, let alone one on your desk; ditto for the chat sessions around the watercooler. The reason cited is loss of productivity. Whether it's real or perceived is another question. <p>

This being the employer mindset, would anyone care to guess their reaction to the Web turning into another TV-like medium? How are they going to react to their workers surfing dozens of Web channels? <p>

There have been quite a few stories during the past year about corporations restricting access to the Web. There have also been a few cases where Web surfers have lost their jobs because they were "caught" perusing nonproductive sites such as <i><a href="http://www.playboy.com/">Playboy</a>.</i> <p>

</font>



<P>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>

<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_20_96b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>

</td>

<td width=3>

</td>
























































































































































































































































































































































































































































































































































<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->































































































































































































































































































<td valign=top width=155>































































<img border=0 height=208 width=155















































src="/Graphics/per_singh_a.gif"><br>























<p>















































<img border=0  height=16 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">































<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" 



width=155 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>


<tr>     




<td align=left width=155>




<span class="shorttakes">





<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">



<!--a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_18_96a.html"--><strong>Pink software</strong><!--/a--><br>
Your article coincided with my viewing last night
of an episode of "The Simpsons" about Lisa's
disgust with Malibu Stacy.  She creates a
competitor doll, "Lisa Lionheart," which flops
commercially.  It's very insightful--it might
help you laugh about  <a href="http://www.mattelmedia.com/barbie/fashiondesigner/">Barbie Fashion Designer</a> .
Why do people buy this crap?  As Lisa says at
the end (observing the sole customer of Lisa
Lionheart), if they touched just one girl's life,
then it will have been enough.
&nbsp; --<a href="mailto:jknudsen@ix.netcom.com"> Jonathan Knudsen </a>
<br> &nbsp; <br>



<a href="/Perspectives/mw/dr12_17_96a.html"><strong>Internet reckoning </strong></a><br>

Mr. Rimer's analysis of the situation is correct on the timing, but he left out one factor, rapid gut-wrenching change. After two years, none of the companies mentioned in his article will be operating as they do today. Hold on to your hats!&nbsp; --<a href="mailto:hrr@fastlane.net">William A. Riggs, Jr., CPA</a>


<br> &nbsp; <br>

<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc12_16_96a.html"><strong>Trust</strong></a><br>
The simple reason that e-commerce hasn't worked to date is that it sucks.  If it
were totally trusted,
people still wouldn't do it because it's providing no real benefit, other than the fact that I can shop in my underwear. 
To get people to change behavior, you [have to] give them something that is not available in the real world. [Take], Amazon.com.  Trust doesn't seem to be
inhibiting them. They have provided something that doesn't exist:  a
1.2 million title bookstore with 3,000 sites pointing to the store.

&nbsp; --<a href="mailto:locke@vwco.com"> David Locke </a>



<br> &nbsp; <br>


<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_12_96a.html"><strong>PlanetStraight?</strong></a><br>
It has been really sad to watch PlanetOut turn into PlanetStraight. What promised to be cutting-edge,
opinionated, and original has gone the way of other vehicles like the <i>Advocate</i> and Harry Taylor's now insipid <i>Out</i> magazine. If the powers that be at
PlanetOut are afraid of offending anyone, they should go work for
America Online and leave PlanetOut to the people with brains and heart
who founded it.
&nbsp; --<a href="mailto:hoffmanj@dnai.com@msmedia.com">John Hoffman</a>

<br> &nbsp; <br>




