<tr>





<td valign=top width=310>





<!-- -----MAIN CONTENT-- -->

<font face="Arial" size=+1><strong>Dimly seen in 1997</strong></font>

<br> <font face="Arial" size=-1>(continued)</font>



<p>



<font face="Times">

<P>
<table border=0 width=310 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1>
<tr><td valign=top width=12><img src="/Graphics/b.gif"></td><td valign=top width=453>
Overseas governments will pay more attention to in the
Internet, not only to tax it, but also to regulate content, control their money supplies, and
boost homegrown firms over imports. U.S. groups that have focused on
Washington, D.C., will find themselves affected by foreign governmentsand
relying on the U.S. government to represent their interests.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<P>

<table border=0 width=310 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1>
<tr><td valign=top width=12><img src="/Graphics/b.gif"></td><td valign=top width=453> 
Virtual reality, in the form of presenting objects on a
computer screen in 3D, won't get real in 1997. VR advocates insist it will prevail in the
long run because it is a more natural way to view and navigate online, but
that's still only an article of faith.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<P>

<table border=0 width=310 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1>
<tr><td valign=top width=12><img src="/Graphics/b.gif"></td><td valign=top width=453>
Money spent on Web advertising will continue to boom,
but virtually every ad-supported site will join an ad network. The media planners who buy
banners can't handle sales calls from standalone sites;  they'll insist on
dealing only with networks.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<P>

<table border=0 width=310 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1>
<tr><td valign=top width=12><img src="/Graphics/b.gif"></td><td valign=top width=453>
The search for new revenue sourcesbeyond advertising
and product saleswill grow more urgent for sites that can't sell ads or products. More
<img height=110 width=120 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_vr.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
sites will try subscriptions for enhanced services (a la <a
href="http://www.quote.com/">Quote.Com</a> and <a
href="http://espnet.sportszone.com/"> ESPNetSportzone</a>), but the
"pay-per-view" approach won't catch on until digital-cash schemes are
widely adopted.  And this won't happen in 1997.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<P>

<table border=0 width=310 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1>
<tr><td valign=top width=12><img src="/Graphics/b.gif"></td><td valign=top width=453>
A shakeout among Internet security firms will begin as
publicly traded, cash-rich firewall companies realize both customers and profits require
them to offer other kinds of Internet security. They'll buy some small
firms, while others will leave the cutthroat security space for easier
business.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<P>

<table border=0 width=310 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1>
<tr><td valign=top width=12><img src="/Graphics/b.gif"></td><td valign=top width=453>
The Net's "soft infrastructure" will expand with
consumer-oriented efforts like <a href="http://www.etrust.org/">eTrust</a>, which guarantees
privacy, quality-assurance seals like <a
href="http://www.shop.org/">shop.org</a>, and trade
groups like the <a href="http://www.edelman.com/IAB/index.html">Internet
Advertising Bureau and the <a href="http://www.netcontent.org/">Internet
Content Coalition</a>.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<P>

The build-ups, shakeouts, expansions, and consolidations are sure to
happen, but the where and when remain fuzzy.  I never said I was a
fortune-teller.  Only one thing is sure:  the future of the Internet
industry as a whole is brighter than ever.
<p>

</font>





<p>

<p>







<font face="Arial" size=-1>

<a href="mailto:timc@cnet.com">Tim Clark</a> hopes readers can see into
their own
crystal balls better than he sees into
his. Send him your predictions for 1997 by email. Yours may run in a future
Perspectives. Don't want your email address linked to your name? Just
indicate that in your email.

<p>


<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html">More Perspectives</a>



</font>



</td>






