<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>It's not over until it's over</strong>
</font>
<br>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>January 10, 1997</font><br>

<p>
<font face="Times">
<p>

"When you come to a fork in the road, you should take it," the inimitable
Yogi Berra once opined. <a
href="http://www.news.com/Newsmakers/Amelio/amelio.html">Gil Amelio</a>
must have taken that advice judging from
his hurried decision to acquire Next.
<p>
The fact is Apple really did not know in which direction to head until last
month. It's interesting that much was made about how a lowly Next marketing
person took the initiative to get the Apple-Next merger talks going. But it
also shows that Apple did not have any direction mapped out when it set out
on the operating-system journey.
<p>
Only time will
tell whether the chosen path is paved with gold or dirt. But what is
indisputable is that in deciding to go with the Next OS,
Amelio has shown that he has the courage to end the tyranny of the status quo.
For this, he should be applauded.
<p>
<img height=113 width=125 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_direction.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>
Mac loyalists may have been hoping against hope that their favorite operating
system was continuing to run circles around Windows (which they have
derisively
dubbed Windoze), but the Amelio regime knew better. In a <a href="
http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/320193/0000320193-96-000023.txt">report</a> filed with
the SEC last month, Apple said:
<p>

"Recent innovations in the Windows platform, including  those introduced by
Windows 95, have added features to the Windows  platform similar to those
offered by the Mac OS.  The company is  currently taking and will continue
to take steps to respond to the competitive pressures being placed on its
personal computer sales as a  result of the recent innovations in the
Windows platform."
<p>
The 10-K filing went on to state that: "Inability to introduce a
next-generation operating system on a timely basis, or to gain developer
support  and market acceptance for it, may have an adverse impact on the
company's operating results and financial condition."
<p>
Wall Street and other critics are less than enthusiastic with Apple's new
strategy. They had been calling on Apple to do something, and when it did,
the reaction was like someone had died. 
<p>
But these naysayers might want to consider a couple of historical facts. Don't
they remember the proclaimed demise of <a
href="http://www.compaq.com/">Compaq</a> early in this decade? The
company was all but given up for dead because it continued to
"over-engineer," meaning it was using home-built technologies (like
motherboards) in its PCs. By adding value, Compaq could, and was, charging
a premium for its machines. But other clone makers, by using generic
components, were putting price pressure on Compaq. <img height=143 width=126 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_died.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
Meanwhile, the engineer
founder of Compaq, Rod Canion, insisted on continuing with Compaq's
heritage of building superior clones. When Canion was ousted, not many
thought Compaq could make a comeback, let alone climb back into its current
number-one position.
<p>
And what of <a href="http://www.ibm.com/">IBM</a> <a
href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=IBM">
(IBM)</a>? Suffice it to say that its stock has jumped from about $40 four
years ago around $160 today. Could history repeat itself in
Apple's case?

</font>


<P>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/js/js1_10_97b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>
</td>
