<br>















































































































































































<p>































































































































































</td>















































































































































































































































<td width=5>















&nbsp;















































</td>































































































































































<td valign=top width="305" align=left>























<!----------- SECTION NAME ---->










<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">
<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif">
</a>










<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->















<font face="Arial" size=+2>







<strong>Embrace and accept</strong>







</font>































<br>































<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 13, 1996</font><br>































<p>















































<font face="Times">







"Can't live with 'em, can't live without 'em." Sure, you've heard this expression before, but to whom does it apply in the computer industry? <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a>, of course. <p>



If there was ever a time when industry leaders collectively displayed their futility in dealing with software's Goliath, this past week was it. <a href="http://www.sun.com/">Sun's</a> <a href="http://www.javasoft.com/">JavaSoft</a> division stirred the pot at the <a href="http://events.iworld.com/fall96/iw/">Internet World</a> conference by claiming Microsoft, which is a Java licensee, was <a href="/News/Item/0,4,6116,00.html">not playing by the rules</a>. In effect, Microsoft was not adhering to the "100 percent pure Java" mandate. One can only deduce that JavaSoft had trouble understanding Microsoft's Internet strategy of "embrace and extend." <p>













<img height=102 width=135 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_live.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>























The rhetoric was different about a year ago when Microsoft asked to license Java. Back then, the Java-givers were gloating over Microsoft's capitulation. Who's crying now? <p>



At the same conference, <a href="http://www.ibm.com/">IBM's</a> Lou Gerstner took center stage to proclaim how <a href="/News/Item/0,4,6124,00.html">the Internet would suffer a setback</a> because of industry infighting and that Microsoft is the only one not playing the "open" standards game. Gerstner emphasized the need for everybody in the industry to get along. <p>



Up until recently, the Boutros Boutros-Ghali role was alien to IBM's corporate mission and Gerstner's mind. The battle of the operating systems--OS/2 vs. Windows--was nothing more than one proprietary OS fighting another. (It was the IS managers who were caught in the middle.) <p>



Ironically enough, while it was pushing OS/2, IBM's own PC division was licensing and bundling Windows into every personal computer that went out the door. IBM's PC division couldn't live without Microsoft. <p>



<img height=150 width=116 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_will.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>





Joining this fray was <a href="http://www.att.com/">AT&T</a> chief Robert Allen. This is <a href="/News/Item/0,4,6106,00.html">what he had to say about Bill Gates</a>: "He's totally dedicated to his work and will do virtually anything to kill the rest of us...Bill Gates can be your partner and be your enemy at the same time." <p>



The question, Mr. Allen, is if that's how you feel, why did you <a href="/News/Item/0,4,1940,00.html">partner with the company</a> in the first place? When your <a href="http://www.att.com/worldnet/">WorldNet</a> division signed the exclusive deal to use Internet Explorer, it wasn't because of a lack of alternatives. A thing called <a href="http://www.netscape.com/">Netscape</a> Navigator has the lion's share of the browser market.<p>



 <p>





</font>















<P>















<font face="Arial" size=-1>































<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_13_96b.html">







<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>































</td>















































<td width=3>















</td>















































































































































































































































































<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->















































































































































