<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->









<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>There goes the neighborhood</strong>
</font>





<br>        










<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 6, 1996</font><br>














<p>











<font face="Times">

It's highly unlikely that <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> would be welcome in Mr. Rogers's neighborhood. But when world domination is the goal, what chance does he or his neighborhood have? Mr. Rogers would have to change his tune slightly once Microsoft took over the block. The edited ditty would go: "Hello, neighbor. Would you be mine, could you be mine, you <i>will</i> be mine." (The original rendition ends with "won't you be my neighbor?") <p>
<img src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_rogers.gif" width="145" height="91" hspace=5 vspace=5 align=left>
So it comes as no surprise that Microsoft is once again being labeled unneighborly. The <i><a href="http://www.wsj.com/">Wall Street Journal</a></i> reports the company is pulling out all stops in a bid to ensure that PC vendors don't mess up its backyard, a.k.a. Windows. Microsoft has told PC manufacturers they had better make sure the first thing users see when they turn on their PCs is the "familiar" Windows environment. Perish the thought of adding shells or other bells and whistles that relegate Windows into an unglamorous, behind-the-scenes operating system. <p>

Why this sudden interest in preventing anyone else to plant their flag on Windows turf? After all, system vendors and software developers have been creating shells to sit atop Windows for years. Remember Norton Desktop for Windows? Tabworks? Dashboard? Not to mention the shell interfaces many PC vendors incorporated into their systems to hide novices from the not-so-friendly Windows interface. <p>

The reason for the change of heart is this darn Internet thing. Microsoft realizes that the rules are changing. Back in the good old days, it knew that when it asked "where do you want to go today?" users had no other place to go but to the Microsoft product arsenal: Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Access, etc. But in this connected, hyperlinked world, users are on a perpetual journey; Windows and its siblings are no longer the only destination. In essence, now the buck starts at the desktop, but doesn't stop there. <p>

Now it's <a href="http://www.marimba.com/">Marimba's</a> Castanet this and <a href="http://www.pointcast.com/">PointCast Network</a> that. It's about "push" paradigms and channels. But what Microsoft is really trying to nip in the bud is <a href="http://www.netscape.com/">Netscape's</a> forthcoming Constellation effort. This program is designed to sit atop Windows and provide the same capabilities as Microsoft's Active Desktop. And with an installed base of over 40 million Navigator users, Netscape has a pretty good shot at neutralizing Active Desktop. <p></font>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>





<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_6_96b.html">




<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   




</td>












<td width=3>

</td>     














<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->    












