<!----------- SECTION NAME ---->

<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html"><img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif"></a>
<br><font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Comdex: Balloon ride or bust</strong>
</font>

<br>        

<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 22, 1996</font><br>

<p>

<font face="Times">

<a href="http://www.comdex.com/">Comdex</a> has lost its usefulness. 


It's not because of long taxi lines, the Ritz-like hotel rates, or the 


maddening crowds. The show seems to have lost its focus.





<p>













Mention Reggie Jackson, Darryl Strawberry, and the Fuji blimp and 
you'd think of the 

World Series, right? Believe it or not, all 
three were hovering around 

Comdex. Reggie was hawking memory drives 
at the 

<a href="http://www.vikingmem.com/">Viking Components</a> booth. 


Strawberry was there to do a Q&A with Jackson, press some flesh, 
and 

sign autographs for attendees who made it through Reggie's long, 
rambling 

presentation. And the Fuji blimp at Comdex? Go figure.



<p>





<img align=left height=99 width=152 


src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_geeks.gif">





The Computer Dealers Expo was started so computer resellers and 


IT professionals could gather in one place, evaluate new products, 

and 
cut deals. Now vendors not only pay megabucks to lease booth space, 

but 
also need <a href="/SpecialFeatures/0,5,5502,00.html">superstar 


pitchmen</a> and 


<a href="/SpecialFeatures/0,5,5446,00.html">gimmicks</a> just to draw 


people to their booths.





<p>




















What's more, this year's Comdex had a decided consumer flavor to it, 


both from a product and attendee standpoint. Companies like 


<a href="http://www.sony.com/">Sony</a>, 


<a href="http://www.philips.com/">Philips</a>, and 


<a href="http://www.samsung.com/">Samsung</a> had a dominating presence, 


at least in terms of square footage. The biggest noise vendors were 
making 

had to do with Windows CE-based handhelds, digital cameras, 
and DVD.





<p>













As for the attendees? Their makeup (or is 
it the psyche?) is also 

decidedly different. Comdex has turned 
into a geek's version of the 

Mardi Gras. The miles and miles of 
show floor aisles in Las Vegas, 

Nevada, are longer than Bourbon Street 
in New Orleans, but that doesn't 

stop these revelers from collecting 
their "beads"--hats, T-shirts, 

umbrellas, pins, posters and 


buttons--<a href="/SpecialFeatures/0,5,5603,00.html">anything</a> 
as 

long as it's free. 





<p>





From the looks of it, it appears evaluating technology is Job 
Number 

Two for most of Comdex attendees. It could be that it's 
the vendors who 

are fueling this party-hardy atmosphere. In their 
bid to draw people to 

their booths, vendors continue to raise the 
ante as far as giveaways and 

gimmicks go.</font>





<p>





<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/js/js11_22_96b.html">
<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   

</td>




<td width=3 valign=top>
</td>     

