<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Welcome to the lion's den</strong></font>

<br>        

<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 15, 1996</font>

<p>


<font face="Times">

"Netscape plans mainframe link. Communicator to include IBM's 
Web-to-host software."

<p>


That was <a href="/News/Item/0,4,5378,00.html">our top headline</a> 
this Friday morning, a clear indication that the more things change, 
the more they remain the same. Not many people would have bet money on 
<a href="http://www.ibm.com/">Big Blue</a> surfing the Internet tidal wave.

<p>


<img align=left height=158 width=103
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_light.gif"> 


This comment from <a href="http://www.sun.com/">Sun</a> honcho 
<a href="http://www.news.com/Newsmakers/Mcnealy/mcnealy.html">Scott 
McNealy</a> encapsulated the general opinion: "To say that IBM has 
seen the light--give me a break!" McNealy was quoted in a 
<a href="http://www.businessweek.com/"><i>Business Week</i></a> 
article from October of last year. "We say to customers, 'IBM, 
<a href="http://www.dec.com/">DEC</a>, and 
<a href="http://www.hp.com/">HP</a> understand where you've been.' 
We understand where you want to go with the Net."


<p>

But far from being in the Net doghouse, as it had been in the 
desktop-centric world, IBM is well on its way to the penthouse in 
the newly reborn network-centric world. Like every other company, 
IBM too has gotten the Net religion. At the rate it's wheeling and 
dealing on the Web front, many are beginning to  call it the Internet 
Business Machine. 

<p>

The biggest reason for this is that the Web is growing up. The 
emphasis is turning from surfing and browser wars to making the 
medium a useful and productive tool for people and businesses. 
While IBM may not understand end users, as evidenced from its failure 
to woo users to adopt OS/2, it sure understands the business of 
businesses. Been there, done that. 

<p>



By some estimates, nearly 70 percent of all "mission-critical" data resides on IBM mainframes. The company still makes multiple billions from its consulting and service and support operations. In other words, IBM is a household word among the Fortune 500 community.

<p>


What's giving the IBM name the cachet of late are two fashionable buzzwords: intranet and e-commerce. Intranets are all about 
corporations conducting business on networks akin to the Internet, but tucked behind firewalls. E-commerce is, well, businesses trading in electronic space, both inside and outside firewalls. Both play to IBM's strengths. <p>

</font>



<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>

<a href="/Perspectives/js/js11_15_96b.html">
<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>  
<p>


<p>

<p>


