<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Disney didn't do it for you</strong></font><br>        





<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 8, 1996</font>

<p>

<font face="Times">


Yo, readers! I'm tired of dishing out all the ideas in this column. I'd

like some answers, please.





<p>





For us journalists, there's no bigger satisfaction than to break a major

story. It provides us the opportunity to beat our chests, flash our

feathers, and collectively proclaim "aren't we the best" at least for one day.



<p>

<img align=left height=95 width=105 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_rain.gif"> 



This past week, we had a scoop on <a href="/News/Item/0,4,5032,00.html">Disney's plans to start its own

online service</a>. We thought we had done pretty good job not only nailing

an exclusive but also providing a comprehensive, in-depth look into

the world of <a href="http://www.disney.com/">Walt Disney</a>. What's more,

we were sure the subject itself

would hit home with most of you, our readers. Disney is, after all, a

household word. We thought its move into cyberdom would, at the very least,

arouse some curiosity. 



<p>


And then, surprise. You decided to rain on our parade. While we

were pretty sure the story would attract the most eyeballs, when we

totaled up the numbers, three other stories came in before it. (Not bad when

you consider that we had over 30 other stories that day, but definitely not

what we were expecting.) By the way, while the story didn't glow on your

radar screens, it sure piqued the interest of some of the traditional press.

Last we checked, Reuters, AP, and Bloomberg wire services had picked up the story and so

had a couple of newspapers.



<p>


One thing Web publishing does well (too well?) is provide precise

statistics on how many readers visited our site and what and how

many of the stories you read. Unlike TV's <a

href="http://www.nielsenmedia.com/">Nielsen</a> ratings, which

extrapolate the number of total viewers from the few households that actually

have the gadgetry to keep count, in the Web world the numbers do actually tell

the true story.


<p>



Traditional print media have no such mechanisms in place. They assume the

lead story will be perused by most of their readers. Whether that is indeed

the case is left to guesswork or to occasional reader surveys.





<p>

</font>

<p>


<font face="Arial" size=-1>

<a href="/Perspectives/js/js11_08_96b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   


<p>


<p>

<p>


</td>











<td width=3>



</td>



































































<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->



































<td valign=top width=155>







<img border=0 height=200 width=155





src="/Graphics/per_singh_a.gif"><br>







<p>










<img border=0  height=16 width=155 

src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">



<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" width=155 

cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>



<tr>     



<td align=left width=155>





<span class="shorttakes">







<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">



<strong><a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc11_06_96a.html">Smart cards not so smart</strong></a>



<br>



The reason I use Visa, MasterCard, or American Express instead of a debit card is the possibility of an error. With a smart card, the cash is gone. With a credit or cash card, you get to review every purchase 20 days later to ensure bogus purchases aren't listed. 

&nbsp;--Doug Ross, dir@worldnet.att.net, 11/6/96

	

<br>&nbsp;<br>



<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw10_28_96.html"><strong>Copywrong 1996</strong></a>

<br>



If they are going to make it that difficult to use a

computer, I'll just quietly turn it off for the last time and put it away. 

I wasn't born with a serial port. 

&nbsp;--Robert Caraballo, susano@bellsouth.net, 11/1/96





<br>&nbsp;<br>





Fair use is a valuable freedom, and collections of information shouldn't 

be able to be copyrighted. 

&nbsp;--Alexander M. Covan, amc@bway.net, 11/1/96





<br>&nbsp;<br>





Editors Note: We received many emails asking where to write concerning 

the electronic copyright issues raised in this column. Contact 

<a href="http://www.public-domain.org/">Public Domain</a>, the 

recently-formed citizens' group opposing these provisions.



<br>&nbsp;<br>



<a href="/Perspectives/js/js10_11_96.html"> <strong> On Bill-bashing</strong></a>

<br>





Yeah! Bill [Gates] gets the bum rap. Has anyone met a billionaire 

they really liked? If Microsoft didn't get the money, IBM would have. 

&nbsp;--Jack Olmsted, jolmsted@frugal.com, 10/11/96



<br>&nbsp;<br>



In regards to your question, "Is it a bunch of 

rhetoric or do you believe Microsoft gets the bum rap?" I think it's 

obviously more Bill [Gates] rhetoric. Frankly, only a company like yours with 

an obviously pro-Windows flavor would even bother asking the question. 

&nbsp;--Adam Masri, masri@nolex.com, 10/12/96



<br>&nbsp;
</td>
</tr>
</table>

