<td valign=top width=310>




<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->















































        















 
      

 
































<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>No win-win with Wintel</strong>



</font>



<br>






















<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 1, 1996</font>


















<p>















<font face="Times">











The Wintel and the Kill-Wintel  camps were busy this week pushing


similar but separate agendas. The two sides made back-to-back


announcements, both seeking to make life easier for long-suffering


computer user. 





<p>



















Their panacea is the network computing device. The Wintel
(<a

href=
"http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a>-<a

href="http://www.intel.com/">Intel</a>) camp


paraded the NetPC, <a href="http://www.sun.com/">Sun Microsystems</a>, 
the

network computer, or the


JavaStation. Both sides want to reduce the cost of owning a PC, which,


according to <a href="http://www.gartner.com/">Gartner Group</a> can cost 
a

corporation anywhere from

$8,000 to $13,000 per user, per year, in 
support and maintenance. 

 









<p>












<img align=left height=123 width=122





src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_priority.gif">










On the face of it, the Microsoft-Intel and Sun initiatives seem very noble.


But scratch the surface and what you get is the same old stuff. 
Service to

the user is secondary or incidental. What this is 
really about is egos and

turf battles. 





<p>  







Check out the following comment and decide for yourselves whether  
user

benefits are at the heart of these initiatives. 
"Kill Microsoft--that's

the top priority for all of us." This is what 
Sun honcho 
<a

href="http://www.news.com/Newsmakers/Mcnealy/mcnealy.html">Scott


McNealy</a> told

the <I><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/">New York Times</I>
</a> following

Tuesday's unveiling of the JavaStation.





<p>
















The Sun king may have been pushing the low-cost, ease-of-use, and


low-maintenance aspects of the JavaStation as reasons users should 
switch

from their current PC-based computing environment. But neither 
McNealy nor

his lieutenants are counting on JavaStation to be a big seller.




<p>








"This thing is a small percentage of the total product


environment, it will help sell more servers,'' Sun executive Ed Zander 
told

Reuters. 





<p>














It boils down to this: The JavaStation NC's primary functions


are to boost McNealy's ego, displace the Wintel hegemony, and help 
sell more

servers. Somewhere buried are the user benefits.





<p>








<img align=right height=125 width=161





src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_empire.gif">










Now let's focus attention on the other set of do-gooders: 
the Wintel group.

Microsoft all but did an about-face in announcing 
the NetPC. Gates until

this week had dismissed the notion of an 
under-powered machine that took

away the "personal" aspects 
from the user.  





<p>









Not only that, the Wintel camp has 
turned up the volume on the cost

of ownership issue the last few 
months. This, after years of pumping out

bloated code and buggy, 
unreliable applications and operating systems. 





<p>





























Why this change of heart? Why this concern? For years IS managers 
have been

decrying the prohibitive costs to own, maintain, and 
support a PC. All this

time the Wintel camp has acted like the 
Roman Empire.  The only difference?

 In their computing

empire, 
users have been thrown to the PCs instead of the

lions, left to 
fend for themselves against the difficult-to-use and


difficult-to-manage personal computer.





<p>





All the while, Microsoft and Intel have responded with empty promises, 
buzz

words, and more acronyms. Plug and play. Simply Interactive PC 
(SIPC).

Sealed-box PC. The newest one is: zero-administrative cost. 
The

implications of this term are obvious. Let's hope this once 
again doesn't

turn out to be a zero-sum game for the users.





<p>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>






Tired of being thrown 
to the PCs? Would you rather be thrown to the NCs? Tell executive 
editor<a href="mailto:jais@cnet.com"> Jai Singh</a> all about it. 




 















<p>

















<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html">








<font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>   















 



















