<p>



 





 



 



        



       





</td>









        






<td width=5 rowspan=1>


<!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->



        






</td>



        















        



       

















<td valign=top width=310>
<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->




















        







        











<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>With friends like these, who needs enemies?</strong>

</font><br>







<font face="Arial" size=-1>October 25, 1996</font>











    










<p>



















<font face="Times">

If you reach out and can't touch someone, don't get mad at your local phone
provider, blame it on the Internet. Of all the things wrong with the
Internet, the biggest problem is telephone service disruption for Bay Area
residents who just want to use the plain, old telephone. If steps are
not taken to remedy the situation, the phone network will be paralyzed by
1998. The average phone consumer will be able to gab no more.
<p>
This message is brought to you by none other than your
not-so-customer-friendly monopoly <a href="http://www.pacbell.com/"> Pacific Bell</a> and its parent <a href="http://www.pactel.com/home.html">Pacific
Telesis Enterprises</a>. 
<p>
<img align=left height=194 width=106


src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_reach.gif">

What's more, the company has all sorts of data to prove its point. For example, Net
usage is putting so much strain on the phone network in Silicon Valley that one out of every six phone calls doesn't get through on the first try, according to Pac Bell. And this will get only worse as users
start transmitting more multimedia content over the Net, the company says.
According to Pac Bell statistics, the phone system is showing signs of wear
even with only eight percent of California residents hooked to the Net.  When that number doubles, there could be "huge tie-ups." Add to this the fact that Internet access calls last more than five times as long as
voice calls, and you have is a time bomb waiting to explode, Pac
Bell and Pac Tel say.
<p>
"My indicators point to a genuine data <I>tsunami</I>, a tidal wave, in the next
18 months," Pacific Telesis CEO Michael Fitzpatrick said in a speech
Wednesday at the  Wescon/96
electronic-equipment makers' convention. "And, ladies and gentlemen, while we can surf the net, nobody
can surf a tidal wave. Our near-term coping strategies
are going to be little more than that--coping strategies," he said. 
<p>  
The regional Bells have been beating the "congestion" and "infrastructure
overload" drums for a while. But the rhetoric is getting louder. Pac Tel,
for one, figures that the best way to get attention is to invoke incendiary
terms like "meltdown" and "communism." 
<p>
"Nothing can save a system based on bad economics. Ask Mikhail Gorbachev,"
warned Fitzpatrick. "Bad economics bring upon the worst meltdown.
Not just an electronic meltdown, but a customer confidence meltdown. And
that could lead to the 'flame out' of what promises to be a really
incredible ride." Neither 
Internet service providers nor users are paying their true share to enjoy the fruits of the Internet, according to Fitzpatrick. He would like to see a "creative"
pricing structure, one which does not discourage use, investment, or
innovation.
 <p>
<img align=right height=113 width=143


src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_surf.gif">

Fitzpatrick sounds like a guy who could sell refrigerators to Eskimos.
While there is some validity to his point about fair pricing,  what he is
really peddling is FUD (fear, uncertainty and doubt). All the talk of
meltdown is intended to scare the general public and force the hand of the
<a href="http://www.fcc.gov/">Federal Communications Commission</a> to end the price break for Internet
service providers. The phone companies want regulators to rescind the 1983 order
that calls for Bell companies to charge discounted rates to ISPs to carry their Internet traffic. 
<p>
And if congestion and meltdown of the phone infrastructure is really a big worry,
why did Pac Bell itself launch what is touted the fastest Internet
service provider start-up in history? Is the strategy geared to kill off
competition in the ISP arena? Seems like these folks want to have their
cake and eat it too.
<p>
Pac Bell and Pac Tel should let the free-market forces work their magic. The
Internet's legacy is its free-wheeling culture and that culture will decide
whether there's a flame out or whether this incredible ride continues.



<p>










<font face="Arial" size=-1>

Email messages to: <a href="mailto:jais@cnet.com">Jai Singh</a>. 


