<td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->

















        







        







<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Did Netscape feint or faint<br>
under Microsoft's glare?</strong></font><br>




<font face="Arial" size=-1>October 18, 1996</font>











    







<p>















<font face="Times">
So, <a href="http://www.netscape.com/">Netscape Communications</a> has 
decided to bury Navigator in something called the Communicator. Navigator, 
the Web browser, is no more. With that, the browser wars are history. 
Did Netscape blink in the face of Microsoft's onslaught on its turf, as 
many pundits gloat, or is this a brilliant tactical move? Maybe it's a
little of both. 

<p>

	  <img align=left height=120 width=128
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_blink.gif">

To get to the bottom of this, let's start by going back to 
<a href=
"http://www.microsoft.com/corpinfo/press/1995/95dec/iswpr4.htm">December 7, 
1995</a>. Microsoft picked the anniversary of Japan's bombing of Pearl 
Harbor to launch its onslaught on the Internet and Netscape. Drawing the 
parallel, Bill Gates said, "probably the important comment that wasn't 
made on Wall Street or by analysts...was made by Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto, 
who said he feared Japan had awakened a sleeping giant." To which 
<a href="/Newsmakers/Barksdale/barksdale.html">Jim Barksdale</a> 
quipped, "God is on our side." 

<p>



             
And why not? Navigator had over 85 percent of the browser market, and 
it was the darling of Wall Street. Plus the odds-makers were betting 
heavily against Microsoft becoming a contender in this emerging market.

<p>

Now, fast forward to May of this year. Microsoft was not only ruing 
Navigator's dominance but saw it as a threat to its very franchise: 
Windows.

<p>

"We look at &#91;Navigator&#93; as a very direct threat for Windows if 
we don't do a good job," Microsoft Executive Vice President Steve Ballmer 
told us in an interview. "That's not a threat a month from now or five 
months from now. It's a long-term threat, but it's a clear threat. It's 
sort of an everyday issue, but if we screw up, we won't know for a few 
years."

<p>


		  <img align=right height=172 width=100
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_threat.gif">

Ballmer spun a yarn: "Once upon a time, there was a piece of software 
that was an extension of an operating system, and it had a nice little 
user interface and it had some programming interfaces and people kind of 
liked it, and over time they built on top of it. One day, the thing 
that it was built on top of wasn't all that important anymore, and it 
kind of got subsumed inside of the thing that was originally an 
extension."

<p>

That "extension" in the tale was Windows. Ballmer compared Navigator 
to Windows, a graphical user interface (or a shell) that sat on top 
of a true operating system, DOS. DOS was ultimately superseded on 
desktops by Windows 95 and NT. The master became the slave.

<p>

This being Internet time, things change rather more quickly than they 
did back when Windows took so long to dethrone DOS. Netscape could have
 posed a real threat to Windows. But, far from muscling in on the desktop, 
Netscape has seemingly retreated to focus on the corporate users and the 
intranet. The browser-as-thin-client on the desktop is no more. From the 
looks of it, Ballmer won't have to worry about his biggest fear coming 
true: Navigator will never rule the desktop. 

<p>

Netscape may well argue that it's not giving up on the desktop at 
all because more people use and "live" in the email world than any 
other. Indeed, since email is the killer application on the Net, Netscape 
figures it could entice more people to use the Communicator as the front 
end for all their tasks. 

<p>

I find it ironic that Netscape wants to go after 
<a href="http://www.lotus.com/notes/">Lotus Notes</a> 
and the groupware market. Some of you may recall that it was only 
a couple of years ago that Jim Manzi, then Lotus's CEO, was actively 
pushing Notes as a desktop environment. His thinking went like this: 
since email and collaboration are the primary activities corporate 
users indulge in, users would "live" in Notes, not only to communicate, 
but also to do word processing or number crunching. The plan was to bury 
Windows beneath Notes. But as we know, that strategy didn't come to pass. 

<p>

Will Netscape succeed where Lotus didn't? Is this strategy of doing 
away with the standalone browser a brilliant tactical move or is it a 
retreat from a battle Netscape knew it could not win? (A free Internet 
Explorer versus a fee-based Navigator browser was a daunting prospect.)  
I believe the answer lies in the what-else curse. Netscape, like so many 
other vendors before it, is caught in the "what else could we do" trap. 
When confronted with the 800-pound Microsoft, the little chimps simply 
find another place to sit. 

<p>

To its credit, Netscape made its move while it is still ahead. 
It has proven to be more nimble than the likes of 
<a href="http://www.borland.com/">Borland</a>, 
<a href="http://www.corel.com/products/wordperfect/index.htm">WordPerfect</a>
, <a href="http://www.ibm.com/">IBM's</a> OS/2, 
<a href="http://www.spco.com/">Software Publishing</a> 
(remember Harvard Graphics?), et al. But will this be enough? 
Probably, at least until Microsoft decides it wants to sit there, 
too. Netscape can't rest now. 

<p>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>
Jane Goodall never takes a break, and neither does 
Executive Editor <a href="mailto:jais@cnet.com">Jai Singh</a>. 
Email him your comments and he'll post the best of the bunch.

<p>

