<td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->











        







        



<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Bill ain't so bad</strong></font><br>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>October 11, 1996</font>


<p>

<font face="Times">
Maybe everyone has pegged <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> 
all wrong.

<p>

Conventional wisdom says that Microsoft plays dirty. That its success is
largely a result of either arm-twisting, chicanery, or skirting the legal
boundaries. That its dominance of the industry is absolute. That it's the
evil empire.





<p>

<img align=left height=102 width=111
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_peg.gif">

But could it be that Bill Gates and Microsoft actually want to do good by
the user? That the company is dominant because it perseveres and is 
passionate about making good software? That the company is all for open


standards and will abide by them? And that far from annihilating the


competition, Gates thinks his own company's existence isn't guaranteed.


Indeed, he doesn't even believe that one single company can dominate the


Internet.





<p>

It's not often that Gates is grilled publicly on issues impacting the 
industry and the user community, especially not when nearly 4,000
influential information technology executives are sitting in the audience.
But Gates appeared to have won over this tough audience judging by the


smattering of applause and the absence of boos when he took center stage 
at

the 
<a href="http://www.gartner.com/events/symposium96/us/index.html">
Gartner Group Symposium</a> in Orlando, Florida, this week.





<p>

Here's how Gates sees things:

<p>

<strong>On giving control of ActiveX to <a href="http://www.opengroup.org/">
Open Group</a>:</strong> Gates's view is

that standards can be very helpful,
and that about 80 percent of what the

industry builds on should be based on
standards. The remaining 20 percent

should be left to the developer's 
discretion so that there's an incentive to

push the technology envelope. 
According to Gates, the "plumbing" is the most


important part of this equation, one that vendors should not compete on. 
So,

for example, object plumbing,  page formats, or mail formats should be 
just

out there as standards. 
(Microsoft's object plumbing is COM, or Component Object Model; for mail, 
it's <a href="http://www.cnet.com/Resources/Info/Glossary/Terms/mapi.html">
MAPI</a>.)  






<p>

"We saw the industry get into a religious war over component models and 
you

just can't have a lot of these. You can maybe have two or three of 
these,

and we could build interoperability bridges," Gates said. 
"It would be nice

if there was only one, but probably there's not 
going to be only one.





<p>





"We are committed to be upwards compatible with what 
&#91;Open Group&#93;

does. This means that if you write to the Open 
Group's ActiveX standards,

those applications will run with DCOM 
(Distributed Component Object Model) that is built into Windows. 
DCOM

itself fulfills everything it's supposed to, so we are not 
going to be doing

any extensions. If the ActiveX group proposes 
extensions, that's not

something we can control."





<p>
<strong>On standards:</strong> "Who should love the standards the most?


Because of our success, when the industry grows that's a huge benefit for 
us

and &#91;other companies like&#93; 
<a href="http://www.intel.com/">Intel</a> and 
<a href="http://www.cisco.com/">Cisco</a>. We are not trying to


create a separate revenue stream in DCOM.





<p>
<img align=right height=93 width=152


src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_bat.gif">







"We feel good about our role in <a href="http://www.ietf.org/">IETF</a>, 
<a href="http://www.w3.org/">W3C</a>, and Open Group. I mean, this is


perfectly good business judgment exercised here to say, 'Let's not have 
a

battle over this one, let's make sure there are very few of these.'"





<p>







<strong>On making Windows 
<a href="http://www.cnet.com/Resources/Info/Glossary/Terms/api.html">APIs</a>
 public:</strong> Asked where does he draw the

line on plumbing--that is, 
why doesn't he open up Windows itself to the standards

process--Gates said, 
"We draw the line where we can no longer can pay our employees. We have 
a

business model where we charge two to three percent of the cost of the 
PC system

if people want to run the operating system on that. 
There are a few things,

like what we do in the user interface, 
or some of the things we do in the

algorithms that we do to make it 
run more efficiently, or the richness of

the way we pull in all those new 
drivers. Those are some of the things that

uniquely define Windows."





<p>





<strong>On why Windows succeeded:</strong> 
"People always forget that back in

1989, nobody used Windows. 
People said we were totally dependent on our

relationship with 
<a href="http://www.ibm.com/">IBM</a>, and all those different kinds of 
Unix flavors, whether

it was Next or Solaris, were going to blow away 
this crummy little PC that

couldn't do anything. So our ability to do 
and renew things and make them

richer is vastly underestimated.




<p>





"If we hadn't done Windows 95 for its usability, I believe other
&#91;operating&#93; systems, including the Macintosh, particularly if 
they had been able to execute...would have been extremely popular today. 
This was not

preordained; it was because of persevering with Windows and 
Windows NT."





<p>





So there you have it, straight from the horse's mouth. How do you see it?


Is it a bunch of rhetoric or do you believe Microsoft gets the bum rap?





<p>





<font face="Arial" size=-1>

Don't send mail to Bill. 
Email messages to <a href="mailto:jais@cnet.com">Jai Singh</a>.







<p>




