<br>
<a href="/cgi-bin/redirect.cgi?location=http://www.microsoft.com/ie/ad/euprod02.htm%3fportal.ad2">
<img src="/Banners/Portal/Perspectives/msie.perspectives.ptl.banner.gif" border=2 width=100 height=115 align=middle></a>
<br><p>
















                



<p>



 





 



 



        



       </td>







        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->



        </td>



        















        



       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->











        







        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Standards or scram</strong></font><br>







      







        <font face="Arial" size=-1>October 4, 1996</font>











    <p>





<font face="Times">



The Internet may be changing the world. But for the harried corporate
users, will the old saying "the more things change, the
more they remain the same" still ring true?
<p>
To be sure, the corporate user community is giddy over this paradigm
shift because Internet technologies are based on open standards. They see
this as an opportunity to get out from under the proprietary yoke.
<p>
That's the good news. Users' consternation, however, has to do with the
vendors' interpretation of the word "open" and "standards." Their
experience with PC standards has been less than stellar. 
<p>
<img align=left height=102 width=166

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_abuse.gif">
The kind of abuse Information Technology (IT) customers have tolerated
is unrivaled. What other group of consumers would suffer through
the pain of buying a new product only to discover it's not "compatible"
with what they already own? Indeed, what other consumer group not only
have the privilege of paying for buggy products, but are forced to
accept the fact that in the software world, quality means Release 1.1?
<p>
Fast forward to the new paradigm where vendors who until recently were
protecting their proprietary turf are suddenly preaching the gospel of
"openness" and adherence to " standards" in their bid to get the
Internet and intranet business.
<p>
This week, Microsoft took center stage as it handed over control of
ActiveX to a independent body with the hope that it will become the
standard for component architecture. Microsoft will turn over key pieces
of ActiveX in the form of source code, specifications, and reference
implementations on Windows, Macintosh, and Unix operating systems. 
<p><img align=right height=102 width=144

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_tiger.gif">
This move surely is a result of Microsoft wanting to catch up with other
vendors touting their "open" wares. But in typical Microsoft fashion, it made sure to
approve all the member companies who are on the steering committee, and
as the largest producer of ActiveX software, Microsoft has 
ensured it will play a large role in shaping the future direction of
ActiveX. Will the ultimate result of this be the fox guarding the
chicken coop? Stay tuned.
<p>
Netscape too has been pushing the open-standards envelope. Although a
member of the W3C consortium--the governing body for HTML standards
among others--Netscape went beyond the published specification to
incorporate proprietary extensions into its Navigator browser. We've all
seen the end result of this: "This site best used with - (Netscape or
Explorer)."  Users are once again the ones left dangling. 
<p>
What is clear is that these standards committees, hand picked or not, are
really toothless tigers. It's time you users get involved in this
networked computing world.
<p>
To ensure that this paradigm shift once again doesn't become paradise
lost, you--who have been signaling SOS for a long time--had
better make sure that this time SOS means something different: "standards
or scram." Don't open up your pocketbook to vendors who veer from the
standards, throw the book at them instead.

</font>

<p>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>



<a href="mailto:jais@cnet.com">Jai Singh</a> has always empathized with Peter Finch.  

</font>

<p>



<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>     
<p>









<p>







<p>







<p>



        </td>



























