        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->

        </td>

        







        

       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>
Do all roads lead to Redmond?</strong></font><br>



      



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 27, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">

The power of one.
<p>


	
Since all roads paved with software lead to Redmond, you know which "one" I am 
talking about.  The latest proof of <a
href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a>'s omnipresence came this week
with the roll out of OS/2 Warp 4. <a href="http://www.ibm.com/">IBM</a> made
a low-key announcement of its
latest revision to the operating system. And it was <i>very</i> low-key,
especially compared with
Microsoft's launch of Windows 4, a.k.a Windows 95. 
<p>

<img align=left height=80 width=96
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_cry.gif">

A little over a year ago, Microsoft spared no expense to announce to the
world the birth of Windows 95. Not only did it sponsor the entire edition of
the  London-based daily, the <i> Times</i>, but it generated so much
hype and publicity that some hardy souls lined up at  midnight August
24 to buy their own copies.
<p>


To top it all off, Microsoft licensed the Rolling Stones' "Start Me Up"
track. Could
Microsoft have known then that the line "you make a grown man cry" would so
literally hit home?  
<p>

Just ask IBM OS/2 officials. The utter futility of their efforts can be
summarized by this forlorn cry: "What else can we do?"
<p>



What else, indeed? The company delivered an operating system  years ago that
had all the features that Microsoft touted in Windows 95: a 32-bit computing
environment, true multitasking, and robust
security, to name just a few.
<p>


And if the feature-war alone wouldn't slay its number-one foe, IBM had
fortified its strategy by designating a Blue Ninja to spearhead the OS
charge. Alas, the warrior, Lee Reisweig, like Borland's Philippe "The
Barbarian" Kahn, fell on his own sword.

<p>


There have been various reasons cited for the failure of OS/2 including time
to market, poor marketing, and lack of third-party application support. But
the fact is that IBM could have moved heaven and earth.  It still
wouldn't have mattered.
<p>



Why? The answer is Microsoft's death-grip on PC manufacturers. Many were
locked into
so-called per-processor licensing contracts for DOS/Windows. This meant that a
Compaq, for example, would have to pay Microsoft a fee for every PC shipped
regardless of whether its machines carried DOS/Windows or any other operating
system. The <a href="http://www.usdoj.gov/">Justice Department</a> asked
Microsoft to stop this practice in
1994, but by that time it was too late for IBM or anyone else. 
<p>


	 <img align=right height=117 width=90
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_fired.gif">
So now OS/2, like so many of its fellow software brethren, will become a
niche player. Rather than fighting an uphill battle IBM has decided to leave
the mass market to
Microsoft,  focusing on its core groups of customers in the banking and
insurance industries. Through it all, IBM said it remains committed to
supporting its core constituency. For this, it is to be applauded. 
<p>

Customers used to say "you can't get fired for buying IBM." Now, the  "IBM" has
been replaced with "Microsoft." Just like in the good old days, perception has
become a reality.
<p>

By hook or by crook, Microsoft has won over the only people who ultimately
count, the customers. Having won the desktop war, it has set its sights on the
"connected" world. 
<p>
The jostling for position on the Internet and intranet fronts has just
begun. But once again Microsoft is in the thick of things. The real question is,
when the Microsoft ad asks, "where do you want to go today?" will most users
and software developers once again head toward Redmond? 

</font>
<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="mailto:jais@cnet.com">Jai Singh</a> wants to know if you're going his way.</font> 

<p>


<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>     



<p>



<p>



<p>

        </td>













</tr>





