       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Reports of their deaths are exagerated</strong></font><br>



      



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 20, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">

There must be something
about the fall and races. Baseball pennant races are in full swing. The
presidential horse race is well under way. And, the computer industry is
just getting into its element as it picks the latest round of 
losers.

<p>

	
Companies put on the death-watch this week include Netscape, Novell, and Apple. Then 
there is General Magic, which announced a management
shakeup on Thursday, but this company has been given up for dead for
quite some time now.


<p>
<img align=left height=153 width=132
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_mere_quote.gif">

For some computer industry prognosticators, a company better be either in robust financial 
health or they deem it too ill to survive. There is not much room in between. You are either a
champ or a chump.  
<p>


It was about this time last year
that many pundits were declaring Microsoft a has-been. The consensus
was that Microsoft just could not make it to the next paradigm shift.
Its stock took a tumble after  Goldman Sachs issued a
report saying Microsoft was in trouble because it did not have a
sound Internet strategy. 

<p>

A year later, not only is everything well with Microsoft, but the
ill-health of these companies is directly attributed to the software
giant. For Netscape it's the Internet Explorer; for Novell it is NT and for
Apple it continues to be Windows and worse. 
<p>


Netscape has been under intense scrutiny since the release of IE 3.0. The fire was flamed
by a report on Wednesday from a Wall
Street analyst who downgraded the company's stock from "accumulate" to
"neutral." The analyst's rational: Microsoft is invincible and Netscape
has no friends - a deadly combination. But that's me putting words in the
in the Merrill Lynch analyst's mouth. Here's what he actually said:

<p>

	
"We believe that we have underestimated Microsoft and that the window of
opportunity for Netscape to partner is closing much more rapidly than
originally thought," Bruce Smith wrote in a report. "With Microsoft's success
and recent problems in the partnership area [for Netscape], we felt the
risk for Netscape has significantly increased."

<p>



Never mind that the company still has the dominant share of the browser
market. Or that it is profitable after only two years in business. Or
that the majority of its second quarter revenue of $75 million came from
corporate sales. Or that it's not counting on the browser to be its only
source of revenue. If these numbers seem puny compared to Microsoft, they
are, but Netscape is making money in the Internet/intranet space, a market that
is just taking off, and one that Microsoft is totally focused on itself.
<p>


Netscape CEO Jim Barksdale is fully aware of Microsoft's entry into his space and its resulting effects. He told us in a recent interview that
he can forsee the day when Netscape and Microsoft have 50-50 share of the
market. His point was that it's difficult to maintain a dominant market share when
users are deploying "open" Internet standards, unlike in the days of the proprietary
desktop-centric world.

<p>


 
"You know, it's very hard to switch from WordPerfect
to Word. That's a conversion you make and then you don't want to do that
again or vice-versa. Here (in the network-centric world) you can go from one client to the other and
that's a whole advantage and that makes it easier to do. That's the fight
we have to fight, but I think the outcome will be decidedly different," he said.
<p>

 <img align=right height=108 width=241
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_market_quote.gif">

"I'm not going to give anybody the benefit that they're going to
gain it all, but I think it's unrealistic for me to expect that anybody
could keep an 85 share of something that has a relatively low switching
cost, he said. "I think that certainly we'll will win some and lose
some. I think it's extremely unrealistic to expect that just all of the
sudden next year they have 85 percemnt and me have 10 percent."

<p>
As for Novell, the drum beat about its survival got louder right after it
unveiled its Intranet strategy. In a bid to convince the world that it's
got the Internet religion, it even changed the name of its
flagship product from Netware to Intranetware. Novell's timing was off a bit - its chief
executive quit the following week (and others have departed since). Still, 
the company is the dominant provider of the network operating system and has taken
steps to put its house in order to sustain the $1 billion in revenues. But at this week's
Networld/Interop show, people were lamenting how the company whose very
name was synonymous with the show is gasping for air. 
<p>
 
And Apple got dinged after a news report that said some of its biggest corporate customer were 
planning to displace the Mac. The implication was that Apples already tenuous market 
postion got even weaker. This news was reported just days before Motorola announced it was
going to build Mac clones  -  giving Apple its first big-name catch. And on Wednesday Apple joined forces with 
Sun to designed to link Macs and Solaris servers as well as to work on technology 
to let Java software work with OpenDoc and QuickTime. 


<p>
To be sure Novell, Apple and - to a lesser extent - Netscape have their work cut out 
for them. In Novell and Apple's case it may be more a case of them getting hooked up 
to an IV than being put six feet under. Microsoft is 
a tough and tenacious competitor and it's take-no-prisoners attitude can 
impact competitior's business tremendously. 
But as Intuit has shown, not every company that crosses a giant's path gets trampled. 
So, obiturary writers take note: the fat lady may be warming up, but it isn't close to singing yet.  

</font>
<p>


<font face="Arial" size=-1>Email messages to <a href="mailto:jais@cnet.com">Jai Singh</a>.
 

