<br>
<a href="/cgi-bin/redirect.cgi?location=http://www.microsoft.com/ie/ad/euprod02.htm%3fportal.ad2">
<img src="/Banners/Portal/Perspectives/msie.perspectives.ptl.banner.gif" border=2 width=100 height=115 align=middle></a>
<br><p>




<!--[Put in the left column bar library]-->





                

<p>

  

 

        

       </td>



        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->

        </td>

        







        

       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Security this, security that</strong></font><br>



      



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 13, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">


"Security breach."    
<p>
No two words have more ominous implications in the nascent world of electronic commerce than these. Talk about your hot buttons. It appears Net users have security on their minds more than the other s-word. An Alta Vista search for the words "secure" and "security" brings up over 1 million matches, compared to only 300,000 for "sex." While totally unscientific, this is some indication of Netizens' state of mind.

<p>

	<img align=left height=140 width=145
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_sex_quote.gif">


Little wonder, then, that many sites doing business transactions on the Net invariably have the word "secure" prominently displayed on their home pages. One has to wonder whether this constant drumbeat pacifies potential customers or just fuels their paranoia. Airlines don't plaster "secure" signs on airplanes or on marketing literature. Likewise, the dozens of unsolicited credit card offers you and I get don't trumpet security as the selling point. "One percent over prime" is more likely to reel in a customer. But the Web merchants seem to have a different interpretation of Marketing 101.

<p>

To wit: "Secure, Hassle Free On-line Shopping" is displayed at the <a href="http://www.booksite.com/">BookSite</a> home page. The site sells books online. You provide the credit card number and they ship you the book. However, this past Monday <a href="/News/Item/0,4,3250,00.html">we wrote a story</a> about how this site wasn't that secure after all.

<p>


Based on a tip, our reporter was able to obtain credit card numbers and other sensitive information from the BookSite location. This was no elaborate hack. It was just a matter of typing some <a href="http://www.cnet.com/Resources/Info/Glossary/Terms/sql.html">SQL</a> code, and up popped names, addresses, phone numbers, and credit card numbers. For the record, we printed the story after BookSite had been notified and after it plugged the security hole. Also, for the record, the intent here is not to single out one site.

<p>

Coincidentally, the very day we broke this story, IBM and several major banks <a href="/News/Item/0,4,3194,00.html">announced the formation of Integrion</a>, a coalition whose aim is to boost electronic commerce. Not surprisingly, they bandied about security as Job No. 1. 

<p>


"With this new venture, electronic commerce will take its biggest step forward to date," IBM Chairman Lou Gerstner said. "This is a secure network marketplace that is essential to the growth of electronic business." 


<p>


   	<img align=right height=120 width=180
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_bull_quote.gif">

That's great, Lou, but people aren't going to jump to e-commerce because of secure transactions. They already conduct business in an environment they perceive to be secure. Users may be more inclined to shop online because of lower prices or convenience, for example.

<p>

 
Look, hacking takes place all the time in the "real" world as well. Businesses like banks and credit card companies are victims of fraud more often than they care to admit. They'd much rather swallow the losses than publicize the break-ins, for fear that customers will become skittish. 
<p>



In fact, the Senate Permanent Investigations Subcommittee in June reported that hackers cost businesses an estimated $800 million through break-ins to computer systems at banks, hospitals, and other large businesses last year. The report went on to say that most bank losses weren't even reported, because they don't appear in required federal paperwork. The losses could be orders of magnitudes larger, so I'm not suggesting that security (on the Internet or otherwise) is a nonissue. 
<p>
When it comes to the Net, though, do we have to paint the proverbial bull's-eye on every home page?

<p>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="mailto:jais@cnet.com">Jai Singh</a> can see you through the monitor, he knows what's on your mind. But email him anyway. He's a lonely man.<br>
</font>

<p>


