<p>

  

 

        

       </td>



        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->

        </td>

        







        

       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Nervous Laughter</strong></font><br>







        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 6, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">


When it comes to the PC, plug and play still means plug and pray.

<p>



   We are no closer to attaining PC nirvana today than we were three
years ago. Comfortable in the knowledge that we have no other choice but to
use what we have, PC industry leaders have pooh-poohed the network computer
as being little more than a crippled PC, while doing little to make PCs
usable for the average human. Instead, they keep churning out new acronyms
like SIPC (Simply Interactive PC) and USB (Universal Serial Bus) with the
full realization that they are years from actually delivering something. Now
that the <a href="/News/Item/0,4,791,00.html">Network Computer</a> is upon
them, the PC-only camp has gone from denial to nervous laughter.

<p>


    <img align=left height=160 width=167

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_nirvana.gif">



Intel's CEO Andy Grove last week acknowledged that Intel's Plug and Play
technology didn't deliver, and USB is likely to fall
short of the mark as well. And the reason why Plug and Play won't work?
The software has gotten too complex, Grove is reported to have said.
Ouch! Talk about providing ammunition to Network Computer proponents.






<p>



 

Microsoft's Steve Ballmer told a gathering at the
Windows Solutions conference last week that what users are demanding is a
cheaper PC, not only to own but to manage.



<p>



"There's a lot frustration with the PC in this area and if companies like
ours and Intel and others don't do the job that we need to do to make it
simpler for the end user and simpler and cheaper for the IT department to
own PCs, the PC will be replaced by alternative devices like the Network
Computer," he said. 

<p>



We'll find out how frustrated everyone really is starting this month.
Several major companies including Sun, Sony, and Oracle are expected to
unveil their Network Computers. IBM said Wednesday that it plans to come out
with a <a href="/News/Item/0,4,3108,00.html">$700
Network Computer </a>later this year, which will be the first of many
different models. 




<p>


       <img align=right height=228 width=125

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_simpler.gif">

Meanwhile, having watched the drama from the sidelines, two of the
world's leading electronics companies figure it's time they became
players instead of spectators in this noncontact sport. Both Toshiba and
Sony think they have the right formula to churn out user-friendly PCs,
devices that combine the best of consumer electronics and computers.
Oracle's threats didn't impress the two-headed Wintel giant, but Toshiba and
Sony are starting to make Intel and Microsoft squirm.
<p>

 
The Toshiba PC, to be unveiled next week, will sport more personalities
than Sybil. It can pass as a PC, a radio, a television or a phone: a
hybrid computer, if you will. Sony, meanwhile, this week started shipping
its consumer PCs. 


<p>



If only these two could come up with better names than <a
href:"/News/Item/0,4,3161,00.html>Toshiba
Infinia</a> and <a href="/News/Item/0,4,1624,00.html">Sony VAIO</a> (Video Audio
Integrated Operation). Now would be a good time to stop making up
acronymns and start making PCs easier to use.
</font>
<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Email comments to: <a href="mailto:jais@cnet.com">Jai Singh</a><br>

</font>



<p>

<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>     


<p>



<p>

        </td>













</tr>





