<td valign=top width="305" align=left>



<!----------- SECTION NAME ---->

<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">
<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif">
</a>

<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Lies, damned lies, and the truth</strong>
</font>
<br>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>January 9, 1997</font><br>

<p>
<font face="Times">
<p>

Pierre Salinger should get a chuckle out of this. The <a href="http://www.fbi.gov/leb/dec961.txt">December</a> issue of the FBI's <i>Law Enforcement Bulletin</i> describes five "new insidious viruses" that don't exist. They're  <a
href="http://www.wdc.net/~bburnett/jokes/virus.html">jokes</a>. No, not hoaxes, but the equivalent of geek knock-knock jokes that circulate routinely on humor mailing lists and Internet discussion forums. 

<p>
Red-faced over
the article, the <i>LEB</i> jerked the offending
paragraphs (see sidebar for the text) from their Web site a couple of days
<img height=129 width=130 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_badge.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left> ago, but the paper
magazine, errors intact, has already been mailed to about 55,000
subscribers.
<p>
While this little incident will surely spur more Internet-as-rumor mill
stories, I think it illustrates that misinformation is neither the exclusive purview of the Internet, nor does it go unchallenged for long. The gaffe was brought to light on the Web pages of <a
href="http://www.kumite.com/myths/">Rob Rosenberger</a> and <a
href="http://sun.soci.niu.edu/~crypt/">George C. Smith</a>, two virus experts who present the Computer Virus Hysteria Awards each year. 
<p>
The Internet may spread myths faster than any other medium, but it also often discredits them with more haste and alacrity than the traditional
press. Once enshrined in books and prominent
newspapers and stored in databases, errors (even those later corrected) can
be perpetuated almost without end. One example: Teddy Roosevelt's charge
up San Juan Hill was, in fact, a ride up the smaller Kettle Hill, a fact that
you will only find if you dig up his original account. Oh, and those joke viruses? They may have originated on the Internet, but the authors of the <i>LEB</i> article, both Ph.D.s and
college professors, lifted them from a British scholarly journal.
<p>
The handwringing tone of recent articles would suggest that we must "do something" to reign in the Net's unbridled nature. But, what makes the Internet such a petri dish for conspiracies, rumors, and innuendo is also what makes it a conduit for truth. It's like a
free society in a macrocosm: While it's hard to contain untruths, it's
equally difficult to spin, fold, bend, or staple the truth.
<p>
The obvious example is <a href="http://www.lexis-nexis.com/">Lexis-Nexis's</a> attempts to corral the fury of U.S.
citizens incensed over the
company's P-TRAK database. The company's efforts were largely unsuccessful because
it didn't really come clean; it didn't lie, but then it didn't exactly tell
the truth.
<p>
While some emails incorrectly accused Lexis-Nexis of selling information
such as credit histories, it is true that P-TRAK users once could look up,
by name, a person's Social Security number. In response to outraged emails,
phone calls, and faxes, the company "masked" Social Security numbers,<img height=175 width=136 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_leb.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
allowing P-TRAK subscribers to look up others' names, former names,
addresses, former addresses--in short, all the information necessary to
assume someone else's identification by simply typing in a Social Security
number. 
<p>
The information is still there; you just get it differently. Lexis-Nexis spin doctors forced the press to play 20 questions. Reporters who knew exactly how to phrase the question got the whole truth. But 
almost every mainstream media outlet didn't know the right question and
subsequently reported that Social Security numbers
were removed from the database entirely. (NEWS.COM has even been chided for
perpetuating "rumors" by the <i><a href="http://www.wsj.com/">Wall Street
Journal,</a></i> ostensibly for our insistence on reporting the Social Security numbers had not been entirely eliminated from the database.)

</font>


<P>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw1_9_97b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>
</td>
<td width=3>

</td>

<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->
<td valign=top width=155>
<img border=0 height=208 width=155

src="/Graphics/per_margie_a.gif"><br>
<p>



<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc"
width=155 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>

<tr>
<td align=left width=155>
<span class="shorttakes">
<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">
<strong>
FBI's Folly</strong>
<br>
The FBI removed from the Web the following portion of an article on computer
crime, wherein joke viruses were portrayed as being real:
<p>
"&#91;S&#93;everal new insidious viruses have been found:
<p>
"Gingrich randomly converts word processing files into
legalese often found in contracts. Victims can combat this virus
by typing their names at the bottom of infected files, thereby
signing them, as if signing a contract.
<p>
"Clipper scrambles all the data on a hard drive, rendering it
useless.
<p>
"Lecture deliberately formats the hard drive, destroying all
data, then scolds the user for not catching it.
<p>
"Clinton is designed to infect programs, but it eradicates
itself when it cannot decide which program to infect.
<p>
"SPA examines programs on the hard disk to determine whether
they are properly licensed. If the virus detects illegally copied
software, it seizes the computer's modem, automatically dials
911, and asks for help."
&nbsp;
<br>
<br>
