<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">
<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif">
</a>

<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Insanely insane</strong>

</font>

<br>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>January 2, 1997</font><br>
<p>
<font face="Times">
<p>



<a href="http://www.ultimate-apple.com/dir/woz.html">Woz</a> forgive me for

I have sinned.

<p>


<img height=144 width=115 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_jobsangel.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>The Most Holy Inquisition of Mac Fanatics detected my heresy early this

week and almost 200 censures flooded my email box in two days. Herewith

lies my

trespass: "The Macintosh didn't change the world, but it did change

Apple...." I wrote upon <a

href="http://www.news.com/News/Item/0,4,6419,00.html"> Steve Jobs's</a>

triumphal return to Apple. Getting flamed is an occupational hazard that I

accept. But usually I am electronically excoriated for something more,

well, <i>serious.</i>

<p>

Macintosh devotees have always been an odd lot, displaying a fervor for a

computer that verges on <a href="http://www2.macevangelist.com/thirdoffive/macevan/macevan.html">religious

mania</a>. But since the Macintosh has lost about 40 percent of its already

slim marketshare over the last year or so, Macophiles are acting

even more paranoid than usual.

<p>

What used to be good-natured poking at "Windoze" and cheery evangelizing of

the good word of the GUI, has turned into nothing less than a hunt for

Commies. The evil Minions of Microsoft are everywhere and must be rooted

out and exposed. Anyone who criticizes the Macintosh (or Steve Jobs now,

apparently) is "stupid," "ill-informed," and worst of all a Windows

sympathizer. It's us against them and it's obvious that not everyone is

bright enough

to see that the Macintosh is the one true and superior computer.

<p>

There seems to be some mistaken premise at work here that if we'd all just

get together, hold hands, a sing along to <a href="http://www2.macevangelist.com/thirdoffive/macevan/macevan.html"><img height=127 width=90 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_preacher.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right></a>"I'd like to teach the world to

mouse," then the Mac would be saved. It's not a test of faith. It's a

computer.

<p>

Yes, Apple pioneered changes to computers that were outright copied--from

the first commercially shipping internal CD-ROM right down to the Macintosh

interface, which Microsoft shamelessly (and clumsily) ripped off in Windows

95. I've used a Macintosh since I bought my first one 11 years ago. Even in

all-Windows shops, I've insisted on my Mac. Now that Windows 95 has come

along, I admit that my Mac crashes more, and more's the pity. But it's

still the most elegant and easiest-to-use computer I've ever laid hands on,

and I recommend it to anyone who will listen. I have hope that it will

survive Apple's misfortunes.

<p>

Still, I remain clear-eyed enough to realize that the Macintosh changed the

industry, but not the world, and certainly not by the measure that Jobs had

hoped when he introduced it in <a

href="http://www2.apple.com/whymac/1984/1984.html">1984</a>. The <a

href="http://www.evangelist.macaddict.com/"> Evangelistas</a> and <a

href="http://www.saracen.com/applejedi.html">AppleJedis</a> (defenders of the OS, let the dark side of the

OS be warned) are jousting at windmills. Since I doubt they will ever

disband completely, maybe the Subcommittee on Un-Macintosh Activities could

redirect its energies toward more effective activities in this new year:

<p>

<table border=0 width=310 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1>

<tr><td valign=top width=12><img src="/Graphics/b.gif"></td><td valign=top width=453>

Try more direct action. Picket computer superstores

responsible for murdering the Mac's image. (I have an old Mac 512Ke you can carry around in

a jar for dramatic effect.)

</td></tr></table>



<p>



<table border=0 width=310 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1>

<tr><td valign=top width=12><img src="/Graphics/b.gif"></td><td valign=top width=453>

How about a reverse "What's on your PowerBook"

advertising campaign? "Out" <a href="http://www.owt.com/users/sdechter/celeb.html">rock stars and artists</a> suspected of being Windows users.

</td></tr></table>



<p>



<table border=0 width=310 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1>

<tr><td valign=top width=12><img src="/Graphics/b.gif"></td><td valign=top width=453>

Lobby Apple to create a Macintosh that replenishes the

dwindling ozone layer. Then you'll win hands down the next time there's an argument about

whether or not the Macintosh changed the world.

</td></tr></table>


</font>

<P>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw1_2_97b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>

</td>

<td width=3>

</td>

