<td align=left width=155>
<span class="shorttakes">
<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">
<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_27_96a.html"><strong>Sour
grapes?</strong></a><br>
Sounds to me like Cronkite is verbalizing the fears of his contemporary
associates; and I am not talking about the fear that you might not be
professional or ethical. If Web news organizations can get it right,
unbiased and unedited, then they will flourish. One word--TRUST. They (the
mainstream news media) don't have it
anymore. &nbsp;--<a href="mailto:yusuf@infomagic.com">Yusuf Faruq
'Abd-al-Hakim</a>
<br>

The traditional press and the new form of reporting (Dateline, 20/20, etc.)

are either biased or downright unethical. They provide news that exists

in their own sphere, with little regard to real, unbiased, and credible

insight. Your efforts to implement a new and different perspective are

a fresh breeze in a news reporting. <a href="mailto:ibelyea@teleport.com">

I. Belyea</a>

<br>

&nbsp;

<br>
<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_20_96a.html"><strong>WebTV</strong></a><br>

Dream on!  The PC is just a digital TV/VCR without a traditional tuner, and

with a lot of unnecessary expense mounted on the desktop instead of at the

cable company where it belongs. You go ahead and live in the past.  Keep

your big clunky dinosaur PC! Disconnect from the network!  Keep your

loyalty to companies who have <i>no</i>

loyalty to <i>you</i>.  But don't expect us to!  We'll be flying down the

Information Highway on our Kawasaki NetCruisers!

&nbsp; --<a href="mailto: jamesefe@concentric.net"> James E. Felton </a>

