<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->

<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Technocracy</strong>

</font>

<br>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 26, 1996</font><br>

<p>

<font face="Times">

<p>
Recently, while rooting deep in the closet for the holiday wrapping paper, I ran across two copies of <i>Technocracy Review</i>. The funky little rag was produced here in San Francisco in the 1930s as a sort of demi-scholarly forum for discussing the sweeping changes that technology was wreaking on the world at that time. (And the Wired gang thinks it's doing something new...)
<p>
<img height=242 width=160 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_goliath.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left><p>
I flipped through the crumbling pages, smiling at illustrations of tin-can machine-men poised to enslave the populace at the bidding of "technocrats." These (invariably) men wielded  remote power through the levers and nobs of Rube Goldberg contraptions, threatening the jobs and livelihoods of honest folk. 
<p>
I love thumbing through these magazines, not because of that smug, superior feeling one gets from knowing how things turned out, but because it's comforting to know that what we're going through isn't new. <i>Technocracy Review's</i> writers were as bewildered by radio as we are by the Internet; they were going through the worst depression in history, and they were scared.  
<p>
"The question is, who shall control society?" one asks. The writers in <i>Wired's</i> predecessor may have been naive about technology, their ideas about the Great Society of Men outdated, but their questions and fears were essentially the same as those we face. 

<P>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_26_96b.html">
<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>
</td>

<td width=3>
</td>

<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->

<td valign=top width=155>

