<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif">























<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->































<font face="Arial" size=+2>















<strong>The monitor has two faces</strong>















</font>









<br>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 18, 1996</font><br>









<p>







<font face="Times">



<a href="http://www.mattelmedia.com/barbie/fashiondesigner/">Barbie's CD-ROM</a> is selling like hotcakes and the pundits are falling over each other to praise Mattel for cracking that impenetrable market: "girls' software." 

<p>









There are so many things wrong on so many levels with this bit of news that I get queasy just thinking about it. <a href="http://www.mattelmedia.com/barbie/fashiondesigner/"><img height=133 width=100 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_barbie.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left></a>It's the same feeling I get every holiday season when I brave the hot-pink aisle of "girls' toys" at the local Toys 'R' Us. Following the nausea comes anger, then resignation.<p>



Year after year, I see the same assortment of toys, but with each passing year, the very adult marketing messages that propel them off the shelves loom larger. "Nobody cares what girls can do; the only thing that matters is what girls look like," the boxes fairly shout. <!--Barbie box around here-->

<p>



Some people argue that any product that gets girls to use computers is good. But I don't agree. It's the same fatuous argument that persuaded my parents to let me waste hours on video games. Playing Pac Man didn't teach me to reason or to write, two key skills in the information economy. Printing out Barbie clothes off a computer isn't going to inspire girls to become engineers, CEOs, or market analysts, either. That's not to say that there's anything wrong with just having fun with software. Girls should play, too.

<p>



<img height=246 width=65 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_kyoko.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>







But you have to ask what message girls are getting when they see virtual images of "perfect" female beauty reflected back from their monitors in passive creatures like Barbie and worse. Japan's virtual pop starlet, <a href="http://www.etud.insa-tlse.fr/~mdumas/kyoko.html">DK-96</a>, for instance, beats Barbie's unreasonable expectations by a mile. Without the constraints of even molded plastic to weigh them down, the creators of DK-96 peg her weight at an anorexic 95 pounds on a 5-foot, 4-inch busty frame. She never talks back; she'll never demand a raise; she'll never compete or threaten. No wonder her (male) creators think she's the perfect girl. 



</font>



<P>







<font face="Arial" size=-1>















<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_18_96b.html">
<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>































































