<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">

<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif"></a>











<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->















<font face="Arial" size=+2>







<strong>PlanetIn</strong>







</font>































<br>































<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 12, 1996</font><br>































<p>















































<font face="Times">







When you turn to venture capital, you dance with the devil, or so the



founders of <a href="http://www.planetout.com/">PlanetOut</a> have learned. 



<p>



PlanetOut sounds like it could be a Web site for skiers or hikers, but it's



not. PlanetOut is for the queer community--in other words, anyone who's not



straight. Hip without being snotty with a whip-smart, twenty-something



sensibility, the site debuted with predictions of a bright future all around. 







<p>















<img height=71 width=145 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_pnologo.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>























Now, only months later, executive producer Karen Wickre has been sacked;



founder Tom Rielly has been tossed from the board and stripped of his



president title; employees are complaining that the site's content is being



sanitized, and PlanetOut is losing its way.<p>







What happened between its founding and today is a classic business tale:



Promising hip young business garners acclaim; venture capital follows;



founders ousted by imagination-impaired investors. PlanetOut danced with the



devil and it seems to be getting burned.















<p>



























Following Wickre's ouster, the site dropped its tag line, "a worldwide online



community for gay, lesbian, bi&#91;sexual&#93; and trans&#91;sexual&#93;



people," claiming it



was necessary in order to please investors who feared the site was too



controversial to attract nongay-specific advertisers.



<p>











"There are bits and pieces where people have ambivalence around the edges of



our community and that's why we decided to reword," said Jon Huggett,



president and CEO of PlanetOut. "What happens if we get into a meeting with



some CEO who's a raging homophobe?...We want to make it an easy sell."







Huggett insists that the content of the site won't change. If anything,



it will be more inclusive of the "edges" like bisexuals and transsexuals, he



says. The new tag line will be "the most inclusive place in cyberspace."



<p>



<img height=160 width=150 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_people.gif" align=right>



"We wanted to be as inclusive as possible, and that means getting support from



advertisers and stores outside our community. What we don't want them doing



is picking apart the community like they're shopping in a grocery store,



&#91;saying&#93; 'I'll take this and not that.'"



<p>







PlanetOut employees tell a different story. They say the site's content is



being toned down to the point of being insipid. The lively attitude that gave



PlanetOut its edge is evaporating. Chat rooms like the popular "Sissy Boy"



have been buried. Bisexual coverage is being minimized and transsexual



coverage and discussion is being eliminated. Some employees are grumbling that soon



the only acceptable portrayal of gay life will look like <i>My Three Sons,</i>



where Dad and "Uncle" Charlie (wink, wink) oversee an otherwise average



middle-class home. <p>







While it's easy to chide Huggett and Taylor for an expeditious retreat,



PlanetOut is hardly the first online community to soft-shoe its mission in



the name of commercial success. <a href="http://www.womenswire.com/">Women's



Wire</a>, which started its life as a bulletin board system that was



refreshingly honest about real live for women, lost cofounder Nancy Rhine



shortly after an infusion of venture capital. The investors brought in a



former women's magazine publisher who moved the service onto the Web and



several online services, but morphed it into another vehicle for selling



lipstick and panty hose to women along the way. Investors are conservative;



they tend to go with what they know. 



<p>



</font>















<P>















<font face="Arial" size=-1>































<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_12_96b.html">







<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>































</td>















































<td width=3>















</td>















































































































































































































































































<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->















































































































































<td valign=top width=155>































<img border=0 height=200 width=155























src="/Graphics/per_margie_a.gif"><br>











<p>























<img border=0  height=16 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">















<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" 































































width=155 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>































































<tr>     































































<td align=left width=155>































































<span class="shorttakes">















<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">







<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_6_96a.html"><strong>Microsoft's neighborhood</strong></a><br>















If <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> wants to require their OEMs to make certain that upon







shipping, the first screen that pops up is the Windows start-up screen







followed by the default desktop, it certainly seems that this is Microsoft's prerogative. &nbsp; --<a href="mailto:tkozik@msmedia.com">Thom Kozik</a>























<br> &nbsp; <br>























How long do you think Microsoft would last if it didn't do some of the things it does? The computer software industry changes too quickly and is too competitive for a company to rest on its laurels. It's not as if Microsoft is saying, "You must use our software!" They are saying, "Check out our software first, and if you don't







like it, use something you think will do it better!"  So please, can't we







all just get along!  &nbsp;  --<a href="mailto: formula@concentric.net">Daniel Anders Garcia Sanroman</a> 















<br> &nbsp; <br>















<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_5_96a.html"><strong>Stay home</strong></a><br>















I don't always agree with positions taken by the <a href="http://www.ala.org/">American Library Association</a>, 







but in this case, their assessment is accurate. The <a href="htttp://www.packardbell.com/">Packard Bell</a> commercials 







are "subtle, bleak, and ultimately selfish."







<br>







[T]housands of...libraries in this country spend millions of dollars every year on computer equipment... I would venture to guess that many librarians will not be 







considering Packard Bell products when they go shopping for new equipment in 1997. &nbsp; --<a href="mailto:Lisa_Paris.IDEA@idea.com">Lisa Paris</a>















<br> &nbsp; <br>







If Margie Wylie's recent column suggested that Microsoft doesn't like public







libraries, I'd like to state for the record: We love them!







<br>







In fact, Microsoft's largest philanthropic effort is a joint program with the







American Library Association called Libraries Online. <br>Microsoft has







committed $15 million in cash, software and technical assistance to 215







libraries in the U.S. and Canada to bring the benefits of Internet and PC







technology to underserved communities.







<br>







The public library is one of the great democratic institutions of the world.







And Microsoft is pleased we could work with the urban and rural communities







to enhance library resources.















&nbsp;  --<a href="mailto: christhe@microsoft.com">Christopher Hedrick</a>, senior program manager, Microsoft Community Affairs,







<br> &nbsp; <br>















It is just a commercial. I never even considered 







it a slam on urban safety or a knock against 







librarians at all. I enjoy the commercials and 







view them as saying that there is a more friendly, 







entertaining way to get information from the 







comfort of your home. &nbsp;  --<a href="mailto:rgcurry@jcpenney.com">Rick Curry</a>







<br> &nbsp; <br>















Nothing is "just a commercial." Packard Bell has no interest in the







ethical, moral, or cultural implications of its advertising. That







sentence should end "of course. [W]hat [the commercial] depicts is the spiritual character of a nation that worships bottom lines, big bucks, and what's in it for me. &nbsp; --<a href="mailto:mickmca@bigfoot.com"> Mick McAllister </a>







<br> &nbsp; <br>























 Basically, I think it boils down to the two "future















views" we've dealt with since computers became popular.  We could live in a















nice society in which computers help us do many things, and enhance our















contact with other individuals. 















<br>















The other view...is one in which we live in















isolation but, alas, everyone has a nice plastic PC!  Yea.















&nbsp; --<a href="mailto:hijinx@enteract.com"> Paul McAleer</a>















































<br> &nbsp; <br>































































