<td valign=top width="305" align=left>





<!----------- SECTION NAME ---->


<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html"><img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif"></a>


<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->



<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Why bother with civic life? Go home </strong>

</font>







<br>







<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 5, 1996</font><br>







<p>











<font face="Times">





What do you think of when you think of librarians? Seems  <a href="http://www.packardbell.com">Packard Bell</a> thinks of shaved-headed, jackbooted

thugs who stomp through dimly lit wood-paneled rooms full of dusty old media--books, that is--shushing cowed library patrons.

<p>



The computer maker is raising the hackles of librarians with a series of <a href="http://www.packardbell.com/ads96/television.html">TV

commercials</a> that portray libraries as decrepit institutions that you can avoid altogether by staying at home with your computer. 



<p>

<table align=left width=145 border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>

<td>

<img height=105 width=140 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_borg.gif">

</td>

<td width=5>

&nbsp;

</td>

</tr>

</table>



While librarians aren't thrilled about the stormtrooper image, the <a href="http://www.ala.org">American Library Association</a>, which recently protested the series, is more concerned that the commercials encourage wealthy people to abandon civic life and public institutions, such as libraries, in favor of closeting themselves up with their computers in their safe suburban enclaves.



<p>



The lush, visually arresting 60- and 30-second spots are

part of a major image makeover for the PC-maker. Packard Bell recently merged with <a href="http://www.nec.com/">NEC</a> and is trying to overcome bad publicity in the wake a scandal which involved selling used parts in new computers. 



<p>

<table align=right width=145 border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>

<tr>

<td width=5>

&nbsp;

</td>

<td>

<img height=105 width=140 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_bang.gif">

</td>

</tr>

</table>

The 60-second commercial opens on a rain-soaked post-apocalyptic future full of ragged, blank-eyed

people shambling through a gargoyle encrusted Gotham. As the operatic sound track swells, the benighted souls inexplicably drag a burned-out car body

down train tracks. A blonde-hair, blue-eyed little girl peeks from behind a giant tome of  <I>Paradise Lost</I> and is hushed by sinister troops marching

around the room in red uniforms. It then moves to  a beautiful, if underfed, Aryan woman waiting in line at the "Bangk," until she develops unsightly fine lines around her mouth and eyes. 



<p>



Finally, the scene changes to a suburban house, afloat in a sea of garish, green grass and bounded by (what else?) a white picket fence. Inside an eye-popping yellow room, the sun shines, the birdies twitter, and a breeze lifts a gauzy curtain as the camera zooms in on a Packard Bell computer screen. A disembodied voice asks,

"Wouldn't you rather be home?"





</font>



<P>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>







<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_5_96b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>







</td>











<td width=3>



</td>



































































<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->



































<td valign=top width=155>







<img border=0 height=200 width=155





src="/Graphics/per_margie_a.gif"><br>







<p>































































<!--<table width=155 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 bgcolor="#FFFFCC"















border=0>















































<tr>























































