</table>-->











<p>



























<p>





<img border=0  height=16 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">



<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" 



width=155 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>



<tr>     



<td align=left width=155>



<span class="shorttakes">



<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">

<strong>Two views of the future</strong>
Basically, I think it boils down to the two "future
views" we've dealt with since computers became popular.  We could live in a
nice society in which computers help us do many things, and enhance our
contact with other individuals. 
<br>
The other view...is one in which we live in
isolation but, alas, everyone has a nice plastic PC!  Yay.
&nbsp;--<a href="mailto:hijinx@enteract.com"> Paul McAleer</a>


<br>&nbsp;<br>


<strong><a href="/Perspectives/js/js11_08_96a.html">Mickey who?</strong></a>

I love CNET. But I'm not interested in Disney. I much prefer articles on companies that directly affect my life.  I'm referring to major corporations such as AT&T, all the
Bells, Microsoft, etc.  Companies that have so much money and influence that
if they catch a cold, I sneeze.  I figure I have to keep an eye on them. 

<br>




&nbsp;-- <a href="mailto: hmccoy@bigeasy.com ">Helen McCoy</a>




<br>&nbsp;<br>

You may have broken the [Disney] story first, but I'm going to hear about it
over and over from other sources as well simply because it is Disney.

&nbsp; -- <a href="mailto:jackdel@cts.com">Jack DeLong</a>


<br>&nbsp;<br>




<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw11_11_96a.html"><strong>Bullies will be bullies </strong></a>


<br>

What your article refers to as "intimidation and bullying" 
is more commonly referred to in corporate America as "doing 
business."
That the concept of a domain name is somehow deserving of 
a status approaching religious talisman and somehow exempt 
from the same hideous injustices that large corporations 
inflict on everything else that gets in their way is silly.

The Internet is a cluster of computer networks--not a 
utopian experiment, not the astral plane, and certainly 
not a sanctuary from the unconscionable evils of 
capitalism.  Delusions that indicate anything to the 
contrary are just that -- delusions. 
<p>
"The Internet is not TVland," you say?  
Hey, give it time. 

&nbsp;-- <a href="mailto:pent@kcmo.metrobbs.com">Pete Thomas</a>,
Lawrence, KS



<br>&nbsp;<br>








<a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com"><strong>What's your Perspective?</strong>
<br></a>
Got a point of view you'd like to share? NEWS.COM wants your Perspective. Email your rantings to opinions editor <a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com">Margie Wylie</a> to be considered for our guest editorial spot, the Soapbox. Please keep it under 1,200 words and type "soapbox" in the subject line.


</font>


<br>&nbsp;<br>

</td>
</tr>
