<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html"><img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif"></a>









<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Margie's excellent blimp ride</strong></font>


<br>        






<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 20, 1996</font><br>


<p>




<font face="Times">

I'm one of those people who spends a lot of time at trade shows asking, 
"Where did you get that?"

<p>









<table width=160 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3 align=left>
<tr>
<td>
<img height=116 width=155 border=0 src="/Images/Comdex/Features/cabs2.gif">
<a href="/Video/Comdex/blimp.mov"><img border=0 src="/Images/Newsmakers/quicktime.gif" width=80 height=16 border=0></a><font size=-1> 1,423K</font>
<a href="/Video/Comdex/blimp.avi"><img border=0 src="/Images/Newsmakers/avi.gif" width=80 height=16 border=0></a><font size=-1> 1,444K</font><br>
<font face=Arial size=-1 color="#666666">
<strong>Experience the blimp!</font>
</td>
<td width=5>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

Whether it's a pair of Styrofoam deer antlers, a particularly 
piquantly sloganed T-shirt, or tickets to see Seigfried and Roy 
attempt to tame Steve Ballmer, it seems that all the great trade 
show giveaways have "just run out, sorry" by the time I've figure 
out they exist at all.

<p>

Not anymore. This week, the hottest Comdex ticket netted the holder 
a ride on the Altavista blimp, and I had two.

<p>








<table width=155 border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 align=right>
<tr>
<td width=5>
&nbsp;
</td>

<td>
<img height=121 width=200 border=0 
src="/Images/Comdex/Features/blimpinside.gif">
</td>
</tr>
</table>



With my trusty video camera operator, Trish Brown, I set out to savor 
my perks, no longer suffering from the delusion that every one of the 
other 199,999 Comdex attendees were sneaking off to a secret room to 
drink brandy, smoke cigars, and talk about that clueless redhead who 
keeps asking where to get a flashing "Intel Inside" pin. 

<p>









I'd like to think that it was my superior inside connections 
that landed me a ride on the airship AltaVista, but the truth is that 
these days the best way to rise above the noise at Comdex is to fly 
over it. Seems that running the lighter-than-air rides all week not 
only craned a lot of necks around the Convention Center, but also cost 
a lot less than putting on a Comdex dog-and-pony show.</font>

<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>



<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw11_20_96b.html">


<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   

<p>


<p>

<p>


</td>











<td width=3>



</td>





















<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->

<td valign=top width=155>


<img border=0 height=200 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_margie_a.gif"><br>







<p>

<img border=0  height=16 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">

<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" width=155 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>

<tr>     

<td align=left width=155>


<span class="shorttakes">


<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">

<strong><a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw11_11_96a.html">Why didn't I think of that?</strong></a>
<br>





This &#91;column&#93; got me thinking about what the next step might be. 
At first, I thought about copyrighting truth. But then it hit me: 
copyright falsehood. Think of the windfall I'd get every election season!
&nbsp;--Mark Valence, kurash@sassafras.com, 11/14/96

<br>&nbsp;<br>

Maybe we could speed up the inevitable copyright process and allow whole 
lists of words to be trademarked at once. Whoever has the most money could 
just send in Webster's Dictionary and be done with it. &nbsp; --Valient 
Gough, val@nilenet.com, 11/11/96


<br>&nbsp;<br>


<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw10_28_96.html"><strong>Copywrong 1996</strong></a>


<br>



If they are going to make it that difficult to use a

computer, I'll just 
quietly turn it off for the last time and put it away. 

I wasn't born 
with a serial port. 

&nbsp;--Robert Caraballo, susano@bellsouth.net, 
11/1/96

<br>&nbsp;<br>




Fair use is a valuable freedom, and collections of information shouldn't 
be able to be copyrighted. 

&nbsp;--Alexander M. Covan, amc@bway.net, 
11/1/96



<br>&nbsp;<br>


Editors Note: We received many emails asking where to write concerning 


the electronic copyright issues raised in this column. 
Contact <a href="http://www.public-domain.org/">Public Domain</a>, 
the recently-formed citizens' group opposing these provisions.

</font>
<br>&nbsp;
<br>&nbsp;
</td>
</tr>
