<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Bullies of the Internet</strong></font>


<br>        






<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 11, 1996</font>








<p>







<font face="Times">







You can find them on billboards and in newspaper ads. You see 

them on 
television, hear them on the radio, and find them scrawled on 

bathroom 
walls in trendy cafes: Internet addresses.





<p>









Two years ago, 
all the "wwws" and ".coms" would have made about as much 

sense to the 
general public as the lyrics to a Frank Zappa tune. Today, 

they are 
readily recognized by most of the 90 percent of Americans 

who've never 
even set virtual foot in cyberspace. 





<p>








<img align=left height=190 width=170
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_intimidate.gif"> 





But what most of us don't see, American or not, when we see an 

Internet 
address is the bullying that might have gone into getting 

that address. 
Johnny-come-latelies to the Internet experience--corporations 

that 
used to buy or cajole their favored addresses--have found a simpler way of 
getting what they want: Threaten the owners with legal obliteration. 












<p>








Last month, a Web site at the address 
<a href="http://www.news.com/News/Item/0,4,5115,00.html">thenewyorker.com</a>
was threatened by <i>The New Yorker</i> magazine, claiming that the site 
was infringing on its trademark by using that name, even though <i>The New 
Yorker</i> already owned the domain name newyorker.com. <i>The New Yorker</i>
attorneys demanded not only that <i>The New Yorker Gazette,</i> a Webzine 
published at that address, quit publishing, but also that it turn over the 
domain. Of course, the Webzine complied immediately.





<p>








The small Web publisher's experience is 
<a href="http://www.law.georgetown.edu/lc/internic/recent/rec1.html">not 
unique</a>. As corporations have begun to flock to the Internet, prime 
commercial spaces in the ".com" neighborhood have become as hard to come 
by as affordable housing in San Francisco. In fact, by the time some 
corporate giants 
(including <a href="http://www.mcdonalds.com/">McDonalds</a>) discovered 
the Internet, they found that the addresses they considered rightfully 
theirs (mcdonalds.com, in this case) had already been 
<a href-"http://www.law.georgetown.edu/lc/internic/recent/rec2.html#mcdonalds">snapped 
up</a>.


<p>



Their owners had registered these addresses (for a $100 fee) 
with the <a href="http://rs.internic.net/">InterNIC</a>, the 
pseudo-governmental agency that passes out Internet addresses on a 
first-come, first-served basis. Once an Internet addresses is registered, 
it's gone. Unlike in the real world, where local businesses like McDonald's 
Plumbing exist alongside multinational corporations, the Internet only has 
one mcdonalds.com. 





<p>







Simply because the folks with money can 
intimidate those with less 
out of domain names doesn't make it right, or 
even legally sound. "Right now, we seem to decide &#91;who gets an Internet 
address&#93; by who can 
intimidate the other," said John Lederer, a retired 
intellectual property attorney and steering committee chair to the citizen's 
group <a href="http://www.public-domain.org/">Public Domain</a>. In most 
cases, the bullies claim trademark on a word or words in a domain to 
justify stealing it from its registered owner. Many times, as in 
the case of 

thenewyorker.com, the legal bully doesn't even want to use 
the name, 

but wants to remove it from circulation.






</font>





<p>




<font face="Arial" size=-1>



<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw11_11_96b.html">


<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   

</td>








<td width=3>
</td>     










