<td valign=top width=310>








<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->


















































        















 


      

 




































<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Where the emperors wear 
no clothes</strong>



</font>






<br>






<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 4, 1996</font>

<p>


<font face="Times">

<a href="www.fox.com">Fox</a> broadcasting 
recently launched a 24-hour cable news TV service and nobody came.


<p>



That's not because <a href="www.foxnews.com">Fox News</a> lived up 
to chief Rupert Murdoch's predilection for tabloid journalism and 
right-wing sympathies. It's not because TV viewers are saturated with 
news or because we want our CNN. It's because only a tiny handful of the 
approximately 85 percent of Americans who have cable TV has ever seen it.


<p>


<img align=left height=109 width=155







src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_fox.gif"> 


Fox News has been frozen out by the nation's largest cable TV owners. 
Time Warner won't carry the channel at all (at the behest of CNN chief 
Ted Turner) and Tele-Communications Inc. (TCI) is only carrying 
the service to less than 20 percent of its viewers. Add a few upstart, 
independent cable companies, and Fox News is reaching a potential 
audience that numbers somewhere under 20 million. (The channel isn't 
even reaching its native Manhattan, which is mostly served by Time Warner, 
except by upstart Liberty Cable, famous for its teeny three-line ads 
at the bottom of.)


<p>



In a monumental battle of the egos, the brash CNN chief Ted Turner, 
the head of the Turner Broadcasting Network,  has decided to strangle 
the equally egregarious Rupert Murdoch's competing Fox News in the 
cradle just by keeping it off the wire. So how does one of the crowned 
emperors of media, his highness Rupert Murdoch get his message out? 
The Internet. 














<p>


Broadcasting sound, if not pictures, from its Web site, Fox News 
is probably  reaching more potential Net listeners than cable TV 
viewers. Depending on who you talk to, the Internet enjoys anywhere 
from 30 to 60 million wallets, er, people. That's very little compared 
to cable TV networks, but its more than Fox News is enjoying on cable 
TV now.




<p>


Murdoch is battling the freeze-out in court right now, 
but until then, it's odd to see the emperor slumming in a medium 
where highness like him wear no clothes. On the Internet, Ted Turner 
little more weight than CNET mogul Halsey Minor, yeah I see you 
scratching your heads. On the Internet, Rupert Murdoch and Fox News 
are only one of many news services. Unlike cable TVs private networks, 
the Internet can't be frozen by monumental egos. At least, not yet.



<p>












<img align=right height=102 width=131







src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_frozen.gif">






<p>


But what happens when the Internet can finally carry video as easily 
as audio? Well, that's when the Internet's emperors will don clothing, 
and swords, and monumental egos may reign supreme. Take, for example, 
the British Telecommunications and MCI merger announced this week. The 
two were already planning to build an international, private backbone for 
carrying Internet-type traffic. Of course, Fox News' parent company, News 
Corp. is 20 percent owned by MCI. Murdoch may yet have his chance to stand 
in Turner's path on the information superhighway, but I hope not. I'd like 
to see the Internet escape cable-TV-ification.



<p>





<font face="Arial" size=-1>



Can the Internet 
escape cable-TV-ification? Opinions 
editor <a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com">Margie Wylie</a> wants to 
know what you think. Your response could be excerpted in an upcoming 
letters section. 







 



















<p>





















<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html">









<font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>   















 



















