</td>



















        















<td width=5 rowspan=1>







<!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->







        

















</td>







        































       

 







       







































<td valign=top width=310>



<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->











































        















        





























<font face="Arial" size=+2>



<strong>Gimme a quarter!</strong>



</font>

<br>



















<font face="Arial" size=-1>October 28, 1996</font>













<p>











<font face="Times">







The digital revolution will be copyrighted. And you, gentle surfer, will 

pay for it.





<p>











That's the message 

<a href="http://www.public-domain.org/">Public Domain</a> is 

trying to get out. The group was organized recently to fight proposed 

copyright laws that would decimate the democratic potential of the 

Internet. 





<p>






<img align=left height=96 width=142



src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_violation.gif">






Under the laws in question, it could be illegal to quote a paragraph of a 

<i><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/">New York Times</a></i> article in email. If you did it anyway, you <i>and</i> your Internet service provider (ISP) would be guilty of felonies. Downloading a Web page to your hard drive could be considered a copyright violation. Databases of public documents that today are free could be copyrighted, and electronic access could be limited to those who can afford to pay. These "minor adjustments," as Patents and Trademarks Commissioner Bruce Lehman called them, would effectively freeze the free flow of academic and civic discourse on the Internet.

<p>  

"This is a stealth issue that will have enormous consequences," said James Love, a member of Public Domain's steering committee and director of the <a href="http://www.essential.org/cpt/cpt.html">Consumer Project on Technology</a>, part of Ralph Nader's Washington-based Center for the Study of Responsive Law. 

<p>





<img align=right height=129 width=142

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_enormous.gif">


It all started last year when the <a href="http://www.uspto.gov/">U.S. 

Patents and Trademark Office</a> issued a white paper suggesting that to 

protect database makers' investments, changes needed to be made in copyright 

laws. Both the Senate and the House wrote bills incorporating Commissioner 

Lehman's suggestions. One of the most controversial proposals is to make it 

possible to copyright any collection of information as though it were an 

original work, like a painting or a novel.

 



<p>






"In 1991, the Supreme Court ruled that phone companies can't copyright 

white pages because there is no originality inherent in them," Love said. 

"That's why competition was introduced in phone directories." The new rights 

would mean "you could copyright things like &#91;Internet&#93; addresses, 

genetic sequences, even all kinds of government information so long as, at 

some point, a contractor was involved," Love added. If that happens, we 

could all wind up paying for electronic access to public documents prepared 

with tax money.





<p>







<img align=left height=124 width=125



src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_burning.gif">







Two other provisions would eliminate all "fair use" and turn ISPs 

into copyright cops. Fair use is the convention that makes it legal to 

email an interesting article to a friend or to quote another writer's 

work in an academic paper without worrying about being sued. What's worse 

is that ISPs could be held responsible for any infringers on their 

systems. If either law passes, ISPs will be burning Bruce Lehman in 

effigy. They shouldn't be drafted as copyright police and certainly not 

for such a draconian extension of the law.







<p>





Both bills stalled under scrutiny before Congress adjourned for the season, 

but that doesn't mean the issue is dormant. The 

<a href="http://www.wipo.org/">World Intellectual Property Organization</a> 

is being pressured by the U.S. delegation to adopt an international 

treaty that looks surprisingly like the stalled bills when it meets 

December 2 through 20. What Lehman couldn't get from the inside, he 

may force from the outside with no comment, laws, or due process.







<p>





<a href="http://www.public-domain.org">Public Domain</a> has pitted itself against some of the richest, most 

powerful corporate interests in the world. It is making enemies of 

information brokers like 

<a href="http://www.lexis-nexis.com/">Lexis-Nexis</a> and 

<a href="http://www.r-e.com/">Reed Elsevier</a>, and it's 

challenging the Clinton administration in the process. Even with 

these opponents, the group's greatest enemy is the issue's complexity 

and seeming obscurity. It's going to be tough to persuade the average 

Web surfer to give a damn.
<p>

The group is organizing a letter writing campaign and will be presenting its objections on November 6 at a public hearing about the U.S. involvement in the coming WIPO meeting. 






<p>

























<font face="Arial" size=-1>



Chirp up to 

<a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com">Margie Wylie</a> if copyright 

matters to you. Look for your reply in an upcoming letters section.

 









<p>











<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html">







<font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>   















 





















