<br><p>
































                







<p>







 











 







 







        







       











</td>















        











<td width=5 rowspan=1>



<!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->



</td>



<td valign=top width=310>

<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->



<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Please don't push<br> the envelope</strong></font><br>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>October 21, 1996</font>



<p>



<font face="Times">



Is anyone else out there tired of all the high-tech Archie Bunkerisms that pass as educated speech these days?

<p>

I've always considered myself a modernist when it comes to American English. It's an adaptable language that ought to adapt to the times.  Usually, however, these changes fill holes in the language. They make understandable that which is not understandable without them. So words like "satellite" and "lift-off" came into common use with the blossoming of America's space program in the late 1960s.

<p>

What's happening in the tech industries, however, seems to be just the opposite. All the new verbiage seems to be aimed at obfuscating, baffling, intimidating, or most anything besides informing. Not only are nonsense tech words being coined at a phenomenal rate, but tech execs are borrowing and misusing horribly technical jargon from the hard sciences. 

<p>



<img align=left height=52 width=137

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_leverage.gif">



"Critical mass" is what flattened Hiroshima; it has nothing to do with selling

network computers. The only place Bill Gates pushes the envelope is in

<a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> Flight Simulator. And it's not possible to "leverage" anything,

although I suspect that one might find it equally difficult to lever the

things the Gil Amelios of the world want to pry up, like customers,

markets, and product features. 



<p>



Year in and year out, at keynote speeches and dinners, in press releases and

on TV, those who would lead us into this brave new world bamboozle and amaze

me by stringing together dense thickets of meaningless circumlocutions.

Sitting in the audience, scratching my head and trying to divine what disintermediated 

object-oriented systems have to do with real life, I often wonder how

one suggests to these Harvard-educated captains of industry that they might

try joining <a href="http://www.toastmasters.org/">Toastmasters</a> if they really want to tell us what's on their minds.



<p>

Then one day, it dawned on me: tech-talk is designed to obscure, not elucidate. Like political double-talk, technical double-talk fills huge chunks of time, while saying little or nothing. 

<p>

<img align=right height=105 width=130

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_critical.gif">



It makes me wonder what it must be like to be married to a high-tech

illuminati. "Honey, the disintermediation of the kitchen output will create

a dynamic, real-time interface that leverages municipal infrastructure and pushes

the envelope of mass market acceptance." Translation: "Great new garbage

disposal."



<p>



If the eager, adoring audiences at trade shows and awards dinners are guilty of absorbing such claptrap unquestioningly, we in the press are complicit with those who spout it. More often than not, we lazily report the meaningless verbiage straight from the horses' mouths. I say lazily because that's what it comes down to in the end: intellectual lethargy. You see, high-tech concepts are often highly abstract subjects. How do you explain the difference between the Internet and <a href="http://www.compuserve.com/">CompuServe</a> to a farmer? It's possible, but just takes some effort. 

<p>

As more high-tech companies start trying to sell their products at <a href="http://www.thegoodguys.com/index.html">The Good Guys</a> and <a href="http://circuitcity.pic.net/index.html">Circuit City</a>, bosses had better start polishing up on the KISS rule: Keep it simple, stupid. If they don't change now, their faces may freeze that way.

<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>

Unload your worst encounter with gobbledygook on <a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com">opinions editor Margie Wylie</a>. She'll post the most egregious ones.









<p>











