<p>



 





 



 



        



       





</td>







        





<td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->



        



</td>



        















        



       











<td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->















        







        





<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Stick with flag burning</strong></font><br>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>October 14, 1996</font>











    





<p>













<font face="Times">











Seems everyone in Washington loves the Internet. Politicians, in their blissful ignorance, think of the so-called information superhighway as one of those nonissue issues on which they can't go wrong, like flag burning. I mean, who would dare say that every public school and library shouldn't be wired to the Internet? Only someone who hates children and puppies, obviously. It seems however, those blissful days are soon to be over. 
<p>




	  

<img align=left height=112 width=211

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_beware.gif">



Last week a group of three senators found out that technology boosterism is no longer as safe a political activity as kissing babies used to be. Early this year,  Sen. Richard Bryan, (D-Nevada) Sen. Larry
                                          Pressler, (R-South Dakota), and Sen. Ernest Hollings, (D-South
                                          Carolina) got all up in arms about privacy on this newfangled Internet thing. Indignant at the slings and arrows suffered by their constituencies, the brave legislators ordered the <a href="http://www.ftc.gov/">Federal Trade Commission</a> to recommend legislation that would protect us Americans and boost their images in the process.
<p>






             

Trouble is, the FTC took them seriously. Late last month, the federal agency came up with a concrete, simple answer that would take very little effort on the senators' parts to make happen. The FTC basically recommended extending existing law under the Fair Credit Reporting Act to cover a little more information, like Social Security numbers, maiden names, and unlisted telephone numbers. That would mean that nobody could purchase your personal information without your permission and that you'd have the right to know what's stored about you, in addition to the right to correct any erroneous information. Is that so much to ask? Apparently so. 
<p>
Ho ho, wait a minute, to paraphrase the politicians. No can do. That's "too controversial," came the reply, after careful soul-searching and, no doubt, reeducation from such impartial parties as <a href="http://www.lexis-nexis.com/">Lexis-Nexis</a>, whose P-TRAK database of personal information so inflamed mouse potatoes that they actually took paper in hand and wrote the senators over the last few weeks. 
<p>
News flash, boys! Welcome to the real world. Communications technology is very controversial. If you're looking for babies to kiss, better pucker up and park that saccharine sweetness elsewhere, because the Internet and everything it stands for is dangerous political turf.
<p>




		  <img align=right height=126 width=147

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_tough.gif">



In fact, it's ground zero. The battles that are being waged on the sacred political ground of the information superhighway are the battles that will shape who has the knowledge, who has the wealth, who has the power, and who will be subjected to that power in the next century. The ire, the outright rage recently poured out over the private information for sale on Lexis-Nexis (and many other electronic sources) and the complaints about junk email show that Americans won't be snowed by the old kitchen-of-the-future cheerleading that plunged us into the huge deficits of the Cold War. Americans like the convenience of our microwaves, but we also have a healthy skepticism, born of Reagan's Star Wars, about bloated technologies looking for something useful to do. Now, after the first blush of romance, we're starting to give these new communications technologies, and those legislators claiming to be on our side in their use, a little more scrutiny. 
<p>

Just wait till our lawmakers have to finally address issues like equality of access to information technologies. Wait till we start stratifying even further into a country where a fraction of the folks order pizzas through the Internet from behind gated communities and the other 99 percent delivers them. Then we'll have gone way beyond angry voters and passed into the realm of civic distress.
<p>
It seems things will have to get that bad before our legislators do anything. Squeezed between powerful business interests and angry voters, the Three Little Senators That Could last week showed that they can't. They can't bring themselves to grant even the most basic of privacy rights to U.S. citizens because it would be inconvenient to require businesses to ask our permissions before spreading around our Social Security numbers. When the going gets tough, the politicians commission a study. That's exactly what they did. 


<p>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>
Since <a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com">Margie Wylie</a> has such a hard time saying what she thinks, email her with your thoughts. She'll post the good stuff. Really, that's a promise.


<p>



