<br>
<a href="/cgi-bin/redirect.cgi?location=http://www.microsoft.com/ie/ad/euprod02.htm%3fportal.ad2">
<img src="/Banners/Portal/Perspectives/msie.perspectives.ptl.banner.gif" border=2 width=100 height=115 align=middle></a>
<br><p>


                <p>                  </td>        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->        </td>                       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->                <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Does Gorby get it?</strong></font><br>              <font face="Arial" size=-1>October 7, 1996</font>    <p><font face="Times">Mikhail Gorbachev and 500 of his closest friends got together last week to talk about how the world's going to hell in a hand basket. Strangely enough, technology was hardly mentioned.<p>I'll be the first to admit that junk email pales in significance next to nukes and ethnic cleansing, but communications technologies like email, cell phones, and the Web have crucial parts to play in the future of the world. Anyone who offers up the increasingly global economy as a reason for world peace, but doesn't understand that this worldwide economy is made possible in part by that Internet thingy kids are so crazy about these days, clearly doesn't get it. Are our aged world leaders really that techno-clueless?<p><img align=left height=102 width=160src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_aged.gif">Maybe the view from my little corner of journalism has skewed my perspective, but it seems to me that so-called technology issues are no longer the exclusive playground of paranoid programmers and conspiracy buffs. Technology questions lurk behind almost all major world issues, including those identified by the Gorbachev Foundation's <a href="http://worldforum.org/">State of the World Forum</a>.<p>How can we stop the flow of arms across borders without dealing with the widely varying encryption policies of all the nations involved? How do we keep encryption from shielding terrorists or arms dealers and still guarantee basic civil freedoms? How are we to deal with the way in which police states use the Internet and other advanced communications to monitor and oppress rather than free their citizens? We all know that access to knowledge will determine wealth and power in the coming years, yet there was little talk of equality of access to advanced communications technologies, for either poor countries or for their poorest inhabitants, usually women and children. <p>How can we halt the fracturing of nation states into fractious groups based on ethnicity, race, gender, socioeconomic classes, racial prejudices, and even sexual orientation when the emerging commercial model for the Web is based on appealing to "communities" of people not joined by geography, but by the very factors that are splitting us apart? <p> <img align=right height=130 width=150src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_lurk.gif"><p>If any of the world leaders at the Forum were aware of the key economic and human rights issues surrounding the cell phones, faxes, and email we use every day, they cleverly disguised it. I asked Bella Abzug, former member of the U.S. House of Representatives, fiery feminist, and one of my childhood idols what part the Internet and other communications technologies could play in leveling the economic playing field for women. Not understanding the question, but still fast on her mental feet, she concocted a vague answer about women moving into the technology fields. When I clarified the question, she just said, "Honey, I don't know about that stuff."<p>She was far from alone. From former Senator Alan Cranston to former Soviet President Gorbachev, the closest anyone in the Forum's main program came to knowing about that stuff was Marian Wright Edelman, the outspoken children's advocate formerly with the Clinton administration, who briefly alluded to how equality of access is crucial to the education and for the future prospects of the world's children.<p>The techno-cheerleaders will say we needn't worry. They say that the Great and Benevolent Market must run its course in order to reveal unto us mere mortals the correct part for technology to play in our lives. So far, the only thing it has revealed are the best ways for a handful of humans to use the rest of us. In most cases, those being most used are the merest of all mortals: poor, uneducated, and unheard. Technology issues are world issues; it's time we embrace them before they steamroll us.<p></font><p><font face="Arial" size=-1>Share your views with <a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com">Margie Wylie</a> in her corner of the journalistic world.<p></font><p><a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>     
<p><p>        </td></tr><tr>        <td valign=top width=120>                <a href="#top"><img border=0 height=37 width=107 src="/Graphics/backtotop.gif"></a>        </td>        <td width=5>       </td>                <td width=465 colspan=2>                <p>             <font size=-1 face="Times"><a href="/copyright.html">Copyright</a> &#169; 1995-97 CNET Inc. All rights reserved.</font>        </td></tr></table></BODY></html>
