<p>

 


 

 

        

       </td>



        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->

        </td>

        







        

       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>
Privacy envy</strong></font><br>



      



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 30, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">

There's a lot I envy the Europeans: month-long vacations, high-speed 
trains, the Prado, and doctors that make house calls. Now it seems I have 
one more thing to envy them: data privacy rights. 
<p>


We may be the land of the free, but when it comes to protecting the basic
rights of our citizens in the Information Age, America is the home of the 
lame. Americans need exactly what Europeans have: a Bill of Data Privacy 
Rights.
<p>

<img align=left height=115 width=172
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_amer.gif">

The jealousy pangs grew particularly acute the last few weeks as I 
watched AOL wage <a href="/News/Item/0,4,3106,00.html">a losing battle 
over junk email</a> and as angry Netizens bombarded 
<a href="http://www.lexis-nexis.com/">Lexis-Nexis</a> with demands 
that the company remove personal information from its P-TRAK research 
service. 
<p>

It would be a lot tougher for either of these travesties to happen in 
the United Kingdom, Germany, or most other European Union member states.
While we're crying into our Cokes over junk email, the Europeans have 
been thinking, writing, and legislating about data protection since the 
1970s, long before the advent of the personal computer. By 1995, that 
thinking had gone into the 
<a href="http://www2.echo.lu/legal/en/dataprot/directiv/directiv.html">
EU Data Protection Directive</a>. Simply put, the document requires member 
states to enact laws that guarantee several rights to their citizens 
including the right to know that personal information is in a database; 
the right to access that information; and the right to correct or erase 
that information entirely.
<p>

These three rights alone would be enough to put an instant end to both 
junk email scourge and the P-TRAK scare. In the United Kingdom, 
<a href="http://www.cyberpromo.com/">Cyber Promotions</a> and Lexis-Nexis 
would be required to register their databases with a government agency. 
They would be required to divulge all that they have stored on people, 
and they would be forced to correct or remove personal information upon 
request. It's the law. 
<p>

	 <img align=right height=128 width=113
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_trak.gif">
Compare that to what's happening with Lexis-Nexis. While the company 
is going above and beyond what is required by law, it is only doing 
the absolute minimum required to avoid more bad PR. Sure, you can ask 
politely to please be removed from the database, but Lexis-Nexis is under 
no obligation to tell you whether your name was there in the first place. 
As a matter of policy, the company also won't tell you if it's removed your 
name. In fact, there's absolutely no law to stop Lexis-Nexis from taking 
all the requests for removal--all those juicy full names, addresses, 
and phone numbers pouring in every single day--and <I>adding</I> them to 
its rosters. 
<p>


Don't get me wrong. European-like data privacy guarantees aren't perfect. 
Some member states are allowed to opt out of huge chunks of them. 
There are loopholes the size of the Louvre in the directive. So far, 
though, those nations which have enacted laws have stuck close to the intent. Is it too much for Americans to ask for a few basic rights in the information age? I say no. If you agree, write your <a href="http://policy.net/capweb/congress.html">Congressional representatives</a>. You can bet <a href="http://www.trw.com/">TRW</a> and Lexis-Nexis already have.
<p>











</font>
<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>

You're always welcome to invade <a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com">Margie Wylie's</a> mailbox.</font> 

<p>


