<br><p>
















                



<p>



  



 



        



       </td>







        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->



        </td>



        















        



       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->











        







        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>A new kind of privacy</strong></font><br>







      







        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 23, 1996</font>











    <p>





<font face="Times">







Should you have the right to keep your whereabouts private?

<p>

If you think that's a vague philosophical question that keeps researchers employed, you'd only be half right, and not about the half you think. The <a href="http://www.fbi.gov/">Federal Bureau of Investigation</a> wants to turn cell phones into tracking devices, right now. And it's perfectly possible. 

<p>

The agency's designs were temporarily <a href="http://www.news.com/News/Item/0,4,3706,00.html">scuttled last week</a>, but that's not the end of the controversy. In the Information Age, "location privacy" is shaping up to be as hotly debated subject as medical or credit records privacy.

<p>

<img align=left height=135 width=128

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_fbi.gif">



"In the past, anyone who knew where you were was usually there with you," says <a href="http://www.ubiq.com/weiser/">Mark Weiser</a>, chief technologist for the <a href="http://www.parc.xerox.com/">Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC)</a>. "Right now, everyone who uses a cellular phone is in effect being tracked. If you're a cellular phone user, your location is known to at least within three kilometers, and with a small amount of work, within ten meters."

<p>

Music to the FBI's ears. The agency claims that under the digital wiretap law passed in October of 1994, it should be able to turn any of the 38.2 million cell phones carried by about 14 percent of the American population into radio collars. Having failed politically, the feds decided to push their luck technically. In a document called the Electronic Surveillance Interface, the FBI tried to, behind closed doors and out of the public eye, strong-arm a bunch of engineers into building real-time surveillance capabilities into every cellular phone.  

<p>



 <img align=right height=175 width=119

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_seiger.gif">



<p>

That Congress has already told the FBI to keep its paws off cell phone location information seems as little a deterrent to the agency as the fact that its director Louis Freeh promised Congress that the FBI wouldn't do exactly what it's doing now. (Maybe we should start calling it the FIB.) 

"Is the FBI making a grab here? Absolutely," says Jonah Seiger, policy analyst with the <a href="http://www.cdt.org/">Center for Democracy and Technology</a>. "But that shouldn't surprise us...and it's not the last we'll be hearing about this." 

<p>

Weiser couldn't agree more. As chief troublemaker at one of the few remaining private research labs dedicated to thinking Big Thoughts, he says that the next wave of computing, ubiquitous computing, will surround us with potential tracking devices. "Location privacy is not a recognized right within the Constitution, in any laws, in any court cases," Weiser says. "And, yet, where you are can be very important." 

<p>





 <img align=left height=145 width=146

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_location.gif">



<p>



Take, for instance, the smart house. Wouldn't a thief like to know who's home? If that's too far out for you, consider this: We're already surrounded. Weiser says that he recently counted 40 microprocessors in his home, and only two were connected to screens. Think you're safe? Start counting, and don't forget about the microwave, dishwasher, stereo, cable box, thermostat, children's toys, telephone answering machine, the garage door opener. You get the idea.

<p>

Weiser may seem like an odd Cassandra since he spends his waking hours creating the technology of ubiquitous computing, but he says he has a moral responsibility to warn us that his inventions, while able to change our lives for the better, aren't harmless. What we do with that information is up to us.



<p>

Strap on your lead helmets, cybernauts. It's going to be an interesting ride.













</font>

<p>



<font face="Arial" size=-1> Whoever pulls <a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com">Margie Wylie</a>'s FBI file better send email. 

 



<p>





<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>







<p>







