       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>No sympathy for spammers</strong></font><br>



      



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 16, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">


I used to think that junk email was an AOL phenomenon. After all, I never use <a href="http://www.aol.com/">America Online</a> for email, yet every time I log on my mailbox is stuffed. "You've got mail!" my computer pipes in cheery, if redundant, English. <p>


<p>


Half the spam, it seems, exhorts me to spam others for fun and profit; a quarter is peddling kooky health aids. The rest seems to be composed of questionable get-rich-quick schemes, psychic readers, and the occasional virtual panhandler. (Yes, I've actually gotten the exact plea for money to fix a shabby home twice with different names and P.O. boxes for sending in your generous donation.) 
<p>

Whatever the message, it's never welcome and I never bother reading all of it. But junk email isn't an AOL problem anymore: It has become an Internet-wide plague. Point in case: less than 24 hours after NEWS.COM went live, I was spammed by the <a href="http://www.animatedgreetings.com/">American Greetings</a> card company! Posting an innocent message in a Usenet group can draw showers of spam. 
<p>

Who are these people? What drives a human being to spam another? These were the burning questions I set out to answer when I called<a href="mailto:wallace @cyberpromo.com"> Sanford Wallace</a>. Wallace is the president of <a
href="http://www.cyberpromo.com"> Cyber Promotions</a>, the "broadcast
emailer" that  AOL is currently
battling</a>. In a <a href="http://infolawalert.com/stories/061496a.html">series of suits</a> that started when Cyber Promotions sued AOL in March, the two have been duking it out over whether Cyber Promotions can have access to send AOL members unsolicited emails. In April, <a href="http://www.sddt.com/files/librarywire/96wireheadlines/04_96/DN96_04_11/DN96_04_11_ff.html"> AOL countersued</a>, and the two are currently wrangling over an order that bans AOL from blocking Cyber Promotions' incoming emails.

<p>
	<img align=right height=165 width=155
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_stick_quote.gif">

By his own account, the president of Cyber Promotions</a> is just an honest
businessman who's being <a href="http://www.news.com/News/Item/0,4,3106,00.html">victimized by
America Online</a>, a powerful corporation that sees him as a competitive threat. Always a sucker for the underdog, I listened on. Wallace has some good points: He doesn't pay to advertise on AOL. They have every reason to want him gone. He allows small business a chance to advertise on the Web for next to nothing, claiming 5,000 satisfied advertising customers. AOL doesn't like that one bit, he says. I was crumbling.
<p>
So, what about all those people who've complained in AOL forums and Usenet groups that they can't get off his lists? Was it technical problems? Growing pains? Surely he was sorry for the inconvenience he had caused? No doing. "At this point, we're not apologizing to anyone," said Wallace. It might be easier to have sympathy for Wallace's plight if he didn't justify broadcasting 2.6 million emails across the Internet each day with the reasoning that it's not illegal, so it must be OK. 
<p>
While Wallace plays Eddie Haskell to the courts and the press--"That's a very nice robe you have on today, Your Honor"--Cyber Promotions is unabashedly swamping email users with its pitches. <p>
<p>
Wallace claims that Cyber Promotions' tactics aren't illegal, but they surely are disruptive and expensive for everyone but his company. By his own admission, Cyber Promotions sends out over 900,000 email messages a day to AOL subscribers alone and claims to have a total list of 1.3 million names and addresses. 
<p>
   	
"Nobody likes being called in the middle of their dinners by MCI," Wallace says, the point being that we get called anyway. Well, yes and no. The difference between MCI and Cyber Promotions is that if I tell MCI to put me on their "no call" list, the company has to do it, under penalty of law. With Cyber Promotions I'm depending on the company's good will. 
<p>
Wallace says that he's only trying to make an honest living and that people on his list <i>ask</i> to be there. They appreciate the service, he says. (A quick count of one month of my junk email, however, shows that around a quarter of it came from Cyber Promotions' domain. I have neither asked for, nor do I appreciate, the company's attention.) Wallace says the company stopped "harvesting" email addresses in February. Since then, all the additions are volunteers, he claims. <p>

Wallace claims that anyone who wants to desert Cyber Promotions' list can just send email
to an address included in every message (<a href="mailto:remove@cyberpromo.com"> remove@cyber-promo.com</a>). Tell that
to<a href="http://www.ca-probate.com/cyberpro.htm"> Mark Welch</a>, a lawyer who has posted a running list of complaints on this score.  He and many AOL members have complained that getting off Cyber Promotions' list is about as easy as making a comment on its Web site, where you can check one of two buttons, like it or love it. Emails are blithely ignored, they say. Wallace says that there's been "confusion" between the company and some 750 subcontractors who run servers in the cyberpromo.com domain. 
<p>
Wallace does a little linguistic tiptoeing around the issue, but what it all boils down to is this: If you want off all of their lists, you'd better find each one individually. All the while, Wallace has no real legal obligation to actually remove anyone from any list.
<p>
Wallace's responsible-corporate-citizen routine even extends to joining the <a href="http://www.bbb.org">Better Business Bureau</a> of Eastern Pennsylvania where the company has only ever had two complaints, both resolved satisfactorily.
<p>
Seems, real-world apathy keeps hundreds of mouse potatoes moaning into their monitors instead of dialing up the local BBB (703-247-9311) to voice their complaints. Holly Cherico, counsel for the Better Business Bureau's national organization, says the BBB will start taking online complaints at its Web site soon. 
<p>
There's been talk about extending the <a
href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/47/227.html">Telephone Consumer Protection Act </a>, the law that outlaws junk faxes and unwanted telephone solicitations, to email. Junk faxes today can carry a minimum penalty of $500 per occurrence. In fact, <a href="http://techsearch.techweb.com/cgi-bin/article?doc_id=NTG19960301S0030">some people</a> even argue that the law can already be applied to email, though there's been no test case. Outlawing
junk email would give us a stick, but how do we hit an invisible target? 

<p>
Wallace has admitted to doing exactly what other junk mailers do. They use
fake return addresses. He claims that he wouldn't want anyone to
"accidentally" reply to Cyber Promotions when they really should reply to
the advertiser on whose behalf Wallace is spamming. The truth is that many junk
email operations are run out of town on the virtual rails after enraged
spammees complain to their ISPs or mail bomb their servers. (Wallace admits Cyber Promotions has already lost service from four ISPs, but he says that's AOL's fault.)
<p>
In fact, Cyber Promotions recently got into a spot of legal trouble when it used "reply.net" as a dummy return address. Unfortunately, it wasn't really fake. It belongs to another Net entrepreneur who sued Cyber Promotions when its adoring audience paralyzed <a href="http://www.replynet.com">ReplyNet's </a>servers with angry emails. Cyber Promotions settled the suit out of court, but Wallace still claims that it was all a typo.
<p>
Whatever we do about junk email, one thing is for certain, the Cyber Promotions of the world will keep pushing their luck and pushing our buttons until someone bigger stops them. Maybe that's AOL, maybe that's the law. The<a href="http://www.ftc.gov/"> Federal Trade Commission</a> has been giving issues like junk email a good, hard look. And maybe it's about time Congress did too. For now, though, it's hard to have any sympathy for junk emailers who keep spamming because we can't make them stop.
<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>
Have some sympathy for<a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com"> Margie Wylie</a>, who sorted through a mountain of spam in order to write this column. Tell her what you think about junk email.



<br>
</font>

<p>


<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>     



<p>



<p>



<p>

        </td>













</tr>





