<a href="/cgi-bin/redirect.cgi?location=http://www.microsoft.com/ie/ad/euprod02.htm%3fportal.ad2">
<img src="/Banners/Portal/Perspectives/msie.perspectives.ptl.banner.gif" border=2 width=100 height=115 align=middle></a>
<br><p>


<!--[Put in the left column bar library]-->                <p>                  </td>        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->        </td>                       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->                <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Who the hell does the IANA think it is?</strong></font><br>                <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 4, 1996</font>    <p><font face="Times">I'll let you in on a little secret about the Internet: The Powers That Be, aren't.<p>The<a href="http://www.iana.org/"> Internet Assigned Numbers Authority(IANA)</a>--the committee that has zillion-dollar companies like PepsiCostanding in line for registrations at the<a href="http://www.internic.net/">InterNIC</a>, like so many slobs at the DMV--doesn't have the authority of aJehovah's Witness at the Vatican. <p>Nobody really cared when the stakes were so low, but with domain namesfetching $50,000 price tags and trademark squabbles breaking out all overthe Internet, people are starting ask just why the hell the three-personboard should control the explosive and potentially lucrative business ofdomain names.<p>        <img align=left height=150 width=115src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_iana_quote.gif">The IANA has decided to conjure out of thin air some very valuableintellectual property.  Starting next year, it proposes to create 50 newtop-level domains (TLDs) to help sate some of the .com-envy going around.(TLDs are indicated by the last three letters of an Internet address.)<p><p>There needs to be more room for international, short, and easy-to-guessdomain names on the Internet, and the IANA has always assigned TLDs in thepast. The problem is the IANA intends to sell these names, unlike .com,which it gave away. The plan has set off a firestorm of controversy thatboils down to one question: Where does IANA get the exclusive authority topass out international-level TLDs?  Once sanctioned by the <ahref="http://www.nsf.gov/">National Science Foundation</a>, the IANAauthorized the InterNIC to assign the Internet's only existing TLDs thataren't geographically specific, like .com and .net. (The only other officialTLDs available end in a country abbreviation, like telegraph.co.uk.) Overthe last few years, however, the committee has quietly slid into the privatesector. Today, the IANA is under the umbrella of a membership tradeorganization called the Internet Society.<p>Under the proposed plan, applicants have to first prove they have theequipment and personnel to run the registry, then they pay $2,000 up frontas well as funnel two percent of their profits back into the pockets of the IANA.Over the next four years, the IANA could create as many as 200 new top-leveldomains. Take your shoes off: That's $400,000 just for starters. I doubtthat reaching $1million will take long. What will the IANA do with the potentialmillions in profits? According to IANA head Jon Postel, they'llreplace some aging root servers, those computers that match up Internetnames with physical addresses, and lighten the fiscal burden that's beenborne by the volunteers who today maintain them.<p>Eugene Kashpureff and Karl Denninger don't buy Postel's explanation because they suspect the IANAof their own motives: to get rich off the Internet. Like a gold rusher inthe old West, <a href="http://www.alternic.net/">Alternic</a>presidentKashpureff has staked his claim to a long list of TLDs by setting up his owncompeting root servers, and is selling TLD registries like .biz to peoplelike Denninger, president of <a href="http://www.mcs.net/">MCS Net</a>.<p>        <img align=right height=135 width=140src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_millions_quote.gif">"Let's say I take up residence in Grant Park here in Chicago and I startselling off pieces of the grass for $1 a square.  Do I have the right to dothat because people will pay me?" asks an outraged Denninger. The rootservers "were developed by the federal government. That makes them a publicgood. Under the laws of the United States, this is public property," Denninger says.The two don't object to IANA selling TLDs; they just thinkthey should get an equal shot at the profits.  As long as IANA controls the "official"root servers, Kashpureff's domains will never be successful.<p>As much as I sympathize with Denninger and Kashpureff's arguments, I can'tagree with their conclusions. Domain names can't just be colonized byvirtual homesteaders. If everyone decides to run their own root servers, thedomain name system will collapse. Top-level domains--especially international TLDs--have to be parceled out in a fair, democratic and impartial process.  The IANA is the closest thing we've got right now.<p>On the other hand, the IANA, smug in its position as the Giver of Law, hasrefused to answer the partner's pointed requests that it publish itsbudget, make clear how its board is elected and, most of all, provide aprocess for public feedback and accountability. <p>For example, the IANA will form a committee to judge and award contracts toadminister domains worth potentially millions of dollars to a contractor,yet it hasn't divulged how those committee members will be chosen.Nor will it say how the committee will fairly choose between two partieswho apply for the same TLD name.  Also, what route of appeal do the losers have?Postel says that the Internet community has trusted IANA in the past andshould trust them in the future. But with so much at stake, that's not enoughanymore.<p>        <img align=left height=172 width=135src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_doubt_quote.gif">I doubt the IANA has any nefarious intent to abuse a public trust, but it does expect too much trust from the public. Perhaps Robert Shaw, adviser to the United Nations' <ahref="http://info.itu.org.br/">International Telecommunications Union</a>, put itbest.  In a <a href="http://www.itu.int/intreg/dns.html">paper</a>presented at a recent conference, he wrote that the IANA was "well-intentionedengineers who have no real legal or policy framework behind them."  Postelmay be right that Shaw and the ITU simply envy the IANA its job, but the ITUjust might be better equipped to rise to the challenge. With all theproblems I've mentioned, I didn't even touch on the thorny issues ofinternational trademark disputes.<p>The issue of international TLDs has pulled back the curtain on the great and powerful Internet.  We can't just ignore the all-too-human handful of people running the show.  Like many of the pseudo-governmental committees left over from the NSF, the IANA has to rise to the occasion of administering a commercialized Internet in the public interest.  If it can't, it has to offer that trust to an agency betterequipped to administer it in a democratically responsible manner.  Not, asDenninger and Kashpureff would hope, to them.</font><p><font face="Arial" size=-1>Email comments to:  <a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com">Margie Wylie</a><br></font><p>

<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>     
<p><p>        </td></tr><tr>        <td valign=top width=120>                <a href="#top"><img border=0 height=37 width=107 src="/Graphics/backtotop.gif"></a>        </td>        <td width=5>       </td>                <td width=465 colspan=2>                <p>        <font face="Times" size=-1>        <a href="/copyright.html">Copyright</a> &#169; 1995-97 CNET Inc. All rights reserved</font>        </td></tr></table></BODY></html>
