       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Are you lost in your intranet space?</strong></font><br>



      



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>October 8, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">

A new product from <a href="http://www.intermind.com">Intermind</a> 
is being introduced today that could help solve one of the major problems 
with running your intranet: helping your users or audience find the latest 
content that you add to your Web site.
<p>




To explain, I'd like to go back in time about three years. Before the 
Web was a household name, the computer game <i>Myst</i> was getting lots 
of attention. I'll confess that even though I have never been much of a fan 
of computer games, I was a <i>Myst</i> addict for several weeks, trying in 
vain to figure out all of its clever puzzles and pathways
<p>

<img align=left height=151 width=148
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_how.gif">


Playing <i>Myst</i> is a good metaphor for how your users navigate your 
intranets. A lot of times your users don't really know how they got to a 
particular page, or how to get back to their starting point. Users 
shouldn't be expected to understand your underlying site design, but 
they are supposed to get something out of the experience other than 
patience practice. You have to learn how to design the site for a wide 
range of interests and skill levels.
<p>

I stopped being interested in <i>Myst</i> once I bought the cheater book 
and worked my way through the game. Too bad there isn't such a book for 
your intranet site. Yet there is this software from Intermind called 
Communicator. It's available now for Windows NT and 95 running with 
<a href="http://www.netscape.com/">Netscape</a>'s Navigator or 
<a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a>'s Internet Explorer, 
coming soon for 16-bit Windows. (Pricing information was unavailable 
last week, so check the company's Web site for more information.)
<p>

What the Intermind software does is allow you to publish a road map
to your Web site. You assemble links to various pages, and arrange them 
into categories or topics. If you have a certain place on your site that 
changes often, you can publish these updates and point your users right 
at them. Once you get your links assembled into a file called a 
hyperconnector, you place the file on your server. (It is quite small, 
only a few kilobytes.)
<p>

	
Now you're ready to set up things so that all your users download 
the Intermind software and add it to their browsers. Once this is done, 
Intermind's Communicator will periodically check your site to see if a 
new hyperconnector has been published. If there is, it will display it 
in your browser, and presto! Your users now know where to go on your site 
for the latest and greatest stuff.
<p>


Think about this for a minute. Right now, you probably have some fairly 
crude ways of doing this kind of publishing. You can send a mass email, 
telling your users the URL where the new stuff is located. Or you use a 
"what's new" page that has links to specific places around your site that 
have been updated. Or you just hope that the people interested in particular 
topics will eventually find their way to the right information. Intermind 
makes this process much easier.
<p>




Many of the off-line browsers such as 
<a href="http://www.travsoft.com/products/webex/">Webex</a> and 
<a href="http://www.openmarket.com/express">Open Market's Express</a> 
do some of this already; you can set them up to bring you to particular 
pages at certain times. But they are going about their business in a 
rather dumb fashion: they just download all the pages you tell them to 
at this particular time, whether they have changed or not. 
(If you like, you can read more on 
<a href="http://www.computerworld.com/search/AT-html/9609/960923SL39strom.html">
why I don't particularly like these products</a>.) With Communicator, 
you are pushing the news to your users when you change the content. You, 
the publisher, set the schedule. You can think of this product as the 
ultimate in intranet narrowcasting, or truly specialized custom publishing.
<p>


 <img align=right height=112 width=186
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_presto.gif">
Indeed, with hyperconnectors you don't have to limit yourself to 
publishing your own content. You can include links to external pages 
around the Internet that might be of interest to your corporation. 
Say you were recently in the news. You can now locate these pages and 
include them in the next hyperconnector that gets beamed out to userland. 
With offline browsers, this would be difficult.  

<p>
The Intermind Communicator is ingenious. It is also simple enough that 
someone without a great deal of programming knowledge (like me) can put 
together connectors easily. The bad news is that you will have to learn a 
few publishing tricks, settling on a schedule for updating your content 
and sticking to it. You might also try keeping individual topic sections 
to under a dozen, and making them mutually exclusive and exhaustive so that 
it is easy to figure out where particular people might look for specific 
kinds of content.

<p>

The downside to Communicator is that it is new. 
The beta versions that I have been fooling with are buggy (what a surprise),
and getting the whole process to work across the Internet is still a bit 
touchy. But this is less of an issue for intranets, where you have better 
control over your bandwidth and connections. I'll be working more with this 
product, and will let you know what happens when I begin publishing my own 
newsletters using it.

</font>
<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>

Tell <a href="mailto:david@strom.com">David Strom</a> what has changed on your intranet.<br>  
Strom is a <a href="http://www.strom.com">consultant</a> based in Port Washington, New York.</font>
<p>


<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>     



<p>



