<br><p>









                

<p>

 


 

 

        

       </td>



        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->

        </td>

        







        

       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Checked your log files lately?</strong></font><br>



      



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>October 1, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">

If you are running a Web server and haven't yet looked at its log files, now
is the time. Why? Because log files offer all sorts of insights into how your
visitors are using your Web site. Indeed, I think they are perhaps the
single most important piece of feedback that an intranet designer can have.
And, there is plenty of software available that can help you interpret your
logs to better understand the way visitors use your Web.
<p>
<img align=left height=136 width=142
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_log.gif">


So what?  "My Web site isn't accessible from the outside Internet,
so why should I care about my visitors?" you say. Your logs are still
important. They
tell you things that you need to know when you have finished putting up your
"version 1.0."  For instance,  who is visiting what pages? How
often? What hyperlinks are broken? This is precisely the kind of stuff
that you need before you begin work on version 2.0.
<p>


So put on your detective hat and let's go take a look. They are
usually in a separate subdirectory underneath the one that contains the Web
server software.  (If you know how to run the Web server administration
program, you can find this location and even change some of the parameters.)
The nice thing about these logs is that they are stored as text files, so
you don't need much software to read them. (The DOS "type" or Unix "cat"
commands along with the file name, or a simple text editor will do).
<p>

Almost every Web server comes with at least one log and usually several
different ones. (There are some exceptions:  The Peer Web servers, which is
what comes with NT Workstation version 4, for example, does not come with
any.) First, there are error logs, which record the broken links and <a
href="http://www.cnet.com/Resources/Info/Glossary/Terms/cgi.html">CGI</a>
scripts that have failed. They also show pages that were requested by
visitors but don't exist on your Web. Now you get to play detective:  errors
such as "page not found" are annoying and should be fixed. Did you mistype a
URL and so have been misdirecting your visitors to a nonexistent page? Or
did someone in the marketing department give people the wrong URL in the
company newsletter? 
<p>

It's your chance to be a hero: Create a file with this "wrong" URL and
have it point to the right place, and your visitors will be happy.  (Here's
a helpful hint: you don't need to duplicate the page's content. Just put a
page with the following tag in it: &#60;meta http-equiv="Refresh"
content="1;URL="correct URL goes here"&#62;.  Your visitors will automatically be
transported to the right place.)
<p>

	
A second kind of log deals with server functions such as starting and
stopping the server. Leave these alone unless your users are complaining
that your Web server seems to be down. 
<p>


Last, there are the access logs. These logs are the real pot of gold at the
end of rainbow: They contain five
pieces of information: <ul> <li>the IP address of each visitor, <li>the date
and time of day that
the visit occurred, <li>the page requested from your Web, <li>how many bytes
of data were transferred, <li> some numerical codes that indicate whether
the hit was completed
or if there was an error. </ul>
<p>

If you use DHCP or BOOTP addressing, or if you use any of the IP/IPX
gateways mentioned in a previous <a href="
http://www.news.com/Perspectives/ds/ds9_17_96.html"> column</a>, then this
first piece of information
won't be of much help. But if each of your users has his or her own
individual IP address, you are in luck.  You now have a record of who
went where when on your Web. 

<p>
 <img align=right height=171 width=160
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_comp.gif">

Wait: There is software that can help. But first you
need to take a look at your Web server's administration software. If there
is a place to change the format of these access logs to what is called
Common Log Format, the logs can be transformed into of reports that even a
line manager can
read and understand. And there are over a dozen
different third-party tools that can be used to produce all sorts of nice
looking graphs and charts. The tool that I use on my own access logs is <a
href="http://www.egsoftware.com">WebTrends</a>. There are others around, and
you can find a nice list of both commercial and shareware products at <a
href="http://www.yahoo.com/Computers_and_Internet/Internet/World_Wide_Web/Se
rvers/Log_Analysis_Tools/">Yahoo</a>. <a
href="http://www.uu.se/Software/Analyzers/Access-analyzers.html">Lars-Owe
Ivarsson's page of analysis tools</a> is also a useful list.  

<p>
These reporting products are very useful: They tell you things such as the
peak times of traffic (down to the hour or day of the week) and the top
requested pages on your Web. Reading them, you might see something
unexpected or learn about how people are navigating your Web. Maybe there is
a page that you thought would be among the top ten but isn't--perhaps the
path to this page is too obscure for anyone to find? You get my drift. Go
back to your design and see where you can do to make it easier for people to
search out topics of interest.

<p>
Or maybe you'll find out that engineers have been reading pages
only supposed to be available for the Human Resources department. Now you
should examine your security scheme and make sure that pages are viewed by the
right people.

<p>
One final thought: Set up your Web software to produce a new log every
month, and run the reports on the first of the month on the previous month's
log. That way you can keep up with what is happening with your Web on a
regular basis.





</font>
<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>

Log your comments, questions, complaints with <a href="mailto:david@strom.com">David Strom</a>.  
Strom is a <a href="http://www.strom.com">consultant</a> based in Port Washington, New York.</font>
<p>



