        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->

        </td>

        







        

       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>The quick and dirty intranet</strong></font><br>



      



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 17, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">

I used to think that the term "intranet" applied to those internal Web
servers popping up all over userland.  Not visible to the rest of us from the
outside Internet, they serve up pages of human resources' manuals and last
quarter's financials. 

<p>

	<img align=left height=125 width=140
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_intra_quote.gif">


Well, that is part of what intranets are all about, but there are
circumstances when, even if  you don't want or need a Web server, you
can still
have a perfectly good intranet. For example, you may not have the expertise
to deploy a
web server right now, or you may not want to put IP everywhere. Or perhaps,
you already have
people that are skilled in running NetWare servers, and don't really want to
learn yet another server operating system (like Unix or NT). 

<p>

If you
are tired of hearing how everyone else has their own Web server, there is a
way to get started without waiting any longer.
Here's how you do it.

<p>


You don't have to do anything to an existing NetWare server for now, but if
you want to
connect it eventually to the Internet, then you should probably go ahead
and modify it to use TCP/IP, the language of the Internet. (Check the box at
right for some products to help you out.) Also, you will have to rewrite
your files in
HTML to make your documents on the server Web-friendly. 

<p>

You can either add an <a
href="http://www.cnet.com/Resources/Info/Glossary/Terms/ip.html">IP</a>
stack to your desktops, or
modify the
Winsock.dll (if you are running Windows) to talk through IPX, Novell's
protocol stack which Novell
includes this as part of their <a
href="http://www.novell.com/intranet_ready/">IntraNetWare solution</a>.  You
can also make use of the products mentioned in the box. 

<p>


Now, run your Web browser. Tell users to bring up their Web pages using the
"open file" command instead of typing in an "http:" address. Guess what?
That's it. You have your intranet and no Web server in sight.


<p>


Indeed, you actually aren't missing much.  Users can still traverse
links embedded in your documents.  The only difference is that they are
file-based instead of
Web-based links. You can still load up your pages with images and sounds,
provided your links refer to mapped drives on your network
(file:/G/document instead of http://servername/document). 

<p>

 
   	<img align=right height=110 width=140
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_html_quote.gif">

Okay, so what's the catch? Well, you can't do a few things. You can't run
<a href="http://www.cnet.com/Resources/Info/Glossary/Terms/cgi.html">CGI</a>
programs and <a
href="http://www.cnet.com/Resources/Info/Glossary/Terms/perl.html">perl
</a>scripts, and that means that forms will be pretty
tough to do. But who cares? Most people don't really want to fill out
forms anyway. And you can't track how people move through your Web since you
don't have any log files. But so what? Who really has the time to write
scripts and analyze these logs anyway? (I am being facetious here: I
actually think logs and forms are very important and key to understanding
how you need to evolve your Web, but that can wait for the full scale
intranet. ) 

<p>



I think this strategy makes perfect sense. It is also somewhat timely, given
<a href="http://www.novell.com/">Novell</a>'s big push this month to package
its various
pieces of software under its IntraNetWare label. The key is beginning to use
HTML as your corporate
document standard.

<p>

This, of course,  will take some doing because most of your documents, I'll
bet, are in
Microsoft Word or
some other word processing format.  Getting them converted won't be easy. You
might want to take a look at <a href="http://www.infoaccess.com">HTML
Transit</a> from InfoAccess. This product can do large-scale
conversions, unlike the toy HTML assistants that Microsoft makes.

<p>
Another suggestion: consider getting a few Macintoshes and using them to add
the multimedia experience to your file-based Webless intranet. Why Macs?
They have the best toolset for adding images, sound, and video to static
text. And since you've already got your NetWare file servers, Macintoshes
 will fit in just fine (as long as you load the Appletalk support properly,
which is
fairly easy to do.) 

<p>
There is one other another situation where a nonWeb intranet  makes sense:
when the
center of the intranet universe is email-based, rather than anything to do
with the Web and HTML. But that topic is for another day.
</font>
<p>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
Email comments to: <a href="mailto:david@strom.com">David Strom</a>.
David Strom is a <a href="http://www.strom.com">consultant</a> based in Port Washington, New York.
</font>

<p>


<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>     




<p>



