       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Making the Web<br>safe for the enterprise</strong></font><br>



   



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 9, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">


I am glad to see so many software and hardware products adopting the Web as
a universal graphical user interface (GUI). Why? Because having a Web GUI is
the best way to build intranets and deploy interoperable, cross-platform
applications across corporate networks. You can deliver information to any
desktop, and all you need is a browser. Forget the network computer, Web
GUIs are the ultimate "thin clients."

<p>

	<img align=left height=123 width=157
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_web_quote.gif">

I've been keeping a lookout for products with Web GUIs, and it is a growing
trend. In fact, it's such a big deal these days that <a
href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a>, <a
href="http://www.cisco.com/">Cisco</a> and
others announced in July the <a href="http://wbem.freerange.com/">Web-Based
Enterprise Management Standards</a> to help the process along. Just
about every software category now has at least one example of software
that has taken to the Web: you can access calendars, groupware, email, and
even 3270 terminal emulators via
an ordinary Web browser. And there are plenty of hardware products too,
including printers
and routers, that now come with their own built-in Web server for management
purposes.  
<p>


  


Software developer Bruce Fram, who runs his own Silicon Valley company,
Relations Software, agrees with me: "Web technology is the
information mechanism of the 90s," he said.  Application developers who are
not using it as their primary end-user interface will be in the same position as
scribes after the invention of the printing press." 




<p>



 

For developers, there is an important cross-platform advantage for having
Web interfaces: software vendors can cancel their Mac and Unix development
efforts and concentrate on figuring out new ways to shoehorn functions into
HTML tags. Web GUIs are a plus for users, too.  There is always the hope that
Web GUIs will simplify training users on how to do things, because they only
have to point and click rather than having to learn a new command
syntax or menu structure.wn but to manage.



<p>



Take computerized calendars, for example. Before Web GUIs, you had to go
through a messy synchronization step just moments before catching your
flight out of town. Now you can leave your data on your server and view it
with your browser, and more importantly, actually have a chance at keeping
your calendar updated. You can be across town or sitting at another desk
across the floor, it doesn't matter. This saves time and makes a great deal
of sense.

<p>


	<img align=right height=150 width=175
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_hasten_quote.gif">

And network management functions also benefit from having Web access.  <a
href="http://www.cai.com/"> 
Computer Associates'</a> Unicenter TNG product and <a
href="http://www.tek.com/">Tektronix</a>'s color printers 
can both be managed from their respective Web interfaces, meaning that
network administrators have more flexibility when it comes time to make
adjustments and keep track of problems. 




<p>


   

Web GUIs aren't always the best solution, however. "Writing HTML interfaces
means that software developers tend to develop to the lowest common
denominator," says Elizabeth Rosenzweig, a usability manager with Kodak's
Boston Development Center in Lowell,  Massachusetts. That could be trouble. But
certainly any graphical interface is better than the cryptic telnet
command-line interfaces used to manage routers and other hardware devices.
Others are even less thrilled: Alan Cooper, a user interface consultant in
Menlo Park, California, thinks that "HTML has set computer programming back 30
years and is about the worst technology I've laid eyes on." 

<p>

 
Well, let's not get too carried away. There are some instances where having
a Web browser doesn't make a lot of sense.  Novell's first implementation of
GroupWise Web Access, for example, doesn't do much for me:  users get only a
slim subset via the Web of the functionality that is available on either the
Windows or Mac clients.ter, if you will. Sony, meanwhile, this week started shipping
its consumer PCs. 


<p>



Nevertheless, the Web is here to stay and Web GUIs are an overall positive
development. Ironically,  having more software go to the Web user interface
might hasten an all-Windows world as  multiplatform applications, 
supported by back-door HTML, encourage developers to move away from
Everything Else and concentrate on Everything Windows. 
<p>
</font>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Email comments to:  <a href="mailto:david@strom.com">David Strom</a>.   David Strom is a <a
href="http://www.strom.com">consultant</a> based
in Port Washington, New York. 
</font>



<p>

