<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Security blankets</strong>

</font>

<br>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>January 6, 1997</font><br>

<p>
<font face="Times">
<p>



<p>
Last week's news that <a href="http://www.nortel.com/">Northern Telecom</a>
is spinning off a unit that sells software to issue digital certificates is
an important sign that the market for Internet commerce is maturing.
<p>
Security is closely intertwined with Internet commerce. For the Net to
become a thriving commercial medium, it must be not only secure but also 
perceived to be secure.
<p>
Most talk of Internet security focuses on sending credit cards numbers
safely across the Net. That's key for consumers but largely irrelevant for
<img height=91 width=160 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_intertwine.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>businesses. Companies that want to use Internet technologies either
internally on intranets or externally to trade information with suppliers,
customers, and partners face different security issues including data
integrity and access control.
<p>
And the corporate market is what Nortel, the big Canadian manufacturer of
telephone switches, is targeting by making its network security
division a separate company. <a href="http://www.entrust.com/">Entrust
Technologies</a> sells its Entrust public-key infrastructure  software
so customers can issue and manage digital certificates.
<p>
<img height=93 width=139 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_outsiders.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
Nortel is opening up a new option for companies. While well-known <a
href="http://www.verisign.com/">VeriSign</a> and <a href="http://www.gte.com/">GTE's <a
href="http://www.cybertrust.gte.com/">CyberTrust</a> emphasize services
that issue electronic IDs for companies, Entrust will let companies that
want to use digitalcertificates on their intranets or screen visitors to their public Web
sites do the work themselves. 
<p>
Entrust Web CA, one of the new company's products, will compete with
certificate servers
from <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> and <a
href="http://www.netscape.com/">Netscape Communications</a>, but Entrust's
real focus is on enterprisewide corporate networks, not the public Web. For
now, its product has more features than either Microsoft's or Netscape's.
<p>

This is an advantage for companies that want to issue their own
certificates, instead of relying on an outside agency to guard
mission-critical data.
<p>

</font>


<P>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc1_6_97b.html">

