<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif"></a>























<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->

<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Why I/Pro imploded</strong>

</font>

<br>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 23, 1996</font><br>

<p>

<font face="Times">

This column is not a success story about an Internet start-up. It's a cautionary tale of how one promising company, <a href="http://www.ipro.com/">Internet Profiles</a>, stumbled. It is told here with I/Pro's cooperation. Not that it's the only new Internet company to retrench in recent months; more will soon. <p>

Successes like <a href="http://www.netscape.com/">Netscape</a> and <a href="http://www.yahoo.com/">Yahoo</a> grab a lot of headlines, but these high-profile firms do not typify the reality of most Net start-ups. 

I/Pro's story offers another perspective on keeping up with a fast-moving market, and its mistakes illuminate difficulties that have and will afflict other firms, too. <p>

<img height=102 width=128 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_toomuch.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>Despite a series of miscues that began to emerge in August, we shouldn't count I/Pro out yet, though. Founder Ariel Poler no longer runs the company, and CEO Mark Ashida is leaving as well. A work force that once numbered 109 is down to 69 and may well drop further. An aggressive competitor, <a href="http://www.netcount.com/">NetCount</a>, is making inroads into the market. But the firm has $8 million in the bank, an impressive customer list, and remains the Web's leading auditor and counter of traffic at Web sites. <p>

I have followed I/Pro since its public debut in April 1995 and have written both puffy profiles and bad-news stories, learning more about the company than most outsiders. <p>

I/Pro exists because Web sites want to sell ads and because ad buyers want to know, at a minimum, how many people see their ad banners. I/Pro's first service, I/Count, looks at the "log files" of Web sites to determine how many pages (and ad banners) the site has served up to visitors. Its other main service, I/Audit, verifies whether Web sites have as much traffic as its Webmasters say they do. <p>

Poler recognized this emerging market in the summer of 1994 after he tried to sell restaurant ads on a Web site and had prospects question who would spot the ads. Shortly after, I/Pro was born, the first third-party service to count how many times an ad banner is seen. <p>

As an early entrant in the ad services arena, I/Pro did a lot to promote Web advertising as an industry. "We tried to do too much too fast," Poler said. "If you are a leader in the space, you have to help build an industry where all the pieces are missing. We thought, 'If we don't provide those pieces, the industry won't grow and the core business won't grow.' We found ourselves with more than we could handle." <p>

<img height=91 width=153 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_automate.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>But the company got distracted, as management's attention was pulled away from its core business. That lies at the root of I/Pro's troubles, but other mistakes were made along the way. <p>

I/Pro moved into other businesses instead of concentrating on its key counting and auditing services. A detour into a universal registration scheme called I/Code burned cash. Chairman David Carlick, an early I/Pro investor, said the company spent $3 to $4 for every I/Code registrant, who signed up once and then shared that data with participating Web sites. As I/Pro wanted 2 million registered users for critical mass, expenses mounted. In August, I/Pro pulled the plug on I/Code and on many employees in that division. <p>

Looking to make itself a central resource for Web marketers--its target customers--the company bought <a href="http://www.cyberatlas.com/">CyberAtlas</a>, a Web site with pointers to Internet marketing information all around the Net. CyberAtlas founder Michael Tchong came too, but he too was cut loose in the last round of layoffs. <p>

</font>



<P>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>

<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc12_23_96b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>

</td>

<td width=3>

</td>
























































































































































































































































































































































































































































































































































