&nbsp;















































</td>































































































































































<td valign=top width="305" align=left>























<!----------- SECTION NAME ---->










<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">
<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif">
</a>









<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->















<font face="Arial" size=+2>







<strong>Who can you trust?</strong>







</font>































<br>































<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 16, 1996</font><br>































<p>















































<font face="Times">

Trust--not technology, money, or available merchandise--remains the
missing element in Internet commerce.
<p>
Consider these developments last week at the Internet World trade show in
New York:
<p>
<li>"Purveyors of electronic commerce are going to have to convince consumers
and executives that they can trust this new way of doing business,"
concluded a report prepared for <a href="http://www.att.com/">AT&T</a> by
San Francisco research firm Odyssey. "Privacy and security concerns
abound--among both consumers and businesses--and relieving those concerns
(both in perception and in fact) is essential to the vitality of electronic
commerce."
<p>
<img height=124 width=85 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_set.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>


AT&T encapsulated the report: "In essence, consumers are ready to buy, but
most businesses are not ready to sell."
<p>
<li><a href="http://www.ora.com/">O'Reilly & Associates</a>, book and Web
publisher turned researcher, defines the problem this way: "Commerce
readiness is an issue of trust, an issue of consumer confidence."
O'Reilly's study found  that just 3,239 of the 648,613 Web sites it queried
electronically are secure enough to be considered commerce-ready.
<p>
"The World Wide Web as an ubiquitous commerce channel remains a vision, not
a reality," O'Reilly concluded. "Substantial opportunity exists for
businesses with sites that engender customer confidence."
<p>
<li><a href="http://www.etrust.org/">eTrust</a>, a joint activity of privacy
advocate of the <a href="http://www.eff.org/">Electronic Freedom
Foundation</a>,
and e-commerce trade group <a
href="http://www.commerce.net/">Commerce.Net</a>, just launched a pilot
program to test three logos it wants Web sites to use to indicate how
carefully they guard personal data received from site visitors. It's about
trusting what happens to information you give a Web site.
<p>
The first two points define the problem; eTrust is part of the solution--but
only part.
<p>
<img height=146 width=102 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_trust.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
It's shocking that, according to O'Reilly, barely 3,200 Web sites have
equipped themselves with both encryption (scrambling to assure that no one
intercepts a message) and authentication (a digital ID that proves the site
is legitimate).
<p>
Granted, most Web sites are marketing tools, not sales efforts. Even so,
O'Reilly's finding means most companies don't understand how important
trust is to selling on the Net, not just selling to consumers but to
businesses, too.
<p>
The biggest players in the trust game, the bank card associations <a
href="http://www.visa.com/">Visa International</a> and <a
href="http://www.mastercard.com/">MasterCard International</a>, are still
on the sidelines. They're now fleshing out a new protocol, Secure
Electronic Transactions, so that credit card numbers can be sent safely
over the
Net.
<p>
But SET's schedule is slipping. Turns out it's harder than the card giants
thought to write a standard that ensures that bad guys can't steal card
numbers. It also will be difficult to implement SET, because it will
require that every consumer and business buying or selling on the Net get a
"digital ID,"  to verify his identity.
</font>

<P>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>







<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc12_16_96b.html">







<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>































</td>















































<td width=3>















</td>















































































































































































































































































<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->















































































































































<td valign=top width=155>































<img border=0 height=185 width=155























src="/Graphics/per_clark_a.gif"><br>











<p>























<img border=0  height=16 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">















<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" 































































width=155 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>































































<tr>     































































<td align=left width=155>































































<span class="shorttakes">















<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">







<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_6_96a.html"><strong>Microsoft's neighborhood</strong></a><br>















If <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> wants to require their OEMs to make certain that upon







shipping, the first screen that pops up is the Windows start-up screen







followed by the default desktop, it certainly seems that this is Microsoft's prerogative. &nbsp; --<a href="mailto:tkozik@msmedia.com">Thom Kozik</a>























<br> &nbsp; <br>























How long do you think Microsoft would last if it didn't do some of the things it does? It's not as if Microsoft is saying, "You must use our software!" They are saying, "Check out our software first, and if you don't







like it, use something you think will do it better!"  So please, can't we







all just get along!  &nbsp;  --<a href="mailto: formula@concentric.net">Daniel Anders Garcia Sanroman</a> 















<br> &nbsp; <br>















<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_5_96a.html"><strong>Stay home</strong></a><br>















I don't always agree with positions taken by the <a href="http://www.ala.org/">American Library Association</a>, 







but in this case, their assessment is accurate. The <a href="htttp://www.packardbell.com/">Packard Bell</a> commercials 







are "subtle, bleak, and ultimately selfish."







<br>







Thousands of...libraries in this country spend millions of dollars every year on computer equipment... I would venture to guess that many librarians will not be 







considering Packard Bell products when they go shopping for new equipment in 1997. &nbsp; --<a href="mailto:Lisa_Paris.IDEA@idea.com">Lisa Paris</a>















<br> &nbsp; <br>







If Margie Wylie's recent column suggested that Microsoft doesn't like public







libraries, I'd like to state for the record: We love them!







<br>







Microsoft has







committed $15 million in cash, software and technical assistance to 215







libraries in the U.S. and Canada to bring the benefits of Internet and PC







technology to underserved communities.












&nbsp;  --<a href="mailto: christhe@microsoft.com">Christopher Hedrick</a>, senior program manager, Microsoft Community Affairs,







<br> &nbsp; <br>













<br> &nbsp; <br>































































