<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>
HP soothes, Sun swaggers</strong>
</font>


<br>        

<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 9, 1996</font><br>

<p>


<font face="Times">





<a href="http://www.hp.com/">Hewlett-Packard</a> <a
href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=HWP">(HWP)</a> unveiled its Internet strategy last week, and I nearly fell asleep.
That was, I believe, the desired reaction.
<p>
Not for me, but for the Fortune 500 computer chiefs HP assembled for a
day-long customer event in San Jose, California. The soothing theme: Don't
lose sleep
over getting your company on the Net. Hewlett-Packard is here to help you. <p>

<img align=left width=116 height=78 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_clear.gif">

The sleeping potion came in the form of droning--about programs, solutions,
alliances,
integration, and frameworks, not to mention frameworks within frameworks.
The "news" of the day was HP's new "Electronic Business Framework" (never
mind that the usual term is "electronic commerce") which included a
"process management development framework," an "AdminFlow framework," and an
"Internet marketing framework." 
<p> 
It was, opined another columnist at my table, "a bit amorphous." 
<p>
But the subliminal message that HP
can take the fear out of the Net will play well in corporate America. This
Net-thing, to paraphrase HP's number-two man Rick Belluzzo, is no
revolution but an expansion of the "extended enterprise" and client-server
computing. Comforting words from an
executive with hundreds of millions of dollars invested in computers not
built around the Internet. 
<p>
HP will mediate technology's Holy Wars  (Unix vs. Windows NT, <a
href="http://www.netscape.com/">Netscape</a> <a
href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=NSCP">(NSCP)</a>
vs. <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> <a href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=MSFT">
(MSFT)</a>, NC vs. PC) to make the
world safe for CIOs, said Belluzzo. "But when it comes time to
deliver IT solutions, those wars can't be delivered to your doorstep."

<p> 
After that reassuring presentation, I retreated to the press room, and
secretly dialed into a <a href="http://java.sun.com/">JavaSoft</a>
teleconference on <I>its</I> electronic commerce strategy. What a contrast. 
<p>
Where HP executives are authoritative but deprecating, <a href="http://www.sun.com/">Sun's</a> <a href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=SUNW"> (SUNW)</a> swagger. And they make better copy. 
<p>
<img align=right width=124 height=143 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_glide.gif">

First Jon Kannegaard, JavaSoft's VP of software, wanted to dispel the
nasty stories that came out of <a href="http://www.comdex.com/comdex/owa/home">Comdex</a> that Microsoft might try
to hijack the Java
train and run off in its own direction. Not so, quoth Kannegaard, JavaSoft
had spoken to the highest level in Redmond and was assured that some
"marketing people" had simply misspoken in Vegas. 
<p> 
Then came some specifics on a Java Commerce Toolkit for Net storefronts,
including a
customizable Java wallet, payment modules for smart cards and credit cards,
and a "shopping cart" applet. We'll know next quarter if JavaSoft can
deliver its promises.   
<p> 
The whole Java story has been a 19-month marketing miracle, adroitly
positioned by Sun's PR handlers and boosted by a good bit of luck. For more
than a few years, Java was
a classic case of technology searching for a
problem to solve. And lo and behold, Sun found the problem right under its
nose: the Internet that it has so influenced for years. 
<p> 


<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc12_9_96b.html">
<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   


</td>


<td width=3>
</td>     
















<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->    













<td valign=top width=155>







<img border=0 height=185 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_clark_a.gif"><br>

<p>


<img border=0  height=16 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">

<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" 



width=155 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>



<tr>     



<td align=left width=155>



<span class="shorttakes">



<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">

<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_5_96a.html"><strong>Two views of the future</strong></a>
Basically, I think it boils down to the two "future
views" we've dealt with since computers became popular.  We could live in a
nice society in which computers help us do many things, and enhance our
contact with other individuals. 
<br>
The other view...is one in which we live in
isolation but, alas, everyone has a nice plastic PC!  Yay.
&nbsp;--<a href="mailto:hijinx@enteract.com"> Paul McAleer</a>


<br>&nbsp;<br>


<strong><a href="/Perspectives/js/js11_08_96a.html">Mickey who?</strong></a>

I love CNET. But I'm not interested in Disney. I much prefer articles on companies that directly affect my life.  I'm referring to major corporations such as AT&T, all the
Bells, Microsoft, etc.  Companies that have so much money and influence that
if they catch a cold, I sneeze.  I figure I have to keep an eye on them. 

<br>




&nbsp;-- <a href="mailto: hmccoy@bigeasy.com ">Helen McCoy</a>




<br>&nbsp;<br>

You may have broken the [Disney] story first, but I'm going to hear about it
over and over from other sources as well simply because it is Disney.

&nbsp; -- <a href="mailto:jackdel@cts.com">Jack DeLong</a>


<br>&nbsp;<br>




<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw11_11_96a.html"><strong>Bullies will be bullies </strong></a>


<br>

What your article refers to as "intimidation and bullying" 
is more commonly referred to in corporate America as "doing 
business."
That the concept of a domain name is somehow deserving of 
a status approaching religious talisman and somehow exempt 
from the same hideous injustices that large corporations 
inflict on everything else that gets in their way is silly.

The Internet is a cluster of computer networks--not a 
utopian experiment, not the astral plane, and certainly 
not a sanctuary from the unconscionable evils of 
capitalism.  Delusions that indicate anything to the 
contrary are just that -- delusions. 
<p>
"The Internet is not TVland," you say?  
Hey, give it time. 

&nbsp;-- <a href="mailto:pent@kcmo.metrobbs.com">Pete Thomas</a>,
Lawrence, KS



<br>&nbsp;<br>


<a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com"><strong>What's your Perspective?</strong>
<br></a>
Got a point of view you'd like to share? NEWS.COM wants your Perspective. Email your rantings to opinions editor <a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com">Margie Wylie</a> to be considered for our guest editorial spot, the Soapbox. Please keep it under 1,200 words and type "soapbox" in the subject line.


</font>


