<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>
VeriFone: The next Microsoft?</strong>
</font>


<br>        

<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 2, 1996</font><br>

<p>


<font face="Times">


<a href="http://www.verifone.com/">VeriFone</a> <a href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=VFI">(VFI)</a>, a growing force in
the online payments industry, is positioning itself to become as ubiquitous and powerful in its niche as <a
href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> is in PC software.   
<p>
Two questions arise: Can VeriFone pull it off? Is it a good thing for the budding electronic 
commerce industry if it does? <p>

VeriFone makes 65 percent of those card-swipe machines that real-world retailers use to ring up a 
purchase on your credit card. That makes VeriFone a known quantity with two crucial constituencies 
for making e-commerce work: banks and retailers. Therein lies its strength. <p>

Microsoft, <a href="http://www.netscape.com/">Netscape</a>, and <a href="http://www.Oracle.com/">Oracle</a>--
the Net's Big Three of software--are already cozying up to VeriFone. Microsoft is literally building 
VeriFone's "cash register" software into Merchant Server, its Web storefront software. 

<p>


<img align=right width=131 height=93 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_deliver.gif">

When Microsoft needs bankers, VeriFone delivers. Nine major banks and credit card processing firms, a sector Bill Gates once referred to as "dinosaurs,"
showed up when Gates unveiled Merchant Server October 30. 
<p> 

VeriFone has been pursuing the Internet opportunity since mid-1995. First it invested in Internet payment firm <a
href="http://www.cybercash.com/">CyberCash</a>; then it bought Internet consulting firm Enterprise Integration Technologies (EIT) and turned it
VeriFone's Internet division. 
<p>
On another front, VeriFone this fall launched a campaign for smart cards, those credit-card sized cards with an embedded chip. It unveiled low-cost smart
card terminals for homes so consumers can download cash onto their cards, and then introduced a portable smart card reader so cab drivers, dry cleaners,
and newsstands can accept smart cards as well as cash. 

<p>

<img align=left width=118 height=119 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_snit.gif">
The trouble with VeriFone's bid in electronic payments, and for Wall Street in evaluating VeriFone as an investment, is that it's hard to sort out
whether it's a hardware company or a software company. 

<p>

It's easy to see how VeriFone, which designs, produces, and markets cheap, reliable merchant card readers, might do well in smart card terminals.
Becoming an Internet software firm, even with the EIT acquisition, isn't so easy.  
<p> 

Roger Bertman, general manager of VeriFone's Internet unit, argues that even its physical-world countertop 
business involves plenty of software. 
<p>


"We sell terminals, but the value in those terminals is as much software as hardware," says 
Bertman.


<p>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>

<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc12_2_96b.html">
<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   


</td>


<td width=3>
</td>     
















