<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->









<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>
Is cyberspace a place?</strong>
</font>





<br>        










<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 25, 1996</font><br>














<p>











<font face="Times">










It's become a wrongheaded convention among journalists and the people 
we interview to refer to various online media as "cyberspace." 
Unfortunately, it's a sign of intellectual laziness that fundamentally 
misrepresents what the Internet, online services, and even interactive 
TV are today and can become.

<p>













"Cyberspace" is a metaphor, and metaphors can aid or hinder understanding. 
This one muddles our thinking and, worse yet, misleads people who aren't 
online by building expectations that cannot be met and fears they need not 
have. 

<p>





<img align=left height=91 width=113 


src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_place.gif">





"Hacker" is a metaphor too, but I won't give it up. Ditto for 
"agents" and "wallets." But I'm growing more dubious about two other 
words that I haven't banned from my writing yet: "storefronts" and 
"firewalls." As a reporter who covers Internet commerce and security, 
I'm not sure what I'd do without them. More on that later, but first my 
take on cyberspace: 

<p>




















The Net is not a place; it's a means of communication. We don't talk 
about the telephone as if it existed in some dimension separate from 
the one where we eat, work, sleep, and play. It's just a device to 
communicate, mostly with other people but also with voice mail machines 
and automated systems that have us punching keypad buttons till our index 
fingers ache. (We may call the experience "voice mail hell," but do we 
really think of it as a place?)
 
<p>
















<img align=right height=119 width=130 


src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_aid.gif">






The cyberspace metaphor mystifies a rather straightforward  
concept. Recently, I asked my friend Magdalena Yesil, an 
entrepreneur-in-waiting since leaving 
<a href="http://www.cybercash.com/">CyberCash</a> 
a couple months back: When will the Net have arrived as a 
mainstream phenomenon? 

<p>






It arrived 15 years ago for academics and researchers who used it in 
their work, she replied. It will be mainstream when her school-age son 
can log on from home, go to the school's Web site, and pick up a homework 
assignment he forgot to bring home. (They may actually do that in Palo Alto, 
where she lives, but I think it's early even in Silicon Valley.)

<p>


That's classic communication integrating the Internet into an everyday 
situation, like flipping on the TV after dinner or picking up the phone 
to call a friend. Calling it cyberspace won't make it happen sooner. 

<p>


Now, "storefront" is a different metaphor. What the heck else are 
we going to call a Web site that sells stuff? We could refer to them as 
"Web catalogs," a better description of what they are today, but the 
catalog metaphor limits what online shopping can become.</font>





<p>





<font face="Arial" size=-1>





<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc11_25_96b.html">




<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   




</td>












<td width=3>

</td>     














<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->    












<td valign=top width=155>






<img border=0 height=185 width=155 




src="/Graphics/per_clark_a.gif"><br>






<p>













<!--<table width=155 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 bgcolor="#FFFFCC" 


border=0>





	




<tr>	












<td colspan=2>








<img border=0 height=16 width=155 




src="/Graphics/per_yourturn.gif">




</td>


</tr>











<tr>









<td width=72 valign="top" align="left">	








<a href="/Polling/Entry/0,1,25,2,00.html">		







<img border=0 align=left height=52 width=72 






src="/Graphics/per_poll.gif"></a>		











</td>



		











<td width=83 valign="center" align="center">










<font face="Arial" size=-1>		






<strong>


<a href="/Polling/Entry/0,1,25,2,00.html">







<p>







This 

is the Poll title.</strong></font></a><br>









<p>







</td>





</tr>	













<tr>		












<td width=72 valign="center" align="center">



		








<a href="/Quizing/Entry/1,32,2,00.html">	











<p>











<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<strong>This is the Quiz 

title.</strong>

</font>






</td>		









<td width=83 valign="top" align="right">	




<img border=0 align=left height=52 width=72 




src="/Graphics/per_quiz.gif"></a><br>  






