<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>
No JFKs in Silicon Valley</strong></font>


<br>        






<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 13, 1996</font>








<p>







<font face="Times">







The notion that Silicon Valley will emerge as a new political force is
laughable.

<p>









That delusion, some call it a hope, follows the high-tech industry's
investment of $40 million in a campaign to defeat Proposition 211, a
California
measure initiated by trial lawyers that would have made it easier to sue 
not just corporations, but their executives, for stock fraud.

<p>








<img align=left height=141 width=124
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_ceos.gif"> 





Prop. 211 was a loaded gun pointed at the heads (and wallets) of Silicon
Valley CEOs who responded appropriately: They bought the election.
That's how initiative politics is practiced here in the Golden State.











<p>








Now that Prop. 211 has been handily defeated, however, don't look to
Silicon Valley CEOs for political inspiration. This group doesn't understand
politics and they don't want to.

<p>








Without bogeyman Bill Lerach,
high-tech CEOs will get bored with politics. Politics takes compromise,
networking, supporting allies on
issues even when you don't care about them. It takes recognizing that the
world
is not black and white but shades of gray. Picture <a
href="http://www.sun.com/">Sun Microsystems</a> chief Scott McNealy
chatting with a local school board candidate in the woefully underfunded
school district where Sun makes its headquarters.  Visualize <a
href="http://www.netscape.com/">Netscape's </a> Marc Andreessen patiently
explaining the World Wide Web to a lawmaker from Montana. Are you getting
anything? Me neither.

<p>




<img align=right height=99 width=159
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_jihad.gif"> 






Don't let the well-publicized "high-tech CEOs for Clinton" boomlet fool
you either. A noteworthy trend in 1992, high-tech Clinton supporters created
barely a ripple this year because the 1992 "trend" was more about prestige
and a
generational-affinity than about politics.

<p>







The anti-211 effort, on the other hand, was more Jihad than a political
campaign, with trial lawyers in general, and William Lerach in particular, as
Silicon Valley's Great Satan. Lerach did what everyone does here  in
California to get a proposition on the state ballot:  spend a couple of
million dollars.   Lerach wanted to make California safe for lawyers who
file class action lawsuits when a company's stock price falls unexpectedly.

</font>





<p>




<font face="Arial" size=-1>



<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc11_13_96b.html">


<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   

</td>








<td width=3>
</td>     










