<!-----------SECTION NAME---->



<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">
<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif"></a>


<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Fat wallet syndrome</strong></font><br>        





<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 6, 1996</font>



































































































    



<p>



















































<font face="Times">



































The fat wallet problem has bedeviled me for years, wearing holes in the hip

pockets of my trousers. But I've seen a solution, and it's not more durable

denim. It's smart cards, the smartest technology never to catch on in the

United States.





<p>





Please, don't stop me if you've heard this before. You have.



<p>



































<img align=left height=88 width=170








src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_thin.gif"> 



"It's been the big thing of the next year for the last ten years," says Bill

Melton, founder of <a href="http://www.verifone.com/">VeriFone</a> as well as cofounder and CEO of <a href="http://www.cybercash.com/">CyberCash</a>, two companies with keen interest in smart cards.





<p>



































A smart card looks like a standard bank card, but instead of having a

magnetic stripe on the back that contains your vital financial information,

it has an embedded memory chip and microprocessor. In other words, as its

name proclaims, it's a lot smarter.





<p>



































My billfold is filled with single-use cards with magnetic stripes: driver's

license, Pacific Bell calling card, auto club card, health

insurance card, Visa cards, ATM card, Macy's card, and frequent flyer card. I'm not counting the two that use UPC

scanner bars and the stack of little-used cards I keep in a drawer because

my wallet won't hold them all. No wonder all my jeans have holes in the

right pocket. I want a thin wallet, not a thin client.

























<p>



All those could conceivably be put on the same chip card (a more generic

term than smart cards) along with what the bankers called "stored value,"

or electronic cash.





<p>



















































<img align=right height=127 width=155








src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_smart.gif">












Here's the idea: Instead of carrying cash for taxicabs when you visit New

York City, you just download "stored value" onto your smart card from a

bank ATM or even from your own PC. Then you hand your smart card to the

cabbie and have the fare deducted. No worries about whether the driver will

have proper change.



<p>



Before you can execute that sunny scenario, however, a lot of

infrastructure must be built. You need access to a smart card terminal

to download digital cash from your bank account. That cabbie needs a

smart card reader to deduct the fare from your card. 



<p>























</font>



















<p>



































<font face="Arial" size=-1>

















































<!--<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives_suzanne.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>-->  



<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc11_06_96b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   





<p>






<p>



<p>





</td>

       
<td width=5 rowspan=2>



       </td>     









<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->  

  





<td valign=top rowspan=2 width=155>





<img border=0 height=185 width=155 



src="/Graphics/per_clark_a.gif"><br>



<p>


<img border=0  height=16 width=155 



src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">

<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" width=155 



cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>


<tr>     


<td align=left width=155>


<span class="shorttakes">



<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">

<strong>Smart cards not so smart</strong></a>

<br>

The reason I use Visa, MasterCard, or American Express instead of a debit card is the possibility of an error. With a smart card, the cash is gone. With a credit or cash card, you get to review every purchase 20 days later to ensure bogus purchases aren't listed. 
&nbsp;--Doug Ross, dir@worldnet.att.net, 11/6/96
	
<br>&nbsp;<br>








<a href="/Perspectives/Perspectives/mw/mw10_28_96.html"><strong>Copywrong 1996</strong></a>
<br>






If they are going to make it that difficult to use a
computer, 

I'll just quietly turn it off for the last time and put it away. 


I wasn't born with a serial port. 
&nbsp;--Robert Caraballo, susano@bellsouth.net, 11/1/96






<br>&nbsp;<br>



Fair use is a valuable freedom, and collections of information shouldn't 

be able to be
copyrighted. 
&nbsp;--Alexander M. Covan, amc@bway.net, 11/1/96






<br>&nbsp;<br>






Editors Note: We received many emails asking where to write concerning 

the electronic copyright issues raised in this column. Contact 

<a href="http://www.public-domain.org/">Public Domain</a>, the 

recently-formed citizens' group opposing these provisions.












<br>&nbsp;<br>










<a href="/Perspectives/js/js10_11_96.html"> <strong> On Bill-bashing</strong></a>
<br>


Yeah! Bill [Gates] gets the bum rap. Has anyone met a billionaire 

they really liked? If Microsoft didn't get the money, IBM would have. 
&nbsp;--Jack Olmsted, jolmsted@frugal.com, 10/11/96







<br>&nbsp;<br>



In regards to your question, "Is it a bunch of 
rhetoric or do you 

believe Microsoft gets the bum rap?" I think it's 
obviously more Bill 

[Gates] rhetoric. Frankly, only a company like yours with 
an 

obviously pro-Windows flavor would even bother asking the question. 
&nbsp;--Adam Masri, masri@nolex.com, 10/12/96






<br>&nbsp;<br>



<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc10_9_96.html"><strong>Trade shows pass</strong></a>
<br>


When I go to a trade show, I'm annoyed by ignorant staff. If I can get


more accurate, and more in-depth information on the Web, I'm certainly 

not
going to sit through a fluffy presentation with subwoofers a rockin'.<br>
--Mike Safar, msafar@ix.netcom.com, 10/09/96








