<td valign=top width=310>



<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->











































        















        





























<font face="Arial" size=+2>



<strong>No Hot Dog on a Stick in these malls</strong>



</font>

<br>



















<font face="Arial" size=-1>October 30, 1996</font>













<p>











<font face="Times">









In the 11 months since I spotlighted "industry malls" as a promising way to
conduct Internet commerce, the Web has experienced no mad rush to open
niche marketplaces. But a few influentials, like former <a
href="http://www.lotus.com/">Lotus</a> president Jim Manzi, have come into
the field, indicating the notion wasn't stillborn.



<p>








Bailing out after <a href="http://www.ibm.com/">IBM</a> bought his 

company, Manzi jumped to <a href="http://www.industry.net/">Industry.Net</a>,

 the pioneer of this genre of industry-specific marketplaces. Industry.Net 

is a "smokestack industry mall," connecting industrial manufacturers and 

distributors by region so they can buy from and sell to each other. 



<p>






<img align=left height=105 width=127



src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_malls.gif">






Manzi is clearly grooming Industry.Net for its next stage of growth, 

but two announcements this week have highlighted this industry mall concept.



<p>






The first news is <a href="http://www.developages.com/">DeveloPages</a>, 

which works the opposite end of a product cycle from Industry.Net. 

DeveloPages just went public with its database of 12,000 potential 

suppliers for companies that want to contract out for services in developing 

new products in consumer electronics, computers, telecommunications gear, 

plastics, and medical devices



<p>







<img align=right height=94 width=109



src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_sellers.gif">







The other is <a href="http://www.inquiry.com/">inquiry.com,</a> 

which is expanding its Web site from just software development into 

the networking area. Inquiry.com provides voluminous product data, 

published comparisons, and discussion groups, all free to users. 



<p>





Last week <a href="http://www.insweb.com/">InsWeb</a>, a 

Web mall for insurance buyers and the insurance industry, added its 

first business-oriented programs. Its new offering is a way for 

self-employed individuals and small businesses to set up plans that 

let employees pay for medical expenses on a pretax basis.



<p>





For anyone who thinks the Web will cut out the 

<a href="/Perspectives/tc/tc10_2_96.html">middlemen</a>, 

pay attention: These malls represent the new Web intermediaries. 



<p>

























What are the key elements of these industry malls? First, they focus on a 

particular industry or function. Second, the early industry malls sprung 

up in markets that are chaotic or inefficient, where organizing comprehensive

 information adds real value. 



<p>



Third, they focus on organizing the online experience for potential buyers, 

not the vendors. Where buyers go, sellers soon follow, and the sellers, not 

the buyers, pay the mall. 



<p>



Fourth, these malls have launched to provide information that facilitate 

sales, but most are moving toward transactions. 



<p>



In fact, their migration from presenting data into sales serves as almost 

a lab experiment for electronic commerce. No one has figured out which 

"business model" will work best for Net commerce, but as these malls move 

at different paces along different paths toward selling, we'll all learn 

something. 



<p>



In that vein, it's also helpful that today's industry malls emanate from 

different industries, although to date the biggest success has been in the 

business-to-business sector, not consumer-oriented markets. 



<p>



<img align=left height=122 width=144



src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_pioneer.gif">An exception to that dictum is what's shaping up in consumer insurance, 

where start-up Ins.Web faces stiff competition from 

<a href="http://www.intuit.com/">Intuit</a>'s 

<a href="http://www.qfn.com/">Quicken Financial Network</a>. Intuit 

clearly intends to move its franchise in personal finance software into 

a Web marketplace for all kinds of investment products. 

(My guess is that Intuit wants to sell products itself, although it 

hasn't explicitly said so.) 

<a href="http://www.autobytel.com/">Auto-by-Tel</a> is likewise pursuing 

consumers with its auto information site. 



<p>



Still, most consumers aren't convinced it's safe to put personal financial 

information on the Net, although that hesitancy has diminished in the last 

year. Businesses too are Net-shy, which is one reason these industrial malls 

have been information-only. 



<p>



To date, the chief business model for industrial malls has been to charge 

companies that join for their listings, often a monthly fee, as is the case 

for Ins.Web, Industry.Net, and now DeveloPages. 



<p>



Inquiry.com has a pay-per-lead model, with software companies paying $25 

for leads that emanate from the developer-oriented Web site. 



<p>



Manzi has signaled that Industry.Net will get more involved in 

transactions; the company just arranged for 

<a href="http://www.pnc.com/">PNC</a> to be Industry.Net's preferred bank 

to handle credit arrangements. 



<p>



In the last 11 months, the barriers to entering the industry mall 

business have gone up. Manzi has put his considerable financial 

resources behind Industry.Net, and inquiry.com has venture funding 

from deep-pocketed <a href="http://www.softbank.jp/">Softbank</a>. 



<p>



Still, it's a fascinating lab test for Internet commerce. 



<p>







<font face="Arial" size=-1>



Stuff 

<a href="mailto:timc@cnet.com">Tim Clark's</a> big brown bag 

with your comments.





