<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->




















        







        











<font face="Arial" size=+2>
<strong>Web ads: One size doesn't fit all</strong>
</font><br>







<font face="Arial" size=-1>October 23, 1996</font>











    










<p>



















<font face="Times">



A fight's brewing over standard sizes for those ever-present ad banners on Web
sites.  





<p>



	  



Here's the problem: There's no such thing as a standard banner size on the
Web. There are now more than a mind-boggling 191 different
dimensions, according to ad services firm <a
href="http://www.focalink.com/">Focalink</a>.  
<p>






   



 <img align=left height=82 width=185


src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_standard.gif">



 
If an advertiser wants to run a campaign on several Web sites, it may have
to create different versions of a single ad banner for every site. To make
matters worse, because most advertisers run several banners in a campaign,
each must be adapted
for each site, so the problem multiplies. One Focalink client, for example, is preparing 200 banners for an upcoming
campaign.

<p>







All that adapting costs money, and advertisers are getting sick of it. Some
are having the Web sites themselves do the work, which costs the sites money.

<p>




		  




The solution is obvious: Standardize Web banner sizes on several different
configurations. 

<p>





There's where everyone agrees. How to do it creates the disagreements. 

<p>







A task force from the <a href="http://commercepark.com/AAAA">Coalition for
Advertising-Supported Information and Entertainment</a> (CASIE)  issued
recommendations early this month. It called for five standard sizes: Two
horizontal banners, two vertical banners, and a button. 

<p>





<img align=right height=165 width=133


src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_problem.gif">





But apparently that initiative doesn't sit well with some elements in the
Internet Advertising Bureau (IAB), a nascent trade group for ad-supported
Web sites. CASIE is polling major ad sites, and IAB is polling its
members, which are for the most part major ad sites. 

<p>






Normally, I'd assume this was a problem between ad sellers and ad buyers.
CASIE is the creation of big advertisers, as represented by the Association
of National Advertisers (ANA), and big ad agencies, represented by the
American Association of Advertising Agencies (4As). 

<p>





The IAB, formed to promote Web advertising, deals with Web sites that sell
ads.
Back in June, it identified standard banner sizes as an early goal,
something that seemed quickly doable.

<p>






But the CASIE task force was headed by Martin Nisenholtz, president of the
<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/">New York Times Company's</a> electronic
publishing
group. Members included another content site, <a
href="http://www.nbc.com/">NBC</a>,
two ad agencies (<a href="http://www.cks.com/">CKS Partners</a> and <a
href="http://www.modemmedia.com/">Modem Media</a>), a major advertiser (<a
href="http://www.att.com/">AT&T</a>) and <a
href="http://www.doubleclick.com/">Doubleclick</a>, an ad sales network for
Web sites. Pretty ecumenical. 

<p>









This should be an easy issue, and there's a hint that some in the trade
press are fanning the appearance of conflict where there isn't one. 

<p>


Nothing in the plan requires a Web site to run only standard ads or an
advertiser to pay for bigger banners or odd placements on a Web page. <a
href="http://www.hotwired.com/"><i>Wired</i></a> magazine, among others,
made a
splash with ads that have to be customized for the publication alone. 
</a>
The issue may be one of approach. The quick-and-dirty strategy would be to
see how the top advertising Web sites, those with the most ads, create their
banners and then build the standard that way. Instead, CASIE started with a
clean slate about what
sizes would be best and made that its proposed standard. 

<p>
<img align=left height=91 width=158


src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_clean.gif">


I'm no techie, but the CASIE approach seems reasonable. It's a question of
pixels, not principles. In the long run, starting with a clean slate makes
better sense.

<p>

Reasonable people can differ. Web sites that must alter their current banner
sizes under the CASIE proposal can argue that the most popular current sizes
should have been the standard. 

<p>

But six months from now, the approach won't matter. To thrive, the Web needs
to grow up as a medium, and that means having the kind of standard ad units
that exist in TV, radio, and print. 

<p>

Standards need not limit the Web's growth. Having no standards surely will.

<p> 

Let's settle this quickly. <a href="http://www.comdex.com/">Comdex</a> is
next month. Sounds like a good target date. 

<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>


Settle your score quickly with   
<a href="mailto:timc@cnet.com">Tim Clark.</a>  Your email may show up in future
Perspectives. 


<p>





<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html">


<font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>   







 








<p>







