<p>



 





 



 



        



       





</td>








        





<td width=5 rowspan=1>
<!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->



        




</td>



        















        



       













<td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->

















        







        







<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Where voluntarism, not regulation, 
can work</strong></font><br>




<font face="Arial" size=-1>October 16, 1996</font>











    







<p>















<font face="Times">



Encouraging news: <a href="http://www.commerce.net/">CommerceNet</a>, the
nonprofit consortium of companies involved and interested in Internet
commerce, will work with the <a href="http://www.eff.org/">Electronic
Freedom Foundation</a> (EFF) on the <a
href="http://www.etrust.org/">eTrust</a> privacy program.  

<p>



	

             
eTrust is likely to emerge as the leading issuer of privacy logos to Web
sites that agree to abide by privacy guidelines, such as not selling user
email addresses. Big Six accounting firms <a
href="http://www.colybrand.com/">Coopers & Lybrand</a> and <a
href="http://www.us.kpmg.com/">KPMG Peat Marwick</a> will help administer
the eTrust program. When it launches early next year, eTrust will absorb
another privacy initiative, called 
<a href=" /News/Item/0,4,4044,00.html">Privacy Assured</a>, 
that is already up and running.

<p>

  <img align=left height=120 width=178
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_assure.gif">

The broad support for eTrust spotlights the quiet but critically important
progress in building the "soft infrastructure" of Net commerce. What's this "soft infrastructure"? It consists of the digital counterparts
of things we take for granted in the physical world: ways to check a
merchant's track record, ways to be certain the party you're dealing with is
really who he or she claims to be, ways to convince people their kids won't find
a "snuff film" while surfing the Net, or run up a huge bill with an online
astrologist. 


<p>


Without these assurances, ordinary consumers and businesses won't do
business on the Net. 

<p>




Some elements of the soft infrastructure, such as privacy protection, are
coming. For tracking scams, the <a href="http://www.bbb.org/">Better
Business Bureau</a> has launched its Web site.  But so far it is just another
way to post its regular warnings. Another group will need to emerge as the
leader in tracking swindlers on the Net. 


<p>

	
	  <img align=right height=141 width=127
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_private.gif">


So far, private efforts are working better than the government's. A year ago
Congress was poised for draconian censorship online: Bad legislation that
was largely derailed because of <a
href="http://www.w3.org/pub/WWW/PICS/">PICS</a>, the Platform for
Interactive Content Selection. The PICS technology allows different groups
to rate online content, then let employers, parents, or schools block content
they deem unacceptable based on those ratings, rather than following the 
whims of Washington.

<p>

To the usual reasons why voluntary, private efforts work better than
government, Lori Fena, EFF's executive director, adds another: jurisdiction.
The Internet is a global phenomenon and thus beyond the reach of any
national government. Put simply: U.S. laws don't work in Madagascar.  

<p>

 
But contracts and licenses do. Artists, publishers, and software companies
have been licensing material across national borders for ages. Virtually
every legal system respects such contracts.  Ironically,  a private agency that lets a
Web site use its logo on certain conditions can enforce that agreement
better than Bill Clinton can.  

<p> 


Granted, private efforts have limits. As I've written here before, agencies
such as central banks may be the best vehicle for regulating electronic cash.
Who wants to be ripped off by an electronic counterfeiter? 

<p>


	
There will doubtless be other areas too, but as Fena says, jumping in with
legislation is not usually the right first step. Initial, voluntary efforts
on privacy can identify the sticky issues so eventually
legislation will address the right areas, not the wrong ones. And they will do so
based on experience, not election-year politics. 

<p> 

 <img align=left height=126 width=116
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/October_96/per_needed.gif">

Needed: Something to deal with unwanted junk email. The <a
href="http://www.the-dma.org/">Direct Marketing Association</a> has task
forces working on these issues.  And <a href="http://www.aol.com/">America
Online</a> is fighting the good fight in court to block junk email delivery 
to its members.  The members of  the newly renamed <a
href="http://www.kww.com/image/">Internet Marketing Association of Global
Enterprises</a>, who style themselves as the good guys of direct marketing,
should jump in next. 

<p> 

Here's an area where the U.S. government's ability to act, even for the
right side, is limited, because of First Amendment protections of free
speech. Here, private efforts are not just the best for today, but probably
forever. 

<p>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>

<a href="mailto:timc@cnet.com">Tim Clark</a> volunteers to read your email. 
He'll even post the best ones.  

<p>

<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html">
<font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>   







 





<p>







<p>



        


</td>



























</tr>












