       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Are trade shows pass&#233;?</strong></font><br>



      



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>October 9, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">

Technology trade shows are doomed. The Net will cripple them.
<p>



Basically, customers don't need to go to shows anymore to experience the
latest and greatest. Software, even beta versions, can be tried out from your
desktop via the Web.
<p>

<img align=left height=100 width=142
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_comdex.gif">


Hardware too: You can't download a <a href="http://www.cisco.com/">Cisco</a>
router or an <a href="http://www.intel.com/">Intel</a> Pentium Pro, but  <a
href="http://www.digital.com/">Digital Equipment</a> offers test drives of
Alpha workstations over the Net.  
<p>

So why would a boss send a buyer to Las Vegas for Comdex? It's a pricey perk.
<p>



Still companies haven't given up entirely.  While you can take that Alpha
test drive anytime, Digital continues to have a major trade show presence.
However, there are signs that some high-tech
companies are reevaluating.  
<p>



On a recent plane trip (coming home from a trade show, naturally), I sat
next to a <a href="http://www.lotus.com/">Lotus</a> marketing manager. A
Lotus executive figured out recently that the firm was spending in excess of
$1.5 million for Comdex (just for people, hotels, and transportation, I
think). That resulted in an internal review: Does every product have to be
shown at Comdex? 
<p>

	<img align=right height=100 width=135
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_day.gif">
I don't know what conclusion Lotus reached, but as the sphere of the
Internet expands, a lot of companies will ask themselves the same question.
The obvious answer: In this day of the Net, not
everybody has
to go.   
<p>




The main economic justification for trade shows is that they put potential
buyers in front of would-be sellers. Otherwise, that trade show line item
would be written out of the marketing budget. 
<p>




Trade shows have plenty of other functions: Positioning products, spying on
competitors, putting key executives in front of key trade rags, and boosting
profits at local liquor distributors. But most of those things
don't have to happen at a convention. Other
marketing tactics may come cheaper than a trade show presence, like
long distance
PR, private eyes, press tours, afternoon beer blasts, and ads.

<p>
 <img align=left height=122 width=130
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_tool.gif">

We've all been to trade shows where attendance seems notably down from the
last event.  Show promoters always have ready reasons to explain away
that impression. But when I hear exhibitors saying, "The crowd was a little
sparse, but they were the right people," I have to wonder if that exhibitor
will be back. 

<p>
Personally, I don't mind trade shows, with the exception of that Disaster in
Vegas next month. Face-to-face meetings are important, especially because
much of my reporting work is done online or over the phone. 

<p>
But the trend is definitely going the wrong way for trade show operators,
unless they're doing something I don't know about. Virtual trade shows?
Sure, you can put company areas up on a Web site and let visitors see, try,
even buy products. Such a scheme keeps exhibits up constantly. But a trade
show company expects more revenue than it can charge for a Web site.

<p>
Maybe this will be the test, not only of high-tech trade shows but of <a
href="http://www.softbank.co.jp/">Softbank</a>'s <a
href="http://www.news.com/Newsmakers/Son/son.html"> Masayoshi Son</a>, who
spent $1 billion in 1995 buying the Comdex, <a
href="http://www.interop.com/">Network+Interop</a>, and other trade shows.
Softbank Expos, which runs all but the Comdex shows, has experimented with
virtual trade shows with little success. Some companies are willing to
buy spots online as part of the trade show package deal, but try selling that
space alone and they start asking why they couldn't do it themselves for a
lot less money.

<p>
Did he buy a dying business? Only time will tell.

</font>
<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>

You can email <a href="mailto:timc@cnet.com">Tim Clark</a>, even when he's attending blasted tradeshows.

<p>

<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>     



<p>



<p>



<p>

        </td>













</tr>





