        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->



        </td>



        















        



       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->











        







        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Who needs the middlemen?<br> We all do. </strong></font><br>







      







        <font face="Arial" size=-1>October 2, 1996</font>











    <p>





<font face="Times">



Last week, in a grove of California redwoods, I witnessed the silent

disintermediation of the real estate industry.

<p>





Disintermediation, that overwrought, seven-syllable bit of economists'

jargon, ostensibly describes what will happen to the middlemen in financial

transactions on the Net: they're supposed to disappear. 

<p>





<img align=left height=126 width=121

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_sound.gif">



I had imagined that an industry of middlemen so established as residential

real estate brokers would at least make a crinkling sound when it collapsed,

rather like a glass mirror sounds as it crumbles. Instead, the sound of an

industry realigning was no louder than the Pacific fog that lifted midmorning.

<p>



You see, despite the big word and all the hype, disintermediation is not a

disappearing act, but a realignment. The argument that the Net's unique

ability to bring buyers directly to sellers makes middlemen unnecessary is

simply not true, as the real estate industry is demonstrating.

<p>



Middlemen won't go away on the Net; they'll only change. Some

traditional middlemen may disappear, but intermediaries as a group will

remain because

both buyers and sellers need them. It's just not practical for individual

buyers and

sellers to find each other one at a time. Then there's the simple fact that

we need their expertise.

<p>



	

Back to the real estate agents decline: After selling one California home

and buying another in the last year, I'm painfully aware of how much the

agents' six percent commission amounts to: too much.  And our agent

is even a friend.    

<p>



 <img align=right height=69 width=159

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_middleman.gif">



Real estate brokers manage to hold onto their fat commissions primarily

because they control one crucial piece of information: the Multiple Listing

Service (MLS) data on all the homes for sale in a particular area. This

simple, flat-file database contains crucial data on every home for sale in

an area and today is only available to licensed agents who pay a hefty fee

for access.

<p>



But the Web is undermining that control, making the data more

widely available and creating new ways for real estate buyers and sellers to

connect. Some buyers and sellers are circumventing the MLS by listing and

searching for houses on the Web. As <a

href="http://www.mapquest.com/">MapQuest</a> executive Perry Evans

says, "The Web has a fascinating way of rebuilding markets very quickly." 

<p>





Evans and I were among about 50 people who attended the Web Hot Properties

Retreat last week, presented by Web real estate news guru Brad Inman of  <a

href="http://www.inman.com/">Inman News Features</a>. 



<p>



It was there I saw how Web-savvy attendees of the conference are

undermining, consciously or

unconsciously, today's real estate agents.

<p>



Bill Janssen, president of the tony San Francisco brokerage <a

href="http://www.pacunion.com/">Pacific Union</a>, sees the handwriting on

the wall. 

<p>

"In the future, agencies will have fewer agents and do more business at far

lower margins," says Janssen. The change agent is information: More data

about homes for sale and sale prices is available than ever before. 

<p>



"We had information lock-up," Janssen adds, "and that's changing rapidly."

Lenders, Web sites oriented to specific regions, and real estate services

are going direct to consumers. 



<p>

"The survivors are going to be the people who know how to access and provide

services," he predicted.  



<p>

But Jeff Johns, Webmaster for a subsidiary of the California Association of

Realtors, argues that most information now is not organized, so a

self-directed consumer quickly gets information overload. 

<p>

"There's going to be a glut of information, 90 percent of it bad," Johns

says. His Web site, <a href="http://ca.living.net/">California Living

Network</a>, is fighting a rearguard action to buy time for the current

franchise of California's real estate agents by publishing incomplete (and

sometimes outdated) listings. For complete information, go to a Realtor.

<p>



From what I saw at the retreat, though, today's Realtor franchise has months, not

years, to live. The Web will help melt away this unnatural monopoly of

information. 



<p>

 <img align=left height=131 width=184

src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_software.gif">



Real estate agents won't be the only intermediaries in a home purchase. But

they will still have a significant role.

They'll have to compete based not on their unfair control of market

information, but on service, knowledge, negotiating skills, and hand-holding

for clients making the biggest financial investment of their lives. 



<p>

In Janssen's real estate agency of the future, the real estate agents handle

those critical activities. Much of the paper-shuffling and coordinating of

vendors that occupy agents today will be handled by support personnel. 

<p>

"And it won't be for a fixed price," says Becky Swann, creator of <a

href="http://www.ired.com/">ired.com</a>, the International Real Estate

Directory, which rates residential real estate sites on the Web. "It's going

to be fee for services, and agents are going to have to come up with a menu

of pricing."



<p>

Who'll gain? Probably home buyers and sellers through lower commissions,

although they'll pay more for real estate data and maybe attorneys to help

them around the devilishly complex rules and regulations governing property

sales. These are the groups that will see a real gain.  



<p>

But today's lesson on real estate agents demonstrates that disintermediation

doesn't mean buyers will deal directly with sellers on the Net. It just

means we'll deal with other middlemen. 



</font>

<p>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>



<a href="mailto:timc@cnet.com">Tim Clark</a> wants to read your email at home.

</font>

<p>





<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>

More Perspectives</font></a>







<p>







