<p>

  

 

        

       </td>



        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->

        </td>

        







        

       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Why e-cash needs the feds</strong></font><br>



      



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 25, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">

I may be one of the few people who is glad the U.S. government is waking up to electronic money. For an electronic economy to blossom on the Net, several issues need to be addressed that are dealt with much more easily with the feds than without them. 
<p>

<img align=left height=109 width=160
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_feds.gif">

	
So I'm pleased that our civil servants in Washington, D.C., last week held a gabfest sponsored by the <a href="http://www.ustreas.gov/">U.S. Department of Treasury</a> on electronic money and what role government should take in its regulation.

<p>



Top officials from the Treasury, <a href="http://www.bog.frb.fed.us/">Federal Reserve Board</a>, <a href="http://www.ftc.gov/">Federal Trade Commission</a>, Comptroller of the Currency, and Congress outlined their views
<p>


Broadly, they are concerned about crooks and consumers. Law enforcement fears hard-to-trace electronic money will become a popular way to launder money from illegal activities. Collecting taxes on virtual transactions may also be difficult, although most credit card transactions today are handled via computer networks. Then there are straightforward fraud and digital counterfeiting concerns.

<p>

For consumers, privacy is paramount, but we'd like to get enough information on issuers of electronic cash to be confident we won't get fleeced when we purchase digital money with the real thing.
<p>



Then most everyone has the usual Internet worries about hackers, security, monopoly (would you put your money in Net.Bank of Microsoft.Com?), and so on. 

<p>

	
The various agencies push slightly different approaches. Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, a Republican, doesn't think electronic money will become economically significant anytime soon, but he counsels letting market forces, not regulations, prevail in its development. 
<p>



The Democrats who head Treasury and the FTC put their social agenda on e-money. They want electronic money to make financial services more accessible, not less, for poor Americans, no mean feat if electronic money requires a $1,000-plus PC and a Net connection. Something like 12 million Americans don't have a bank account, so they cash paychecks, welfare checks, disability benefits, and retirement payments at expensive check-cashing services. 
<p>


 <img align=right height=79 width=193
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_dems.gif">

But the Democrats too are soft-pedaling government's role. Robert Pitofsky, chairman of the Federal Trade Commission, argued existing approaches to consumer protection and antitrust concerns can be applied to electronic money. He also suggested technology (encryption, digital signatures, etc.) might protect consumers better than laws. 

<p>


Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin believes that maintaining public trust in private markets, such as the one for e-money, is critical and that government has an appropriate role in making this happen.

<p>

Let's not underestimate the importance of last week's gathering. Less than two years ago a Washington reporter, Brock Meeks, told me that what most federal bureaucrats knew about digital money came from a <i><a href="http://www.hotwired.com/">Wired</a></i> magazine article published around that time.

<p>
We've come a long way from that stage. Companies like <a href="http://www.cybercash.com/">CyberCash</a>, for example, have taken it upon themselves to educate official Washington about electronic money.

<p>
Of course, one conference in Washington doesn't mean everything is resolved. As the Washington gathering acknowledged, a global Internet requires international approaches. At that level, new considerations will arise involving currency trading and the roles of central banks in regulating national economies. 

<p>

 <img align=left height=126 width=148
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_greenspan.gif">

Some e-money champions see electronic money as a means to undermine central economic authorities, a move they applaud. Clearly, no centralized government will endorse that kind of move, so we may see conflict at that level.  

<p>
The Washington conference was more at the stage of identifying the issues than at solving them. But the issues that were identified are the right ones.

<p>
It's encouraging that even the most activist regulators see limits to how quickly they should jump in. Regulating too soon could choke off private efforts to address these issues, just as regulating too late could create an opportunity for the crooks to cheat consumers or launder dirty money.
<p>
It's a fine line, but even in this election season, the underlying issues have not become unduly ideological.   

</font>
<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Send your two cents to <a href="mailto:timc@cnet.com">Tim Clark</a>.</font> 

<p>


<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>     




<p>



<p>



<p>

        </td>













</tr>





