        <td width=5 rowspan=1><!----------------------------------GUTTER-------------->

        </td>

        







        

       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>A stitch in Internet time</strong></font><br>



      



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 18, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">

"Internet time" is an ugly phrase. Unfortunately for linguistic aesthetes,
it describes a real phenomenon. Like "dog years," Internet years race past
faster than earth time. If a dog year passes seven times faster than a year
on the calendar, an Internet year goes about four times faster than I like
to count my birthdays.  
<p>

	
Just consider what three of today's Internet kingpins were doing not so long
ago:

<p>
<img align=left height=71 width=190
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_andreessen.quote.gif">

Three years ago, <a href="http://www.netscape.com/">Netscape</a> whiz kid
Marc Andreessen was an undergraduate at the University of Illinois, where he
and his band of  programmers were writing Mosaic, the Web browser that
launched the Net toward broad popularity.

<p>


Two years ago, <a href="http://www.oracle.com/">Oracle</a>'s Larry Ellison,
Mr. Network Computer, was shilling for interactive TV and bad-mouthing <a
href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a>.   (Well, not everything has
changed.)

<p>

Fourteen months ago, Bill Gates, was still clueless about the Net and
promoting the hell out of Windows 95 and Microsoft Network, his proprietary
online service. 
<p>


In fact, we're almost all Net newcomers, even those who can remember when
there was but one search engine. Here's the test: If you can remember what
<a href="http://www.yahoo.com/">Yahoo</a> originally stood for, you're not a
newbie. (The answer: Yet Another Hierarchical Officious Oracle.)


<p>

	
How fast does Net time fly? Let me count the months:
 

<p>



In July, Wall Street's infatuation with Internet IPOs waned as <a
href="http://www.hotwired.com/">Wired</a> magazine's parent delayed going
public. Many new issues of Internet stocks had soared at first, then dived
as investors decided profits might actually matter.

<p>

 <img align=right height=126 width=139
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_ellison.quote.gif">

In February, Congress passed a landmark telecommunications deregulation
bill. In April, Internet service provider <a
href="http://www.uu.net/">UUNet</a> was swallowed up by alternative phone
carrier <a href="http://www.mfs.com/">MFS Communications</a>, which last
month sold out to long distance carrier <a
href="http://www.wcom.com/">WorldCom</a>.


<p>


 
In January, a reporter's name was morphed into a verb. "We don't want to get
Markoffed," said skittish <a href="http://www.visa.com/">Visa</a> and <a
href="http://www.mastercard.com/">Mastercard</a> negotiators as they put the
finishing touches on standards to safeguard credit cards on the Net. They
referred to <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/">New York Times</a> man John
Markoff, whose frequent stories about
Internet security issues helped to mold media coverage of the Net. 

<p>
In September 1995, Masayoshi Son was nursing his wounds after getting outbid
for <a href="http://www.zdnet.com/">Ziff-Davis Publishing</a>. Since then,
his <a href="http://www.softbank.co.jp/">Softbank</a> empire has spent
billions for Ziff, giant trade show promoter <a
href="http://www.comdex.com/">Comdex</a>, and now memory maker <a
href="http://www.kingston.com/">Kingston Technology</a>, plus sunk millions
into more than a score of Internet start-ups.

<p>
 
In July 1995, there were five major online services, all running on
proprietary technology. Today, only the biggest, <a
href="http://www.aol.com/">America Online</a>, still runs on its own private
protocols. <a href="http://www.apple.com/">Apple</a>'s eWorld is dead, and
<a href="http://www.compuserve.com/">CompuServe</a>, <a
href="http://www.msn.com/">Microsoft Network</a>, and flagging <a
href="http://www.prodigy.com/">Prodigy</a> are Webifying and adopting
Internet standards. 
<p>
 
In May 1995, <a href="http://www.sun.com/">Sun Microsystems</a> unveiled <a
href="http://java.sun.com/">Java</a>, a difficult but powerful programming
language, with flash and panache. Java, which doubled Sun's stock price,
reigned as the undisputed Net's hottest technology for almost a year, before
Microsoft's ActiveX challenge. 
<p>
	<img align=left height=168 width=133
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_gates.quote.gif">

In April 1995, it was a big deal when Yahoo got a couple millions of venture
capital from Sequoia Capital. Now entire venture funds with hundreds of
millions to play with are devoted solely to funding Internet firms. Even
Java has its own fund. 
<p>
No question: The velocity of change on the Net is staggering, Internet time
or no Internet time. 
<p>
And the next change is bound to be that things will change even faster.
<p> </font>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>If you're old enough to read <a href="mailto:timc@cnet.com">Tim Clark</a>, you're old enough to write. Where
were you three Web years ago? 

<p>


<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>



<p>



<p>



<p>

        </td>













