       <td valign=top width=310><!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





        



        <font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Why the Net<br>needs Big Blue</strong></font><br>



       



        <font face="Arial" size=-1>September 11, 1996</font>





    <p>


<font face="Times">


If it seems to you as though <a href="http://www.internet.ibm.com/"> IBM's</a>
recent push into electronic commerce belies its image as a slow-moving
behemoth, you're right. That's just what Big Blue's media handlers intended
us to think.
<p>

	<img align=left height=110 width=105
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_blue_quote.gif">

But this time, there's substance behind the Blue haze. Taking IBM's recent
announcements as a wholea consumer banking partnership with major banks,
its electronic commerce strategy, electronic commerce partners and
customers, new mainframes for electronic commerceelectronic commerce will
gain. And that's good for anyone interested in doing business on the Net. 

<p>


  


Could that Big Blue Blur really be IBM? Yes, because for PR and Wall Street
purposes, that's the right reputation. In truth, IBM's Internet initiatives
have been incubating in its labs for about nine months, says Mark Greene,
IBM's vice president of electronic payment and certification.



<p>



 

Take this week's announcement of Integrion Financial Network, IBM's venture
with 15 big banks to build the infrastructure for home banking and consumer
bill-paying. It illustrates why it helps to have Big Blue on the e-commerce
team: What other technology company could have done that deal?

<p>



Not Microsoft. Since Bill Gates' injudicious reference to bankers as
"dinosaurs" a few years back, bankers see red when they hear Microsoft.
Listen to one of IBM's bank buddies, Robert Gillespie, presidentand CEO of
KeyCorp: "If we be dinosaurs, today we're putting our competitors on notice
that it's a new breed evolving with a voracious appetite for marketshare."
Ouch. 
<p>


	<img align=right height=80 width=160
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/per_bankers_quote.gif">

Not Netscape. Imagine 15 bank CEOs telling their boards of directors that
they're going with a 3-year-old start-up, besieged by Microsoft, with zero
experience in banking as their key technology partner for Internet banking.
No way. Netscape did convince Wells Fargo Bank, but even I can't be
convinced that's a good move, and I've only peeked into two bank boardrooms
in my life.


<p>


   

Not Intuit. The best name in personal finance software doesn't do
infrastructure, but bankers have branding issues with Intuit anyway. IBM
Chairman Lou Gerstner Jr. got that message: "IBM is not in the business of
putting our brand between our customers and their customers. We are an
enabler and partner, not a competitor."

<p>

 
I dwell on the bankers because if the banks don't play on the Net, real
commercial activity doesn't happen there. Period. 


<p>



Big Blue's comfort factor will mean much to other key, conservative
industries too. Look for IBM deals with old-line retailers. A number of
Internet start-ups, bookstore <a
href="http://www.amazon.com/">Amazon.com</a> and vintner <a
href="http://www.virtualvin.com/">Virtual Vineyards</a> are doing well on
the Net, and these early adopters are using Silicon Graphics hardware. But
even Hollywood's favorite animation company doesn't expect to sign up JC
Penney and Macy's anytime soon. 

<p>

In another conservative industry, KPMG Peat Marwick, the Big Six accounting
firm, is turning to IBM technology for its initial forays into electronic
commerce. 
<p> 

Even one of the Net's most successful commercial sectors, software sales,
may rely on IBM for infrastructure technology. One key element in selling
massive amounts of software electronically is keeping track of software
licenses. IBM will be the technology supplier to ELSI (Electronic Licensing
and Security Initiative), a clearinghouse being set up for such licenses.
<p>

Internet commerce is an interesting sideshow if boutiques and bookstores are
its leading sector. Serious commerce happens when serious players from the
economic mainstream--the bankers and retailers and boring transportation
firms and hospitals and government bureaucrats--get on the Net. 
<p>

Thanks, Big Blue. Bring your credibility and help them join us out here on
the frontier of electronic commerce.  
<p>

</font>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Email comments to: <a href="mailto:timc@cnet.com">Tim Clark</a><br></font>



<p>


<a href="/Perspectives/archive.html"><font face="Arial" size=-1>More Perspectives</font></a>     

<p>



