<a href="/cgi-bin/redirect.cgi?location=http://www.microsoft.com/ie/ad/euprod02.htm%3fportal.ad2">
<img src="/Banners/Portal/Perspectives/msie.perspectives.ptl.banner.gif" border=2 width=100 height=115 align=middle></a>
<br><p>




<br>

<p>
</td>

<td width=5>
&nbsp;
</td>

<td valign=top width="305" align=left>



<!----------- SECTION NAME ---->

<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">
<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif">
</a>

<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->

<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Bulls in the silicon shop</strong>

</font>

<br>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>January 7, 1997</font><br>

<p>
<font face="Times">
<p>



<p>
After last year's dismal negative ten percent growth, I believe the semiconductor
industry is set to take off. Look for a multiyear-bull market run starting
in 1997.
<p>
Why? Semiconductors live and die by the PC, and the forces of software,
price and consumer demand are conspiring to bring chip makers the same
successes they saw in 1992.<p>

Over $73 billion in semiconductor sales are estimated to be driven by the
PC and PC peripherals user markets. About 56 percent of all worldwide
semiconductor sales find their way into the computer-user market. The
closest runners-up--consumer devices and communications--claim only 16 and
14 percent of semiconductor sales respectively. That makes the PC in
general, and the two companies who dominate the PC market in particular,
the perfect weather vanes for chip sales.<p>
<img height=119 width=138 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_multiyear.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>
 <p>
<a
href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> <a
href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=msft"
>(MSFT)</a> and <a href="http://www.intel.com/">Intel</a> <a
href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=INTC"
>(INTC)</a>, the so-called Wintel consortium, lead the charge in PC
growth. Over 90 percent of personal computers are built using Intel-based
microprocessors. And, whether it's DOS, Windows, WindowsNT, Word,
Excel, or something else, most of the world's computers operate at least
one piece of Microsoft software. In fact, most require Microsoft
software.<p>

Prior to  the fourth quarter of 1992, the worldwide semiconductor industry
had just almost
completed its fourth year of single-digit growth, its worst growth rate
since the early 1980s.  Intel's 486 chip, introduced in 1989, was still
languishing, because the company wasn't able to produce large enough
volumes at low-enough prices for consumers to bite on the faster chip.<p>
<img height=113 width=128 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_down.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
But in late 1992, things started to change.<p>

PC prices had dropped considerably, due to the effects of the 1991-1992
recession and concurrent U.S. semiconductor market crash. This led to
dramatic improvements in PC performance at each price point.<p>
<p>

</font>


<P>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>

<a href="/Perspectives/Marketwise/dn1_7_97b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>
</td>
<td width=3>

</td>
<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->
<td valign=top width=155>
<img border=0 height=228 width=155

src="/Graphics/per_niles_a.gif"><br>
<p>

<img border=0  height=16 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">

<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc"
width=155 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>

<tr>
<td align=left width=155>
<span class="shorttakes">
<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">
<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_27_96a.html"><strong>Sour
grapes?</strong></a><br>
Sounds to me like Cronkite is verbalizing the fears of his contemporary
associates; and I am not talking about the fear that you might not be
professional or ethical. If Web news organizations can get it right,
unbiased and unedited, then they will flourish. One word--TRUST. They (the
mainstream news media) don't have it
anymore. &nbsp;--<a href="mailto:yusuf@infomagic.com">Yusuf Faruq
'Abd-al-Hakim</a>
<br>
The traditional press and the new form of reporting (Dateline, 20/20, etc.)
are either biased or downright unethical. They provide news that exists
in their own sphere, with little regard to real, unbiased, and credible
insight. Your efforts to implement a new and different perspective are
a fresh breeze in a news reporting. <a href="mailto:ibelyea@teleport.com">
I. Belyea</a>
<br>
&nbsp;
<br>
<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_20_96a.html"><strong>WebTV</strong></a><br>
Dream on!  The PC is just a digital TV/VCR without a traditional tuner, and
with a lot of unnecessary expense mounted on the desktop instead of at the
cable company where it belongs. You go ahead and live in the past.  Keep
your big clunky dinosaur PC! Disconnect from the network!  Keep your
loyalty to companies who have <i>no</i>
loyalty to <i>you</i>.  But don't expect us to!  We'll be flying down the
Information Highway on our Kawasaki NetCruisers!
&nbsp; --<a href="mailto: jamesefe@concentric.net"> James E. Felton </a>
<br>
&nbsp;
<br>
