<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->

<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Putting the bank before the horse</strong>

</font>

<br>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 24, 1996</font><br>

<p>

<font face="Times">

Savvy railbirds from California's Belmont Park to Santa Anita often bet the jockey and not the horse, and for good reason. <p>
It's the rider who knows that when the field gets packed, it may be wise to hold back, wait for the right moment, and then take the outside track for the win. <p>
<img height=172 width=139 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_stable.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>Likewise in the sport of IPO investing. Some market observers believe an edge can be had by following a particular firm's underwritings, rather than a single company or specific industry. And like horse farms, some investment houses have a stable of winners while others are littered with losers. <p>
Among the underwriters with at least six information technology (IT) IPOs in 1996, <a href="http://www.dlj.com/">Donaldson, Lufkin, & Jenrette</a> takes first with an average gain of 49.9 percent from nine deals. <p>
The investment banker's IPO with <a href="http://www.whittman-hart.com/">Whittman-Hart</a> is the firm's top underwriting in the IT field. Since this computer consultancy services company's debut on May 3, the stock has jumped over 182 percent. Also among DL&J's top IT deals includes <a href="http://www.univision.com/">Univision Communications</a>, which is up nearly 65 percent this year. <p>
<a href="http://www.ms.com/">Morgan Stanley</a> placed second in my IT IPO survey. If you jumped on the ground floor of the 13 companies Morgan Stanley brought public this year, your IT portfolio would outperform the Dow Jones Industrial Average by more than 25 percentage points. <p>
<img height=141 width=162 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_public.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>The investment house's average gain was 48.9 percent this year, paced by a 152 percent gain in DuPont Photomasks and a 124 percent move in the shares of <a href="http://www.fibre.com/">Advanced Fibre Communications</a>. Still, even a top house comes up with some laggards. Among these include <a href="http://www.cellnet.com/">CellNet Data Systems</a>, which is off 30 percent from its offer price, and Ploycom, a developer of telecommunications equipment, which has left its investors about 46 percent poorer. <p>
Taking the show position among IT IPO underwriters is <a href="http://www.vwco.com/">Volpe, Welty & Company</a>. The firm's six issues in this category have gained, on average, 39.4 percent this year. Shares of <a href="http://www.cotl.com/">Cotelligent Group</a>, which have risen 150 percent from its offer price, are primarily responsible for Volpe, Welty's strong showing. <p></font>

<P>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/Marketwise/rp12_24_96b.html">
<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>
</td>

