<td width=5>















&nbsp;















































</td>































































































































































<td valign=top width="305" align=left>























<!----------- SECTION NAME ---->










<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">
<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif">
</a>









<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->















<font face="Arial" size=+2>







<strong>It's coming:  Internet Judgment Day</strong>







</font>































<br>































<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 17, 1996</font><br>































<p>















































<font face="Times">


As we near the turn of the 21st century, the number of doomsayers, seers, and
diviners increases. I'm sure there is a law which correlates the proximity
of <img height=127 width=145 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_ads.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>
Judgment Day to the level of interest or excitement it generates. (In
fact, you can see Wall Street live out this law every quarter as trading
volumes increase immediately before quarterly earnings reports.) So, in
vogue with the coming millennium, let me add my divinations: Companies that
sell advertisements on the Web are nearing Judgment Day.<p>

The shakedown is coming in the latter part of 1997 or early 1998:  In that
period,  the hot companies will be selected and backed as winners; the
others will be dropped and left to die.
<p>
For almost two years now, entrepreneurs, venture capitalists, investors, and
analysts have been evangelizing the need to Get Big Fast.  In other words,
start-ups must 
grow fast enough to address the wave  of
demand that has been unleashed with the rise of the Internet.<p>

And numerous companies--many of which are now public--have executed this model
successfully, growing at unprecedented rates.<p>

But the point of inflection--the time when investors expect
financial models and projections to turn and young companies to maintain high
revenue growth and start to reap profits--is undeniably upon us.  Judgment
Day is coming within
the next 20 months.<p>
<img height=124 width=164 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_profits.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>

Wall Street expects public Internet companies that derive their revenues from
advertising to generate between $25 million and $35 million in revenue
next calendar year (an average growth rate of 115 percent over this year's
expected numbers) and turn profitable either in the second half of
1997 or early 1998.<p>

Internet companies such as
<a href="http://www.excite.com/">Excite</a> <a
href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=XCIT"
>(XCIT)</a>, <a href="http://www.infoseek.com/">Infoseek</a>  <a
href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=SEEK"
>(SEEK)</a>, <a href="http://www.lycos.com/">Lycos</a> <a
href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=LCOS"
>(LCOS)</a>, <a href="http://www.yahoo.com/">Yahoo</a> <a
href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=YHOO"
>(YHOO)</a>, and, yes, the owner of NEWS.COM, <a
href="http://www.cnet.com/">CNET: The Computer Network</a> <a
href="http://www.dbc.com/cgi-bin/htx.exe/squote?source=blq/cnet&ticker=CNWK"
>(CNWK)</a>, all of which derive their revenues from advertising, will be
expected to be in the black.<p>

</font>

<P>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>







<a href="/Perspectives/Marketwise/dr12_17_96b.html">







<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>































</td>















































<td width=3>















</td>















































































































































































































































































<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->















































































































































<td valign=top width=155>































<img border=0 height=200 width=155























src="/Graphics/per_rimer_a.gif"><br>











<p>























<img border=0  height=16 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">















<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" 































































width=155 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>































































<tr>     































































<td align=left width=155>































































<span class="shorttakes">















<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">







<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_6_96a.html"><strong>Microsoft's neighborhood</strong></a><br>















If <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> wants to require their OEMs to make certain that upon







shipping, the first screen that pops up is the Windows start-up screen







followed by the default desktop, it certainly seems that this is Microsoft's prerogative. &nbsp; --<a href="mailto:tkozik@msmedia.com">Thom Kozik</a>























<br> &nbsp; <br>























How long do you think Microsoft would last if it didn't do some of the things it does? It's not as if Microsoft is saying, "You must use our software!" They are saying, "Check out our software first, and if you don't







like it, use something you think will do it better!"  So please, can't we







all just get along!  &nbsp;  --<a href="mailto: formula@concentric.net">Daniel Anders Garcia Sanroman</a> 















<br> &nbsp; <br>















<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_5_96a.html"><strong>Stay home</strong></a><br>















I don't always agree with positions taken by the <a href="http://www.ala.org/">American Library Association</a>, 







but in this case, their assessment is accurate. The <a href="htttp://www.packardbell.com/">Packard Bell</a> commercials 







are "subtle, bleak, and ultimately selfish."







<br>







Thousands of...libraries in this country spend millions of dollars every year on computer equipment... I would venture to guess that many librarians will not be 







considering Packard Bell products when they go shopping for new equipment in 1997. &nbsp; --<a href="mailto:Lisa_Paris.IDEA@idea.com">Lisa Paris</a>















<br> &nbsp; <br>







If Margie Wylie's recent column suggested that Microsoft doesn't like public







libraries, I'd like to state for the record: We love them!







<br>







Microsoft has







committed $15 million in cash, software and technical assistance to 215







libraries in the U.S. and Canada to bring the benefits of Internet and PC







technology to underserved communities.












&nbsp;  --<a href="mailto: christhe@microsoft.com">Christopher Hedrick</a>, senior program manager, Microsoft Community Affairs,







<br> &nbsp; <br>













<br> &nbsp; <br>































































