<td valign=top width="305" align=left>















<!----------- SECTION NAME ---->














<a href="/Perspectives/perspectives.html">
<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif"></a>











<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->























<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>

Tech companies raked in the cash in 1996</strong>

</font>





<br>        



<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 10, 1996</font><br>



<p>





<font face="Times">







Venture capital investment in the United States continues to break all records, and information technology (IT) companies are the most prized deals among the venture community. While it's not possible to pick one winning investment from the 450 that have garnered investment in the last year, there are a few companies that stand out.<p>



IT companies reaped about 45 percent of all dollars invested between 1992 and 1995. <img align=left width=152 height=152 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_reaped.gif" vspace=5 hspace=5>But this year, they are taking almost 60 percent of all equity dollars raised, overshadowing venture money committed to biotechnology and nontechnology deals. <p>







Two groups of companies--software and information services and communications and networking--each accounted for 25 cents of every dollar raised by venture capital portfolio companies in the first nine months of this year. <p>



The biggest boost in IT investment, however, goes to Internet-related companies such as Internet software tools developers, content providers, Internet service providers, and Internet appliance manufacturers. Collectively, these companies have received $1.1 billion so far this year. <p>



In fact, a number of new venture funds were formed over the year to invest solely in Internet companies. These funds include the <a href="http://www.kpcb.com/keiretsu/JavaFund.html">Kleiner Perkins Java Fund</a>, The Flatiron Fund, and 21st Century Internet Partners, to name a few. <p>



Meanwhile, California continues to lead the nation in IT venture capital deals. IT companies in the Silicon Valley raised the bulk of the $1.78 billion in funds in California. Those observing the venture markets since the late 1970s are well aware that most venture capitalists live and work in the San Francisco Bay Area. <p>



Last week at a luncheon I asked a few of the San Francisco Bay area venture capitalists for their best investments of the year. <p>

<table align=right cellpadding=5><tr><td>

<img width=125 height=249 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/vcapital.gif">

</td></tr></table> 



Dick Kramlich, founding general partner of <a href="http://www.nea.com/">New Enterprise Associates</a> (NEA), picked <a href="http://www.jnx.com/">Juniper Networks</a>. While still pretty quiet about its technology and market, the company does admit to building high-performance switching and routing equipment for the Internet and intranet markets. Along with NEA, the company had attracted a virtual "who's who" of top-tier venture investors, including <a href="http://www.kpcb.com/">Kleiner Perkins Caufield & Byers</a>, <a href="http://www.benchmark.com/">Benchmark Capital</a>, <a href="http://www.ivp.com/">Institutional Venture Partners</a>, and <a href="http://www.crosspointvc.com/">Crosspoint</a>.<p>



<a href="/Newsmakers/Doerr/doerr.html">John Doerr</a>, general partner at Kleiner Perkins, chose <a href="http://www.amazon.com/">Amazon.com</a>. Amazon allows customers  to purchase almost any book currently in print at a discount via the Internet. This investment may do as well as Doerr's last Internet home run. He was the venture investor in <a href="http://www.netscape.com/">Netscape</a>. <p>



Meanwhile, John Mumford, a partner with prominent VC seed firm <a href="http://www.crosspointvc.com/">Crosspoint</a>, chose <a href="http://www.usweb.com/">USWeb</a>. The company offers Internet and intranet consulting, Web site development, hosting, maintenance, and marketing. The company is headed by CEO Joe Firmage, 26, who founded Serius Corporation (devoted to object-oriented applications development) at age 19 and later sold it to <a href="http://www.novell.com/">Novell</a> in 1993. 

<p> 





<a href="/Perspectives/Marketwise/rs12_10_96b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   





</td>





<td width=3>

</td>     

































<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->    



























<td valign=top width=155>















<img border=0 height=200 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_snipes_a.gif"><br>



<p>





<img border=0  height=16 width=155 src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">



<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" 















width=155 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>















<tr>     















<td align=left width=155>















<span class="shorttakes">



<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">

<a href="/Perspectives/js/js12_6_96a.html"><strong>Microsoft's neighborhood</strong></a><br>



If <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> wants to require their OEMs to make certain that upon

shipping, the first screen that pops up is the Windows start-up screen

followed by the default desktop, it certainly seems that this is Microsoft's prerogative. &nbsp; --<a href="mailto:tkozik@msmedia.com">Thom Kozik</a>





<br> &nbsp; <br>





How long do you think Microsoft would last if it didn't do some of the things it does? The computer software industry changes too quickly and is too competitive for a company to rest on its laurels. It's not as if Microsoft is saying, "You must use our software!" They are saying, "Check out our software first, and if you don't

like it, use something you think will do it better!"  So please, can't we

all just get along!  &nbsp;  --<a href="mailto: formula@concentric.net">Daniel Anders Garcia Sanroman</a> 



<br> &nbsp; <br>



<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw12_5_96a.html"><strong>Stay home</strong></a><br>



I don't always agree with positions taken by the <a href="http://www.ala.org/">American Library Association</a>, 

but in this case, their assessment is accurate. The <a href="htttp://www.packardbell.com/">Packard Bell</a> commercials 

are "subtle, bleak, and ultimately selfish."

<br>

[T]housands of...libraries in this country spend millions of dollars every year on computer equipment... I would venture to guess that many librarians will not be 

considering Packard Bell products when they go shopping for new equipment in 1997. &nbsp; --<a href="mailto:Lisa_Paris.IDEA@idea.com">Lisa Paris</a>



<br> &nbsp; <br>

If Margie Wylie's recent column suggested that Microsoft doesn't like public

libraries, I'd like to state for the record: We love them!

<br>

In fact, Microsoft's largest philanthropic effort is a joint program with the

American Library Association called Libraries Online. <br>Microsoft has

committed $15 million in cash, software and technical assistance to 215

libraries in the U.S. and Canada to bring the benefits of Internet and PC

technology to underserved communities.

<br>

The public library is one of the great democratic institutions of the world.

And Microsoft is pleased we could work with the urban and rural communities

to enhance library resources.



&nbsp;  --<a href="mailto: christhe@microsoft.com">Christopher Hedrick</a>, senior program manager, Microsoft Community Affairs,

<br> &nbsp; <br>



It is just a commercial. I never even considered 

it a slam on urban safety or a knock against 

librarians at all. I enjoy the commercials and 

view them as saying that there is a more friendly, 

entertaining way to get information from the 

comfort of your home. &nbsp;  --<a href="mailto:rgcurry@jcpenney.com">Rick Curry</a>

<br> &nbsp; <br>



Nothing is "just a commercial." Packard Bell has no interest in the

ethical, moral, or cultural implications of its advertising. That

sentence should end "of course. [W]hat [the commercial] depicts is the spiritual character of a nation that worships bottom lines, big bucks, and what's in it for me. &nbsp; --<a href="mailto:mickmca@bigfoot.com"> Mick McAllister </a>

<br> &nbsp; <br>





 Basically, I think it boils down to the two "future



views" we've dealt with since computers became popular.  We could live in a



nice society in which computers help us do many things, and enhance our



contact with other individuals. 



<br>



The other view...is one in which we live in



isolation but, alas, everyone has a nice plastic PC!  Yea.



&nbsp; --<a href="mailto:hijinx@enteract.com"> Paul McAleer</a>











<br> &nbsp; <br>















<a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com"><strong>What's your Perspective?</strong>



<br></a>



Got a point of view you'd like to share? NEWS.COM wants your Perspective. Email your essay to opinions editor <a href="mailto:margiew@cnet.com">Margie Wylie</a> to be considered for our guest editorial spot, the Soapbox. Please keep it under 1,200 words and type "soapbox" in the subject line.











</font>











<br>&nbsp;<br>







</td>



</tr>



</table>



