src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif"></a>


<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>

As January goes, so goes the year</strong>

</font>





<br>        



<font face="Arial" size=-1>December 3, 1996</font><br>



<p>





<font face="Times">





Investors tend to be skittish at the beginning of a new year because 

how January goes often sets the direction for the year.

<p>

That's been true in 40 of the last 45 years. All bear markets began or

continued with losing or below-average Januarys, while the best market

years all had above-average Januarys.

<p>

<img align=left width=163 height=104 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_january.gif">



With investors watching the market so closely, January is also the most

volatile month for the stock market. For the last 45 years, January has had

the second highest average point change of all months.

<p>

There are trends you should watch:  During the first couple of weeks of

January, low-priced, depressed stocks normally outperform quality stocks as

they bounce back from the

tax-loss selling pressures felt in late December.

<p>



But that doesn't mean you should turn a blind eye to the biggies.

Investors should always watch the direction of the major averages for the

first five trading days because these critical days

may influence big investors to either buy stocks if they head up, or trim

back should they slip down.

The greatest concentration of market downturns since 1949

started in the first six trading days of the month of January.

<p>

<img align=right width=155 height=171 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/12_96/per_crash.gif">



Investors should also be especially sensitive to any signs of weakness after

the spectacular performance of 1996.  Investors wary of a bearish market

should note that the sixth

year of a decade has always been up when it was an election year (1916,

1936, 1956, 1976, 1996) but each of the those years was followed by a

substantial bear market.

<p>



Still tech stocks may not be affected in 1997.  Next year should be a

strong year for PC sales to corporations because of Windows 95 and Windows

NT upgrades. Those PCs are loaded with memory

and drive capacity, and usually include CD-ROMs, fast modems, network

cards, big

displays, and lots of new software which will boost sales for a myriad of

high-tech companies.



</font>

<P>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>



<a href="/Perspectives/Marketwise/mm12_3_96b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   



</td>





