<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->











<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>

Is the semiconductor bull market back?</strong>

</font>







<br>        












<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 26, 1996</font><br>
















<p>













<font face="Times">











Christmas is approaching, and given the recent upswing in semiconductor 

stocks led by <a href="http://www.intel.com/">Intel</a>, the question again 

surfaces: Is this another multiyear bull market for semiconductors, or was 

this upswing just another head fake?



<p>













For those not familiar with the semiconductor market, calling it 

volatile would not do it justice. One of the best examples of this 

volatility is the performance of the 

<a href="http://www.phlx.com/">Philadelphia Semiconductor Index</a>, or 

SOX, which has rallied and plummeted, rallied and plummeted, and is now 

on its third upward swing since January 1995. In comparison, the 

<a href="http://www.dowjones.com/">Dow Jones Industrial Average</a> and 

the <a href="http://www.nasdaq.com/">Nasdaq Composite</a> have been 

relatively stable. 

<a href="http://www.news.com/Perspectives/perspectives.html#bundan">(see chart)</a>



<p>









Semiconductor stocks are best described as cyclical growths; 

every four to five years they go through the same boom-bust cycle.  

Initially, there's strong end-market demand, then increasing semiconductor

margins, followed by increasing semiconductor capacity. This leads to 

rapidly falling semiconductor prices, resulting in cheaper end-market 

products and elastic end-market demand.



<p>
























I believe this will probably never change, although the declines will 

probably be moderate due to market size.

 

<p>



















In my opinion, the key to the semiconductor industry, unlike other 

cyclicals such as oil or paper, is to view it as probably one of the best 

growth sectors for the foreseeable future. The period between these cycles 

represents a great investment opportunity if you have the courage to invest 

in the down cycles.



<p>







For example, even though semiconductor revenues fell 17 percent to 

$4.2 billion in 1975 from the previous year, revenues grew roughly 

fivefold to $21.5 billion over the following decade through 1985.  

In 1996, even with an expected 10 percent revenue decline, semiconductor 

revenues are still expected to reach $130 billion. That's a sixfold 

increase since 1985.



<p>





So given this historical perspective, where do I stand on the 

bull-market-or-head-fake question?



<p>



<a name="bundan"></a>



<table width=310 cellpadding=0>

<tr><td>

<img src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_chips.gif" width=310 height=260>

</tr></td>

</table>



<p>



<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/Marketwise/dn11_26_96b.html">
<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   




</td>














<td width=3>


</td>     
















<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->    













<td valign=top width=155>







<img border=0 height=228 width=155 





src="/Graphics/per_niles_a.gif"><br>








<p>















<!--<table width=155 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 bgcolor="#FFFFCC" 



border=0>





	





<tr>	













<td colspan=2>









<img border=0 height=16 width=155 





src="/Graphics/per_yourturn.gif">





</td>



</tr>













<tr>










<td width=72 valign="top" align="left">	









<a href="/Polling/Entry/0,1,25,2,00.html">		









<img border=0 align=left height=52 width=72 







src="/Graphics/per_poll.gif"></a>		













</td>



		













<td width=83 valign="center" align="center">











<font face="Arial" size=-1>		







<strong>



<a href="/Polling/Entry/0,1,25,2,00.html">









<p>









This 

is the Poll title.</strong></font></a><br>











<p>







</td>





</tr>	















<tr>		













<td width=72 valign="center" align="center">



		









<a href="/Quizing/Entry/1,32,2,00.html">	













<p>













<font face="Arial" size=-1>

<strong>This is the Quiz 

title.</strong>

</font>







</td>		











<td width=83 valign="top" align="right">	





<img border=0 align=left height=52 width=72 





src="/Graphics/per_quiz.gif"></a><br>  







</td>	





</tr>





</table>-->









<p>






<p>











<img border=0  height=16 width=155 

src="/Graphics/per_letters.gif">











<table border=0 bordercolor="050000" bgcolor="#ffffcc" 

width=155 

cellspacing=0 cellpadding=5>









<tr>     







<td align=left width=155>







<span class="shorttakes">







<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">





<strong><a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw11_11_96a.html">Why didn't I think 

of that?</strong></a>





<br>











This &#91;column&#93; got me 

thinking about what the next step might be. 

At first, 

I thought about copyrighting truth. But then it hit me: 



copyright falsehood. Think of the windfall I'd get every election 

season!

&nbsp;--Mark Valence, kurash@sassafras.com, 11/14/96







<br>&nbsp;<br>







Maybe we could speed up the inevitable copyright process and 

allow whole 

lists of words to be trademarked at once. Whoever has 

the most money could 

just send in Webster's Dictionary and be done 

with it. &nbsp; --Valient 

Gough, val@nilenet.com, 11/11/96







<br>&nbsp;<br>









<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw10_28_96.html"><strong>Copywrong 

1996</strong></a>





<br>











If they are going to make it that difficult to use a



computer, 

I'll just 

quietly turn it off for the last time and put it away. 





I wasn't born 

with a serial port. 



&nbsp;--Robert Caraballo, 

susano@bellsouth.net, 

11/1/96







<br>&nbsp;<br>













Fair use is a valuable freedom, and collections of information 

shouldn't 

be able to be copyrighted. 



&nbsp;--Alexander M. Covan, 

amc@bway.net, 

11/1/96











<br>&nbsp;<br>









Editors Note: We received many emails asking where to write 

concerning 





the electronic copyright issues raised in this 

column. 

Contact 





<a href="http://www.public-domain.org/">Public Domain</a>, 

the 





recently-formed citizens' group opposing these provisions.











</font>











<br>&nbsp;<br>









	



&nbsp;                  











</td>





</tr>





</table>


















