<img border="0" width="310" height="60" src="/Graphics/item_perspectives.gif"></a>


         








<!--------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->





<font face="Arial" size=+2><strong>Tech IPOs take in the dough to pay down debt</strong></font>


<br>        






<font face="Arial" size=-1>November 19, 1996</font><br>









<p>







<font face="Times">







Follow the money.

<p>











That was the advice given by <I>Washington Post</I> executive editor Ben
Bradlee
to his reporters during the Watergate scandal of the 1970s.

<p>








 Now, nearly a quarter of a century later that same bit of wisdom
holds true for the Great High-Tech IPO Boom of 1996.












<p>








Over 200 computer equipment, communications, and electronics companies have
launched IPOs this year, raising a record sum of over $11 billion.

<p>








<img align=left height=124 width=106
src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/11_96/per_ipo.gif"> 








The real question is: for what purpose?

<p>



If you guessed plant expansion, acquisitions, or job creation, then it's
back to Finance 101.

<p>







While investors may believe that their dollars were spent to
finance research and development or to expand facilities, the truth is that
$4.8 billion--just under half--of the money raised by  high-tech firms was
not spent in the pursuit of grander facilities, nor the hiring of new
talent, but rather to refinance old debts or pay off creditors.

<p>


Contrast these numbers with last year's figures when 189 computer and
communication-related firms went public and raised about $8 billion.  Only
one-quarter of that capital was targeted for debt servicing.
<p>

Semiconductor manufacturer <a href="http://www.sipex.com/">Sipex</a>,
information retrieval service provider Nova, and healthcare software
developer <a href="http://www.tsidds.com/">Transition Systems</a> were
among the notable companies that headed to the public till to refinance
their debt.</font>





<p>




<font face="Arial" size=-1>



<a href="/Perspectives/Marketwise/rp11_19_96b.html">


<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>   

</td>








<td width=3>
</td>     










<!--Multimedia & Related Links column starts here-->    









<td valign=top width=155>




<img border=0 height=228 width=155 


src="/Graphics/per_peterson_a.gif"><br>


<p>









