<tr>     


<td align=left width=155>


<span class="shorttakes">


<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">

<strong><a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw11_11_96a.html">Why didn't I think of that?</strong></a>
<br>





This &#91;column&#93; got me thinking about what the next step might be. 
At first, I thought about copyrighting truth. But then it hit me: 
copyright falsehood. Think of the windfall I'd get every election season!
&nbsp;--Mark Valence, kurash@sassafras.com, 11/14/96

<br>&nbsp;<br>

Maybe we could speed up the inevitable copyright process and allow whole 
lists of words to be trademarked at once. Whoever has the most money could 
just send in Webster's Dictionary and be done with it. &nbsp; --Valient 
Gough, val@nilenet.com, 11/11/96


<br>&nbsp;<br>








<a href="/Perspectives/mw/mw10_28_96.html"><strong>Copywrong 1996</strong></a>


<br>





If they are going to make it that difficult to use a

computer, I'll just 
quietly turn it off for the last time and put it away. 

I wasn't born 
with a serial port. 

&nbsp;--Robert Caraballo, susano@bellsouth.net, 
11/1/96

<br>&nbsp;<br>







Fair use is a valuable freedom, and collections of information shouldn't 
be able to be copyrighted. 

&nbsp;--Alexander M. Covan, amc@bway.net, 
11/1/96







<br>&nbsp;<br>







Editors Note: We received many emails asking where to write concerning 


the electronic copyright issues raised in this column. 
Contact 

<a href="http://www.public-domain.org/">Public Domain</a>, 
the 

recently-formed citizens' group opposing these provisions.




</font>



