<!-- ------------------------------MAIN CONTENT---->
<font face="Arial" size=+2>

<strong>Other views on Mac mania</strong>
</font>
<br>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>January 8, 1997</font><br>

<p>
<font face="Times">
<p>

<p>
Editor's Note: A <a
href="http://www.news.com/Perspectives/mw/mw1_2_97a.html"> recent
column</a> about the excess of some Macintosh fans generated probably
more email than Perspectives has ever received before. We couldn't print it
all, but we've selected a few responses for your edification.
<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<strong>Macintosh <i>did</i> change the world</strong>
</font><br>

The Macintosh did change the world, but certainly not in the ways that
Steve Jobs or anyone else at Apple imagined. It changed the world similar
to the way the printing press and the Industrial Revolution did, giving
individuals the ability to mass produce high-quality documents (in other
words, information) cheaply.
<p>
The Macintosh changed computing from being a
complicated, little-used instrument, to a widely needed tool
for business and communication.
<p>
<img height=163 width=141 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_press.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>
We now live in a society that could not exist, perform, or function without
computer systems. The Macintosh has influenced and changed the
face and expectation we have of computers.  And every operating system
since has been trying to model the Macintosh.
<p>
Whether it's the Mac OS, Windows 95, or Unix, operating systems are in a
process of achieving feature parity.  The amount of change that computer
operating systems will experience over the next ten years will nowhere near
match the change the Macintosh invoked on an infant industry in 1984. Those
changes permeate every facet of our computing experience today.
<p>
It was the Macintosh that introduced, invented, and/or made practical items
which we take for granted in computing today: i.e., the mouse, GUI,
WYSIWYG, multiple fonts, laser-printer output, sound, 3.5-inch floppies,
SCSI devices, cursors, drop-down menus, built-in
networking, and plug and play to name a few.
<p>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
When not slaughtering his fellow employees in marathons, <a
href="mailto:rhartung@macromedia.com">Robert Hartung</a> is responsible for
maintenance of Macintosh and Newton technologies at Macromedia's San
Francisco headquarters. The views expressed are his own and not necessarily
those of Macromedia or its employees.
</font>
<p>

<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<strong>Hard to be a Mac Fanatic</strong>
</font><br>

It's hard being a Mac fanatic these days. I know, I'm an addict, too. I
help run a newspaper that is produced on Macs, and I helped design the
system. And yes, I'm even an EvangeLista, which means I get cheerful,
upbeat emails almost every day from the irrepressible Apple Fellow Guy
Kawasaki.
<p>
But folks, let's get a life. A Mac is a wonderful thing, but it's a
computer. You use it to do things, not to worship.
<p>
<img height=71 width=127 border=0 src="/Images/Perspectives/Stories/01_97/per_sneer.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
The publication I work for ushered in the brave world of desktop publishing
just a couple of years ago. Our first try at desktop publishing was
burdened by a PC-Novell system that didn't work too well and had a nasty
habit of eating people's files, usually on deadline.
<p>
So we shopped around and found a Mac-based solution. Under an intense
deadline, we set up a couple of Macs in minutes. We loaded the system
software--the whole engine of our editorial system--in about 15 minutes.
OK, so it took me awhile for the first few Macs, to remember where to put
certain files, or which fonts to put where, but I bit the bullet. When my
colleagues came in on Monday, they got to work, and I went back to editing,
my real job.
<p>
I have the credentials to be a bonafide, genuine Mac fanatic.
Just the same, my fellow fanatics need to get a grip. And more importantly,
they need to regain their senses of humor. Sure, it's hard when evil MIS
types tell you they're going to cart your Mac away and leave a (gasp)
Windows 95 box on your desk. Just say no, but cheerfully and with panache.
<p>
Don't act like a Christian in the bowels of the Coliseum, about to go
<I>mano a mano</I> with a lion. Practice your pre-Windows 95 sneer.
Remember how
you used to make jokes about DOS? You still can, but now you can make fun
of "plug and play." (Yours works, theirs doesn't.) Remember, not everyone
appreciates caviar, fine Bordeaux, a Rolex, or a Mac. We can all live
together. (I just wish Bill Gates would keep the same thing in mind.)
<p>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
Anthony Paonita is the deputy managing editor and part-time system
administrator of The National Law Journal, based in New York. In his spare
time (every other Sunday) he plays SimCity 2000 on his Mac at home.
</font>
<p>

</font>


<P>
<font face="Arial" size=-1>
<a href="/Perspectives/Soapbox/var1_8_97b.html">

<font face="Arial" size=-1>Continued</font></a>
</td>
<td width=3>

</td>
