        <td width=5 rowspan=1>
        </td>
        



        
       <td valign=top width=305>


       <font size=+2 face="Arial", "Helvetica"><STRONG>Softbank expands empire</STRONG></font>

        <br>

        
<font size=-1 face="Arial", "Helvetica">
        By <a href="mailto:timc@cnet.com">
			Tim Clark</a><BR>

        
	
	
	
		September 18, 1996, 1:45 p.m. PT
		</font>


    <p>

    <font  face="Times">




	<img border=0  alt="Just In" src="/Graphics/justin.gif">


ATLANTA--<a href="http://www.softbank.co.jp/">Softbank Ventures</a> expects
to invest in 20 more Internet companies by year's end, Chairman
Masayoshi Son told a press conference here today.
<p>
That will make Softbank the leading investor in more than 50
companies, according to Son. 
<p> 
"We are already the leading shareholder in more than 30 companies on  the
Internet," Son added, indicating that Softbank is interested only in the top
companies in any specific market niche. "In each one of those areas," he said, "we are
investing in the number-one companies."
<p>
Softbank's best-known Internet investments include large minority stakes in
<a href="http://www.yahoo.com/">Yahoo</a>, <a
href="http://www.cybercash.com/">CyberCash</a>, and <a
href="http://www.usweb.com/">USWeb</a>, along with an investment in memory
maker <a href="http://www.kingston.com/">Kingston Technology</a> and
outright ownership of computer industry publisher <a
href="http://www.zdnet.com/">Ziff-Davis</a>. 
<p>
</font>

        </td>

<td width=5 rowspan=1>
</td>



     


